<FIRST>u i AM-Refugees-Glance 1stLd-Writethru a0658 09-11 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0658,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Glance at Developments in Mass Exodus of East Germans to West Germany</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with Die Welt reporting 10,000
East Germans crossed into the West. Picks up graf 4 pvs, `East Germany's
...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a glance of the key
developments in the mass exodus of East Germans to West Germany
through Hungary:
   _ Hungary announces Sunday it will allow thousands of vacationing
East Germans to leave for West Germany, and the exodus through
Austria begins shortly thereafter. Hungarian border guards at
Hegyeshalom, about 120 miles northwest of Budapest, are instructed
to let all East Germans through with only cursory checks.
   _ East German refugees, many crammed in private cars, begin
arriving in Passau, West Germany, early Monday after an all-night
drive. More than 2,000 arrive in West Germany by midday. The West
German newspaper Die Welt reports in its Tuesday edition that about
10,000 East Germans crossed into the West on Monday.
   _ East Germany's state news media Monday denounces Hungary's
action as ``illegal'' and charges that its Warsaw Pact ally ``under
the guise of humanitarism is engaging in organized smuggling of
humans.''
   _ West Germany's ZDF television network reports East German
leader Erich Honecker is in failing health after his gall-bladder
surgery three weeks ago. ZDF also says ``critics in the Politburo
reportedly are charging that Honecker misjudged the meaning and
scope of the wave of refugees.''
   _ West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, in a speech Monday in
Bremen, calls on his countrymen to welcome the East German refugees
and to have faith in the future of a reunified Germany.
</TEXT>
