<FIRST>r i AM-NorthernIreland     09-11 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northern Ireland,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Men Accused in Catholic Death in Belfast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two soldiers and a taxi driver
appeared in court Monday accused of killing a Roman Catholic who
allegedly was targeted after security documents were leaked to
Protestant militants.
   Both soldiers belong to the British army's locally recruited
Ulster Defense Regiment. One also was charged in the murder of a
second Catholic in June, the court heard.
   Police charged Pvt. Andrew Neville Browne, 25, with murder in the
deaths of Loughlin Maginn, 38, and barman Liam McKee, 36, shot at
his home in Lisburn south of Belfast on June 24.
   Pvt. Andrew David Smith, 29, and Edward Charles Jones, 25, a
self-employed taxi driver, were charged with murder in Maginn's
death, police told the court.
   An outlawed Protestant extremist organization, the Ulster Freedom
Fighters, claimed to have used a leaked security document to select
Maginn as their target. Gunmen broke into his home at Rathfriland,
County Down, on Aug. 25 and killed him.
   The extermists tried to back up their claim that Maginn worked
for the Irish Republican Army by producing a stolen security file,
which alleged he was a suspect.
   Maginn's family denied he was an IRA member.
   More than half the Ulster Defense Regiment's 6,500 members work
part-time, mostly in rural counties along the Irish Republic's
border, and 97 percent of them are Protestants.
   The outlawed IRA is fighting to drive the British from Northern
Ireland and unite the Protestant-dominated province with the
overwhelmingly Catholic Irish Republic.
   The three accused men appeared separately at a 9-minute hearing
in Banbridge Magistrates Court, and all were were ordered held until
a further court appearance in Belfast on Sept. 22.
   All three appeared in court in handcuffs, and all have pleaded
innocent, police told magistrates.
   The three were taken to the court in Banbridge, 19 miles
southwest of Belfast, in an armored convoy of police vehicles.
   In Belfast, a judge sentenced Damien Martin Nicell, 20, to life
in prison after he was convicted of the March 21, 1988, killing of
policeman Clive Graham in Londonderry. He was also sentenced to 92
years to be served concurrently on other charges ranging from
hijacking to arson.
   In Dublin, a statement issued by Irish Prime Minister Charles
Haughey's Cabinet said it was ``deeply concerned'' at claims about
leaks and wanted to concentrate solely on security matters during
Friday's session of the Anglo-Irish conference.
   The meetings between Irish and British officials are held under
the 1985 Anglo-Irish Agreement, giving the republic a say in
Northern Ireland's affairs.
   ``At this meeting, the government will be insisting on a full
review of these matters, and their far-reaching implications, with
particular reference to the role of the UDR (Ulster Defense
Regiment).''
</TEXT>
