<FIRST>u w AM-FBIGuns     09-11 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FBI Guns,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bureau Agents to Get 10mm Pistols</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI will soon join many police departments
in arming its agents with high-capacity semi-automatic pistols,
according an interview with the director.
   The bureau's 9,700 agents will be issued 10mm pistols that can
fire at least 12 rounds before reloading, said Director William S.
Sessions in an interview Monday with reporters and editors of The
Washington Post. Currently, agents carry six-shot revolvers.
   A report on the interview appeared in Tuesday editions.
   Many police departments have switched from revolvers to 9mm
semi-automatics to match the greater firepower being deployed by
drug gangs.
   A revolver, considered by many departments more likely to fire if
contaminated with dirt, cannot hold more than five or six rounds in
the calibers needed for police use. Semiautomatics may carry many
more rounds stacked in magazines that may extend out the bottom of
the butt of the weapons.
   The interview account quoted unidentified FBI officials as saying
Sessions ordered the switch to the new firearms about three months
ago following a review that began in 1986 when two agents were
killed in a shoot-out with drug dealers in Miami. The change should
be accomplished next year.
</TEXT>
