<FIRST>r a PM-McKinneyWill     09-11 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-McKinney Will,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Loses Bid to Share In Congressman's Estate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDD EVERHART</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WESTPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man claiming to be the late Rep.
Stewart B. McKinney's lover lost an attempt to share the
congressman's estate.
   Arnold R. Denson, an unemployed real estate agent living in
Georgia, said his lawyer is studying whether an appeal of Monday's
probate court decision would be filed.
   Probate Judge Earl F. Capuano ruled that McKinney's widow, Lucie,
is entitled to the $387,000 that her husband borrowed from her trust
fund at a Bridgeport bank. The ruling effectively wiped out the
Connecticut Republican's estate.
   Capuano also denied Denson's request that Mrs. McKinney be
removed as administrator of her husband's estate.
   Denson claims he was McKinney's lover for five years. McKinney
died of AIDS in 1987 during his ninth term. He left a 40-percent
share of his Washington home and a 1975 Chevrolet to Denson.
   McKinney's family has steadfastly denied he was a homosexual, and
his doctor said at the time of his death that he had contracted AIDS
from a blood transfusion after heart surgery in 1979.
   Denson, 34, said in August that he and McKinney lived together in
McKinney's Washington home and kept their relationship secret from
the congressman's family to protect them.
   Mrs. McKinney's lawyer, Lawrence J. Halloran, said he hopes
Capuano's ruling ends the matter.
   ``You pay your bills before you make gifts under the probate
law,'' he said. ``There just was no blood in this stone for Mr.
Denson.''
</TEXT>
