<FIRST>r i PM-TurtleReappears     09-11 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Turtle Reappears,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Missing Turtle Turns Up After 13 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JESSICA BALDWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A turtle, presumed dead for 13 years, has been
found alive and well in her compartment at a zoo in Devon, the
curator says.
   Colin Bath said Amy, an Oriental soft shell turtle who
disappeared in 1976 from Paignton Zoo, 130 miles southwest of
London, was found last week hiding in a silted pond after a gardener
spotted her stealing meat.
   ``How she survived for 12 or 13 years without food is a bit of a
mystery,'' said Bath, who described Amy as now full size with a
large, bobbing neck and a 12-inch grey, soft, pliant shell.
   Zookeepers were amazed at Amy's excellent condition especially
since the turtle's primary diet is meat and there was no meat in the
Tropical House until last week, when meat-eating birds arrived.
   They said she probably survived by stealing fruit from the bird
cages and eating the odd insect or mouse.
   Bath believes it was the lure of the meat that finally brought
Amy to their attention.
   ``She couldn't resist the diced beef, her first square meal in 13
years,'' Bath said.``So she risked the daylight raid.''
   Amy and a mate arrived at the zoo in 1973 when, Bath said, she
was probably only a couple of years old and 3 inches long.
   For the first two years the turtles lived in a grass tank where
they did not flourish.
   ``They are not the easiest creatures to keep,'' said Bath,
Paignton's curator for 25 years.
   In 1975 the Tropical House, a huge planted aviary, was opened and
the turtles were transferred to their shrub-filled compartment with
its 10-foot-square, shallow pool.
   Soon after the move the turtles, natives of Asia, disappeared.
   The fate of Amy's mate was still unclear.
</TEXT>
