<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 2345EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-TaxWar Bjt   09-11 0762</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Tax War, Bjt,0785</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Gets Upper Hand in Tax War But Harsh Methods Used</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel has gained the upper
hand in a tax war with Palestinians who refused to pay taxes as part
of their revolt against Israeli occupation.
   Israel's army-run civil administration has forced payment of
taxes in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip by demanding proof of
tax payment for almost all official documents, ranging from birth
certificates to travel permits and export licenses.
   Soldiers and tax collectors have raided homes to seize television
sets and stereos and have seized cars at checkpoints in lieu of tax
payments.
   Makram Saad, a pharmacist in Bethlehem who has endured a series
of tax raids, said Israel's policies have only strengthened his
determination.
   ``You pay taxes to a legal government that is elected and you get
services in return,'' said Saad. ``We are getting nothing. We get
closed schools, arrests. Why should we pay to have more guns to kill
my people?''
   But Israel's determination to force tax payments has worn down a
boycott launched in early 1988 as part of a civil disobedience
campaign.
   By both Palestinian and Israeli estimates, most of the 1.7
million Arabs in the occupied lands are now paying income and sales
taxes. Underground leaflets no longer insist on compliance with the
boycott.
   An Israeli military official said more Arabs were paying taxes
now than before the Palestinian uprising, or intefadeh, that began
Dec. 8, 1987, even though Arab tax collectors quit after being
threatened by PLO groups.
   Because of a sharp decline in the economy as a result of the
uprising's strikes and boycotts, however, the army has not yet
collected enough money to finance the pre-uprising annual budget of
$239 million of the Civil Administration.
   ``In real terms. we have succeeded in coming close to what we
collected before the intefadeh, but a lot now goes to repairing
damaged buildings, utility poles, etc., and little to new
development,'' said the military official, who could not be
identified in keeping with army regulations.
   Israeli sources said Yasser Arafat's PLO had funneled at least
$200 million to the occupied territories in 1988 to compensate
Palestinians for losses. But they said the figure was only about
$100 million in 1989 because donations from Arab oil states
declined, making the continued tax boycott more difficult.
   Dr. Abdel Fattah Abu Shokor, a Palestinian economist at An Najah
University in the West Bank, estimated the gross domestic prodcut of
the occupied lands fell 20 to 30 percent in the past 20 months from
about $1.5 million in 1987. The jobless rate is also about 30
percent, up from a pre-uprising level of 10 percent.
   He estimated 60 percent of Palestinians avoided paying taxes in
1988, but conceded there was less compliance with the boycott now.
   ``The Israeli measures are not easy to avoid,'' he said.
   The Israeli military official said the tax battle continues to be
a ``real war'' even though most Palestinians are now paying taxes.
   For example, on Aug. 14, an Israeli tax collector was fatally
burned and three colleagues injured in a firebomb attack on their
car in the West Bank.
   Some Palestinians say they will not pay taxes regardless of the
pressure.
   Saad, 30, whose pharmacy is near Bethlehem's Manger Square, said
a squad of soldiers raided his home last year, seizing the family's
22-inch TV set and a 1987 Peugot 104 in lieu of tax payments.
   In the past year, tax collectors also raided his store three
times to confiscate medicine and cosmetics, finally clearing all the
shelves on July 11, he said.
   Saad estimates the raids cost him about $100,000 and said he has
spent 17 days in jail for refusing court orders to pay taxes.
   The pharmacist maintains that some of the property seized
belonged to relatives, not to him. A military official, however,
said Saad and three other pharmacists, all leftist activists,
transferred their property to relatives at the same time in an
attempt to fool tax collectors.
   What infuriated him most, Saad said, was the raid on his home in
nearby Beit Sahour, where he was ordered at gunpoint to sit in the
living room while soldiers rummaged through the house looking for
valuables to take as compensation for not paying taxes.
   ``This was an attack on my home, in front of my wife and child.
It's harder to take than confiscating things in the pharmacy. It's
where you live and sleep,'' he said.
</TEXT>
