<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 2346EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AnnieAuditions     09-11 0748</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Annie Auditions,0768</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search Begins for Broadway's New Orphan Annie</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She must be between 3-foot-10 and 4-foot-4, sing
loudly and clearly, be able to act and tap dance, look 10 or 11
years old and, of course, not be afraid of dogs.
   The search for Broadway's new Annie began as 29 little girls
walked on stage at the Golden Theater to face Martin Charnin,
director of ``Annie 2: Miss Hannigan's Revenge,'' the new musical
about the world's most famous orphan.
   ``Why are we doing this mad thing?'' sighed composer Charles
Strouse as he prepared to listen to endless renditions of a little
melody he wrote called ``Tomorrow.'' ``We should be playing poker.''
   The girls on hand Monday morning were the first batch of
youngsters to audition for Charnin, Strouse, casting director Pat
McCorkle, choreographer Danny Daniels and others connected with the
$7 million musical that is to open March 1 on Broadway.
   Some girls waited for more than more than four hours before they
were let into the theater. The audition was open to anyone with
enough courage to be there.
   Nine-year-old Brandie Gray of Louisville, Ky., and her mother,
Teresa, arrived at the theater at 5:30 a.m. to stake out their place
in line.
   ``We got up at 3 a.m.,'' said Mrs. Gray, ``for the last leg of
the trip.''
   Right behind them was 9-year-old Jill McEachern of Jackson,
Miss., who with her mother, Carolyn, showed up at 6:30 a.m. Jill
confided she never had appeared in ``Annie,'' but ``I watched the
movie a lot.''
   Like most of the girls, Jill was not even born when the original
``Annie'' opened on Broadway in 1977. It ran 2,377 performances
before it closed in January 1983.
   The show's first star, Andrea McArdle, is now 25, married and the
mother of a year-old daughter. She last appeared on Broadway in
``Starlight Express'' in 1987.
   The first Annie ended with the nasty Miss Hannigan, the orphanage
matron, going off to prison. The sequel picks up the story six weeks
later, though producers aren't saying much about how Miss Hannigan
gets, or tries to get, her revenge.
   As the girls hoping to follow in Ms. McArdle's footsteps were
sent to the stage Monday, parents were relegated to the back of
theater where they whispered nervously.
   ``One of the things you want to get a sense of is how these kids
function by themselves without their parents,'' Charnin said. ``Some
of them instantly reveal that they are frightened to death and are
not trustworthy enough to be alone.''
   The girls were lined up across the stage, standing in front of a
yellow ribbon hung at 4 feet, 4 inches above the floor, some of them
towering above it.
   ``One of the things I learned from the last `Annie' was to cast
smaller,'' Charnin said. ``It didn't have to be younger, but it had
to be smaller. There's just so much of a hem of a dress you can let
out.'' Still, even the too-tall girls got a chance to show their
singing and dancing skills.
   Charnin described his role during the audition as ``Pied Piper
and psychiatrist. I get a sense of where their heads are and hear
their voices.''
   The girls first sang the ubiquitous ``Tomorrow'' in groups of
five. Charnin then asked each her name and age, and they got a
chance to do a couple of simple dance steps, again in groups of five.
   The moment of truth came when Charnin had the girls solo on four
bars each of ``Tomorrow.''
   ``This is the hard part,'' he told the girls. ``This is where we
have to pretend that this is not `Annie' but `A Chorus Line.''' The
girls who didn't make the cut got a thank-you and an ``Annie 2''
button.
   By midday, four youngsters had made it through the first hurdle
and got invited to come for a second look. Neither Jill nor Brandie
made the first cut.
   Charnin and company continued to look at hopefuls through the day
Monday and planned to repeat the audition process today and
Wednesday in New York and next Monday in Washington.
   ``By the end of all of this, I hope to have 25 kids who will then
take specific material that we will want them to look at, and come
back for a concerted audition,'' he said. ``From that group, our
Annie will be picked.''
</TEXT>
