<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 2347EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Warhol     09-11 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Warhol,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warhol Time in London</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andy Warhol is making waves in London, 2{ years
after his death. Posters with his magic name are everywhere.
   Six exhibitions devoted to the American master of pop art opened
this month. Also taking place were a retrospective of his
avant-garde films and a two-day conference on his film-making at the
National Film Theater, a six-week series of lectures at the Chelsea
School of Art and Design and, next month, a dance at Sadler's Wells
inspired by his helium-filled floating silver pillows.
   ``I cannot remember such a concentration on a single artist
before, and it reflects Warhol's stature as one of the great artists
since the Second World War,'' said Andrew Dempsey, assistant
director of the Hayward Gallery, which is staging Britain's first
comprehensive retrospective Warhol exhibition.
   The Hayward is the big draw: 183 works assembled by the Museum of
Modern Art in New York.
   Visitors streamed in as soon as the doors opened on Thursday,
even at $6.65 _ nearly as expensive as a modest theater seat in the
West End.
   The show runs through Nov. 5 and then goes to Cologne, West
Germany; Venice, Italy, and Paris.
   The Hayward works include the celebrated images of Chairman Mao,
Marilyn Monroe, Jacqueline Kennedy, Elvis Presley and Elizabeth
Taylor. There are the Campbell soup cans, the repetitive dollar
bills and the 210 Coca-Cola bottles that are all slightly different.
   There are the early paintings derived from comics, and chilling
images of the electric chair and auto and aircraft crashes.
   Other galleries are showing Warhol's drawings as a successful
commercial artist in the 1950s, the self-portraits which occupied
him from the start of his career to the last year of his life, an
exploration of his attitude toward sex, the years at the Factory
where he and his acolytes worked in New York and, at Liberty's
department store, a window display he designed for Bonwit Teller's
New York store in 1961.
   ``These six shows reflect Warhol's importance,'' said Dempsey.
   ``He made an extremely interesting contribution, not just as an
artist but as a creator and reflector of his period _ the 1960s to
the 1980s. It was not an accident _ he was quintessentially an
artist of his time.''
   Dempsey described Warhol as an extremely radical artist who could
also reach a wide public.
   ``Artists like that are rare. Clearly, he had the magic, and was
extraordinarily interesting and innovative,'' he said.
   Warhol was born in Pittsburgh on Aug. 6, 1928, of Czechoslovak
immigrant parents who had settled in the United States seven years
earlier.
   When he died, world-famous on Feb. 22, 1987, after a gall bladder
operation, he had been so successful in obscuring details of his
life that obituaries could not agree on the year of his birth, the
Hayward show notes.
   Although the Times of London reporting on Warhol this month spoke
of the ``genius of the ultimate salesman,'' the artist does not get
a unanimous chorus of acclamation.
   Peter Fuller, one of Britain's top critics and editor of the
country's most popular art journal, Modern Painters, called Warhol
``trivial, empty, banal and vacuous and therefore not worth
attending to.''
</TEXT>
