<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 2352EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Bogota-Life     09-11 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bogota-Life,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daily Life in Bogota: Traffic Jams, Armed Soldiers and Pickpockets</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO A. WINDHAUSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caravans of security vehicles tear
through the streets, machine guns poke out the windows and troops
whistle to keep other cars and pedestrians away from the whirlwind.
   A limousine passes, and life in Bogota's Santander Park returns
to what passes as normal during an unprecedented war between the
government and Colombia's drug chieftans.
   ``Don't you think this is a lot of noise for nothing?'' asks
Maria, who sells sweets at a candy stand.
   ``People abroad think we're running around shooting each other,''
laments a salesman at a photo shop.
   Several people in the park, who ask only that their first name be
used, complain more of the damage the nearly monthlong showdown has
done to tourism rather than to its victims.
   ``This terrorism stuff is hurting my business,'' said Alvaro, a
man in a red cap, as he shined shoes. ``It's keeping tourists away.
But then, even petty thievery is down.
   ``Around here, you have to look ahead, because if you look behind
you, it's frightening,'' he said, laughing.
   Other Bogota residents try to joke or shrug their way through the
wave of bombings, shootings, arson and other drug-linked violence
terrorizing this South American republic.
   In middle and upper class neighborhoods, many parents keep their
children out of school, and restaurants report business is down by
40 percent.
   Most violence is in Medellin, 150 miles northwest of the capital,
where bombs have gone off in restaurants, factories and shops.
   But despite the headlines, life in this bustling city hasn't much
changed _ except for the police motorcades and the resulting traffic
jams.
   In a seedy section of town, prostitutes as young as 12 sell their
bodies for as little as 50 cents.
   Pickpockets and the ever-present ``gamines'' _ as the street
children are called _ still prey on unsuspecting pedestrians and, of
course, tourists in this city of 6 million.
   The few visitors at traditional tourist attractions arrive in
charter buses. They hurriedly enter and exit, back to the safety of
the bus.
   In the Gold Museum, where a wealth of pre-Colombian artifacts
lure thousands of visitors every year, business is down 30 percent,
said a ticket seller who didn't want his first name known ``for
security reasons.''
   Employes from other museums agree.
   Santander Park is filled with its usual characters: the old
snake-handler doing tricks with his defanged pet, the ``scar man''
who rolls on a bed of glass, the native Indians selling blankets and
ponchos.
   Dressed in a white guayabera tropical shirt, a fortune teller
sitting on a chair brags he can tell the future and starts to spark
the interest of onlookers when, suddenly, the circle around him
breaks up. He is removed, hands pinned behind his back, to a remote
corner of the park.
   He's accused of stealing a policeman's wallet.
   ``This is part of everyday life,'' Alvaro said.
   In the northern residential sector, site of yuppies, BMW's and
discos, the good life appears to go on, with many outdoor cafes and
restaurants brimming with well-dressed young customers.
   Entrance is only restricted at government buildings, where
soldiers search visitors and packages, apologizing for the
incovenience.
   ``Sir,'' said one young soldier, ``here in Colombia, we all want
this to end.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
