<SECOND>PM-Box Office,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Uncle Buck' Still No. 1; `Kickboxer' Opens Strongly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Uncle Buck'' was the No. 1 moneymaker in the
nation's theaters for the fourth consecutive weekend. The
independently distributed ``Kickboxer'' made a strong debut in third
place.
   Universal's ``Uncle Buck,'' which stars John Candy as an
obnoxious relative brought in to supervise his two nieces and a
nephew, grossed $4.6 million, according to figures released Monday
by Exhibitor Relations Co.
   Director Ron Howard's ``Parenthood,'' the family comedy with
Steve Martin, Jason Robards, Mary Steenburgen and Rick Moranis,
finished in second with sales of $4.4 million.
   The martial-arts film ``Kickboxer,'' starring Jean-Claude Van
Damme and distributed by Cannon, finished a surprising third on
revenues of $4.1 million. It was followed by the romantic comedy
``When Harry Met Sally...,'' which collected $3.1 million.
   Falling into fifth place and losing momentum with $2.9 million
was the underwater adventure epic ``The Abyss.'' After five weeks of
release, ``The Abyss'' has now netted $44.6 million and has yet to
recoup its production costs.
   ``Lethal Weapon 2,'' reuniting Mel Gibson and Danny Glover as
unconventional police officers, came in sixth with $2.6 million.
   In seventh was the acclaimed character study ``sex, lies and
videotape,'' which earned $2.14 million last weekend.
   Rounding out the top 10 were ``Turner &amp; Hooch,'' in eighth with
$2.12 million, ``Batman'' in ninth with $1.9 million, and
``Relentless' in 10th on $1.4 million.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
   1. ``Uncle Buck,'' Universal, $4.6 million, 1,824 screens, $2,495
per screen, $40.5 million, four weeks.
   2. ``Parenthood,'' Universal, $4.4 million, 1,388 screens, $3,175
per screen, $69.6 million, six weeks.
   3. ``Kickboxer,'' Cannon, $4.1 million, 973 screens, $4,249 per
screen, $4.1 million, one week.
   4. ``When Harry Met Sally...,'' Columbia, $3.1 million, 1,171
screens, $2,658 per screen, $71.6 million, nine weeks.
   5. ``The Abyss,'' 20th Century Fox, $2.9 million, 1,498 screens,
$1,913 per screen, $44.6 million, five weeks.
   6. ``Lethal Weapon 2,'' Warner Bros., $2.6 million, 1,538
screens, $1,688 per screen, $134.8 million, 10 weeks.
   7. ``sex, lies and videotape,'' Miramax, $2.14 million, 363
screens, $5,882 per screen, $10.7 million, six weeks.
   8. ``Turner &amp; Hooch,'' Disney, $2.12 million, 1,494 screens,
$1,422 per screen, $59.8 million, seven weeks.
   9. ``Batman,'' Warner Bros., $1.9 million, 1,284 screens, $1,470
per screen, $241.1 million, 12 weeks.
   10. ``Relentless,'' New Line, $1.4 million, 836 screens, $1,630
per screen, $5.1 million, two weeks.
