<FIRST>r a AM-EthiopianTalks     09-11 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethiopian Talks,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethiopian-Eritrean Talks Continue for Fourth Day in Atlanta</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Preliminary peace talks between the Eritrean
People's Liberation Front and Ethiopian officials on Monday neared
the end of their fourth day at the Carter Center.
   Center spokeswoman Carrie Harmon said the delegations met
separately Monday morning before reconvening in the afternoon for
further talks at the center. She said the two sides would resume
discussions again Tuesday.
   On Sunday, the chief of the Eritrean People's Liberation Front
said he was optimistic that the discussions in Atlanta would end
soon, but he said there were were still several points prolonging
the talks.
   Isaias Afwerki said that although Eritreans ``have reason to
believe they are getting close to a solution,'' another round of
negotiations for the end of the 28-year war in the Horn of Africa is
unlikely for several months.
   ``If we agree and finish these preliminary negotiations, we will
want to go back to Eritrea and do our homework for the next phase of
the process,'' Afwerki said Sunday. ``There should be enough time
for everyone to prepare their positions.''
   With former President Jimmy Carter acting as a neutral observer,
the visiting Ethiopian and Eritrean delegations are trying to map a
plan for future peace talks.
   In the war over the independence of Eritrea, an estimated 1
million people have died in combat or in the famine that has
resulted from blocked delivery of relief supplies.
</TEXT>
