<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--DrugPooch     09-11 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Drug Pooch,0155</SECOND>
<HEAD>Berkeley to use Gentle Spaniel to Sniff out Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials have located a politically
correct dog to sniff out drugs: a gentle spaniel.
   Last May, City Council reversed a long-standing policy against
using dogs to fight crime. But the council refused to allow dogs
such as German sheherds, which stirred memories of attacks on
civil-rights workers in the South.
   The city had trouble finding a small dog until its search made
news last month and offers began pouring in.
   The sweet-tempered spaniel will be flown in from Southern
California on Tuesday and will attend the City Council meeting that
night, city spokeswoman Peggy Sullivan said.
   The spaniel's specific breed will be a secret until then, she
said.
   Berkeley officials are pleased about finding the drug-sniffing
spaniel, Sullivan said, because it ``maintains the city's commitment
to a humanitarian approach'' in the drug war.
</TEXT>
