<FIRST>r i PM-Rushdie     09-11 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rushdie,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rushdie Sees U.S. As Land `Hungry for Gods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salman Rushdie, the author who was driven into
hiding by a death threat from Moslem extremists, describes the
United States in a newly published book review as a ``secular nation
hungry for gods.''
   Rushdie, in the latest of his occasional reviews for The Observer
weekly since he was forced out of sight in February, on Sunday
praised the new novel ``Billy Bathgate'' by American author E.L.
Doctorow.
   The story of the rise and fall of gangster Dutch Shultz is told
by the young narrator Billy Bathgate, an apprentice.
   ``A secular nation hungry for gods, America made of men like the
Dutchman, dark deities in whom it desparately wanted to believe, as
15-year-old Billy ... wants to believe in Shultz,'' he wrote.
   ``But what America loves most, needs most, more than light or
darkness, more than gods or demons, is the myth of itself.
   ``Mythical America, its writers tell us constantly, is the real
America, and myth demands, among other things, that heroes fall as
well as rise. Billy Bathgate is the story of the Dutchman's long,
last dive,'' said the review.
   Rushdie called the novel Doctorow's ``most brilliant proof'' to
date of the fact that American novelists have always been more ready
than their European counterparts to demonstrate that the art of
literature can adopt the form of popular entertainment without
losing an iota of seriousness.''
   Rushdie's own novel, ``The Satanic Verses,'' drew him a ``death
sentence'' from the late Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini of Iran for
alleged blasphemy of Islam.
   Rushdie was forced into hiding with a $5.2 million bounty on his
head and given police protection. His American wife, Marianne
Wiggins, who is also a writer, said last month that they had
separated because of the strain.
</TEXT>
