<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Malek     09-11 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Malek,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Adviser Makes Peace With Jewish Groups; In Line for New Bush Job</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish leaders are backing Frederick V. Malek
for a White House role after hearing the business executive's
apology for an incident in the Nixon administration with
anti-Semitic overtones.
   The White House said Sunday that President Bush wants Malek to
run next year's economic summit of Western industrialized nations,
expected to be held in Texas.
   Malek, 51, a central player in three major business deals this
year, including the nearly $4 billion takeover of Northwest
Airlines, said he still must make arrangements with his partners
before taking on the part-time White House post.
   But Malek has cleared one possible hurdle in a series of private,
fence-mending meetings with leaders of major Jewish organizations.
   Malek said he both explained and apologized for his role in the
1971 incident in which he complied with a Richard Nixon request to
find out how many top Bureau of Labor Statistics officials were Jews.
   Malek resigned as a top Bush campaign adviser and deputy
Republican chairman last Sept. 11 after reports about the memo
resurfaced.
   He denied charges of anti-Semitism, but said then he was
relinquishing his posts ``because of my belief that nothing should
interfere with the vice president's victory in November.''
   Seymour D. Reich, chairman of the Conference of Presidents of
Major American Jewish Organizations, said Malek ``made a mistake 18
years ago when he agreed to a regrettable request by President
Nixon.''
   But Reich added that Malek ``has taken pains to assure the Jewish
community that he realizes his error and that he intended no harm. I
believe he is sincere ... and that he intends to serve the president
and the country with integrity and with respect for all Americans.
We wish him good luck in his new assignment.''
   ``He did make one mistake and he's apologized for it,'' said
Abraham H. Foxman, national director of the Anti-Defamation League
of B'nai B'rith. ``I think he's put it behind him.''
   White House spokesman Roman Popadiuk said: ``The president has
spoken to Fred Malek about (the summit post). The president would
like him to do it. No final decisions have been made. We do expect
it to occur.''
   Malek, 51, who ran last year's Republican convention in New
Orleans, said he wrote the memo only after ignoring several earlier
demands from Nixon for the information.
   Nixon had complained to aides that a ``Jewish cabal'' within the
bureau was trying to undermine his economic policies, and demanded
to know how many top officials were Democrats and Jews.
   Malek said he provided the data on Democrats after a check of
voter registration rolls, but balked at fulfilling the rest of
Nixon's query.
   ``I refused four times,'' Malek said Sunday. ``The fifth time he
came back and gave me a direct order through (chief of staff H.R.)
Haldeman, so I gave him a number.''
   ``I regret my compliance. It was a mistake,'' said Malek, a West
Point graduate who was a special assistant to Nixon in 1970-73 and
then deputy director of the Office of Management and Budget until
1975.
   ``I don't think anyone has ever found any shred of evidence of
bigotry or anti-semitism in my life, except this footnote,'' Malek
said in a telephone interview from his McLean, Va., home.
   Before accepting Bush's offer, Malek said he first must make sure
his other business obligations allow him to take on the job of
summit coordinator and that there are no conflicts of interest.
   Malek is a former Marriott Corp. executive and president of
Marriott Hotels.
   In addition to the Northwest Airlines takeover, he was a
principal in two other recent major business deals: the purchase of
Coldwell Banker's commercial real estate operations from Sears for
$300 million and the $800 million sale of Marriott's airline
catering business to Malek and executives of the catering division.
   Bush attended a party at Malek's home overlooking the Potomac
last month to mark the first anniversary of the GOP convention.
   The last summit was in Paris in July. Bush is believed intent on
holding the next in Texas _ probably San Antonio or Houston _ in
late spring. Neither the date nor site is firmly set.
</TEXT>
