<FIRST>r w PM-US-Hostages     09-11 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Hostages,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Evacuation of US Embassy in Beirut Won't Affect Intelligence, Experts
Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The evacuation of the U.S. Embassy in Lebanon
will have little effect on Washington's ability to gather
information about American hostages because the diplomats had been
isolated for months, experts say.
   Since civil war erupted full-force in Lebanon in early March,
diplomats at the embassy in Christian-controlled East Beirut were in
contact with Moslem-controlled West Beirut only by telephone, said
George Malleck, a State Department spokesman.
   The eight American captives in Lebanon are believed to be held by
pro-Iranian Shiite Moslems, all linked to the Hezbollah umbrella
group.
   Another State Department official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the diplomats were ``limited in their movements'' in
Lebanon, confined primarily to the embassy compound and their
apartments.
   Neil Livingstone, a private consultant who has written
extensively about the hostages, said it was doubtful embassy
personnel had much to do with the hostage situation. ``The options
and decisions to be made are done in Washington. They are done at a
high level,'' he said.
   Any indirect contacts with hostage-holders or their Iranian
sponsors usually take place in European capitals, he said.
   Ambassador John McCarthy and 29 American diplomats were evacuated
by helicopter Tuesday.
   On Friday, McCarthy met with Secretary of State James A Baker III
to discuss the situation in Lebanon where heightened hostilities
have claimed the lives of 827 people over the last six months. U.S.
diplomats fled, first shredding documents and destroying electronic
coding equipment, after Christian factions besieged the embassy,
claiming that the Americans had not done enough to protect from the
Syrian army and its Moslem allies.
   Thomas Cicippio of Norristown, Pa., the brother of hostage Joseph
Cicippio, said the family had heard nothing about the captives, but
they were worried. ``We just have to keep our fingers crossed,'' he
said.
   Joseph Cicippio's wife, a Lebanese-born woman employed at the
embassy, continued to work with other foreign nationals who stayed
to run the embassy compound, officials said. Thomas Cicippio said he
had not been in touch with his sister-in-law because of the
difficulty in making telephone calls. Regular mail service also is
sporadic.
   The American aid program, most of it consisting of food and other
supplies, is in the hands of local private voluntary organizations.
The program totalled about $16 million in the fiscal year that ends
this month.
   Cicippio, 58, was threatened with death, but granted a reprieve
in early August, shortly after a group calling itself the
Organization of the Oppressed on Earth released a videotape showing
Lt. Col. William R. Higgins in a noose. American officials confirmed
the picture showed Higgins, but his corpse has not been returned.
   Livingstone said the hostages are moved around among various safe
houses, probably no more than a dozen, operated by the captors. At
different times, the hostages reportedly have been held in the
southern suburbs of Beirut and in the Bekaa Valley, northeast of
Beirut.
   President Bush focused on the hostage issue in early August after
the death of Higgins, prompting a flurry of optimism about their
possible release. When none were released, the Bush administration
took another tack, announced that it would lower the decibel on
discussions about the hostages.
   ``We would like to lower our voices a little and let these issues
play out for a few days and see what happens,'' Bush spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater said on Aug. 11.
   In an interview published Tuesday in The Washington Post, Sheik
Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah, the spiritual leader of the Shiite
Moslems in Lebanon, said Bush would have to make the first gesture
of good will toward Iran.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
