<DOCNO> AP890911-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 0140EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AmbassadorFlap     09-11 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ambassador Flap,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Debate Heats Up Over Political Ambassadorial Appointees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Among State Department officials, there is no
shortage of anecdotes about the moral and intellectual shortcomings
of political activists who won prestige assignments as ambassadors.
   Some of the more noteworthy tales:
   _One recent ambassador to a European country had his bedroom
covered with mirrors. He often frolicked there with call girls
imported from a neighboring capital.
   _When Maureen Reagan, the former president's daughter, showed up
in an African country a few years ago, the local U.S. ambassador
received her at the airport in an advanced state of drunkenness.
   _An ambassador to an Asian country a decade ago was so ignorant
about world affairs he was unaware that there were two Koreas and
had never heard of the heads of government of either France or West
Germany.
   The debate over political appointees versus those chosen from the
career diplomatic service heats up each time a new administration
takes office, and President Bush's accession is no different.
   The union of career diplomats is so upset with some of Bush's
nominees that it is accusing the State Department in a lawsuit of
covering up background information about some of the choices in
order to avoid embarrassing disclosures.
   The State Department declines comment on the suit but cites a
1970 ambassadorial appointment by President Nixon to defend the
practice of going outside the foreign service for some key
diplomatic posts.
   The assignment was U.N. ambassador and the appointee was a
defeated Senate candidate named George Bush.
   The career service has never argued against political appointees.
Indeed, the list of such ambassadors is long and distinguished. Mike
Mansfield, who recently completed a 12-year tour as ambassador to
Japan, is but one example. Otto Reich, who left Venezuela in July
after a three-year stay, initially encountered official hostility in
Caracas because he was thought to be a right-wing extremist. When he
left, he took with him Venezuela's highest decoration.
   Also, political appointees sometimes have the ear of their
president, an asset few career diplomats can claim. They are
sometimes more reliable in carrying out the president's policy than
their more cautious colleagues in the foreign service.
   Tony Motley, who as President Reagan's top aide for Latin America
policy had almost 30 ambassadors under his scrutiny, said the best
of them were equally divided between career and political appointees.
   At issue now, however, are the credentials of a handful of Bush's
selections, usually Republican activists who helped Bush in the 1988
campaign but who are untutored in diplomatic matters.
   Examples are Joseph Zappala, a Florida developer who was
nominated ambassador to Spain after contributing a reported $126,000
to the campaign.
   Another Florida businessman who made a similarly generous
contribution was Melvin Sembler, nominated to be Bush's man in
Australia.
   Della Newman won an appointment as ambassador to New Zealand
after helping Bush carry Washington state. Peter Secchia, who helped
deliver Michigan to Bush, was rewarded with the embassy in Rome.
   He quickly alienated many Italians by suggesting that the Italian
Navy now boasts glass bottom boats ``so they can see the old Italian
Navy.''
   Confidence in the process was not enhanced with the answers given
by Sembler and Zappala when they were asked to write their special
qualifications to be ambassadors.
   Sembler wrote: ``I have been known as a coalition builder, able
to organize my peers to action in support of worthy civic,
charitable and political causes.'' Zappala's response was almost
identical.
   It was episodes such as this that prompted Sen. Paul Sarbanes,
D-Md., to dismiss the system as ``insulting.'' And in going to court
over the issue, the career diplomats' union, known formally as the
American Foreign Service Association, believes the law is on its
side.
   A 1980 law says ambassadorial nominees should be knowledgeable
about all aspects of the country of their assignment and that
political campaign contributions ``should not be a factor'' in the
selection process.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890911-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 0143EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     09-11 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PATTERSON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who would be king of a
northwestern Ohio community is not going to get the chance.
   Tom Wigle was the only person in the community of 200 to file for
November's election for the Village Council's six seats.
   Wigle says he could have declared himself council president,
become mayor by default _ and perhaps made himself king, since there
would be no one to disagree with him.
   ``They're starting to call me the king. I'm getting a hell of a
kick out of that,'' he said.
   But publicity about the possibility prompted Ida Lawrence to file
for election, and Mayor Pat McKee said she would run as a write-in
candidate.
   Wigle, 63, who has lived here for 30 years, said no one else
wanted to run because they were too afraid of offending someone they
knew.
   ``Everybody who lives here is damn near related,'' Wigle said.
``You can't get nothing done because nobody wants to make their
relation mad. Since you can't get nothing done, there's no use
running.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOYES, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Montana's livestock may be getting tired of
statehood centennial celebrations.
   A week ago, nearly a thousand sheep were paraded down the
6-block-long main street of Reedpoint to the cheers of 12,000 sheep
partisans. Since then, about 2,700 cows have been herded by 2,400
drovers during a week-long cattle drive from Roundup to Billings.
   Now it's the pigs' turn. The Great Montana Centennial Swine Drive
is set for Oct. 1 in this southeastern Montana community, where two
families live, according to Kerry Gardner, an organizer of the
event. The drive is a fund-raiser for repairs to the community hall,
damaged in a June hail storm. Cattle and sheep already had been
taken and there's no glamour in chickens, so pigs won out, Gardner
said.
   Promotional fliers say there could be 5,000 porkers on the drive,
but sponsors admit they would prefer a lot fewer. For people who
don't own their own, pigs will be available for rent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romance gave way to reality, but love found a way
for 773 couples to celebrate 50 years of wedded bliss with Cardinal
Joseph Bernardin at Holy Name Cathedral.
   ``Sometimes you feel like it isn't worth it, sure,'' said Samuel
Smith, who will be married for 50 years in November. ``But you say
you're together for better or worse and deal with it.''
   The theme was the more the merrier, as about 2,000 children,
grandchildren and great-grandchildren were packed into the nearby
Cathedral School auditorium to watch the Mass Sunday on
closed-circuit television.
   The main focus of the Mass was to balance some of the negative
press about marriage and divorce, said Marsha Ross, a volunteer for
Marriage Encounters for Family Ministries.
   ``This balances that with a real vision of the commitment that
you see 773 times 50 years represents,'' Ms. Ross said. ``I mean its
a very powerful witness to ... well, marriage.''
   Catherine and Joseph Bergthold were married Sept. 9, 1949, and
now have 10 children, 25 grandchildren and seven
great-grandchildren. They say the secret to a successful marriage is
to concentrate on family, togetherness and working together to solve
problems.
   ``It certainly keeps you together,'' Catherine Bergthold said.
``The key is to get mad and get over it.''
</TEXT>
