<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to fix category code.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Suspended Priest Urges Boycott of Newspaper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident Roman Catholic priest Rev. George A.
Stallings Jr. is calling on parishioners at his unsanctioned church
to boycott The Washington Post and its advertisers in retaliation
for articles about Stallings' alleged homosexual relationship with
an altar boy.
   News cameras and some reporters were barred from Sunday's service
of Stallings' Imani Temple in suburban Washington. The church later
released a videotape of parts of the service.
   ``Let me tell you something, Washington Post, we're going to hit
you where it hurts,'' Stallings shouted. ``We're going to start with
your advertisers one by one by one ... You're messing with the wrong
man.''
   Stallings also urged more than 1,000 churchgoers to cancel their
subscriptions, the Post reported today.
   A week ago the newspaper reported that a man, now 28, said he
repeatedly had sex with Stallings in a Washington church rectory in
1977 when the man was a 16-year-old altar boy.
   At Sunday's service, the Post said Stallings said he would not
respond to any allegation. ``I will not dignify it with a response.
As African Americans, we refuse to allow you to set our agenda.''
   In response, Washington Post Managing Editor Leonard Downie Jr.
said Sunday, ``We believe we have treated the Rev. Stallings
fairly.'' Downie added that the Post and other news media ``have
repeatedly sought ... to give him the opportunity to explain his
actions fully.''
   Stallings was suspended from performing sacraments by Washington
Cardinal James A. Hickey shortly after Stallings formed the Imani
Temple in July. Stallings contended the Catholic church did not
serve the needs of black parishioners.
</TEXT>
