<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru a0418 09-11 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0418,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Stock Prices Move Slightly Higher in Early Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with closing Nikkei, dollar. Pickup
4th graf `The index...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed higher against the Japanese yen
Monday, while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange ended
marginally lower after regaining most of its morning losses.
   The dollar closed at 147.77 yen, up 1.15 yen from Friday's
146.62-yen finish. The currency began trading at 147.75 yen and
ranged between 147.50 yen and 148.03 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues regained most of
its earlier losses and ended down 2.15 points, or 0.006 percent,
closing the day's trading at 34,113.66. It lost 36.75 points Friday.
   ``The index fell largely due to the yen's recent weakness against
the dollar,'' said Tsuneo Ishii, a Nomura Securities stock analyst.
   The dollar's opening Monday was its highest since a 150.30-yen
opening June 15.
   Except for some winners including steels and construction issues,
prices generally fell as participants were discouraged by the yen's
depreciation, he said.
   Dealers said the yen's decline made market players also worry
about possible hikes in domestic interest rates, while a series of
reports on the U.S. economic performance, including trade figures
for July and the retail price index for August, are due out toward
the end of this week.
   Following a similar uptrend in New York since Friday the U.S.
currency remained strong despite the Bank of Japan's dollar-selling
market intervention to stop the dollar's further rise, said a Bank
of Tokyo trader.
   He said the Bank of Japan intervened at around 147.70 yen ``in an
attempt to prevent the dollar from surpassing the 148-yen level.''
   The amount of the currency sold by the central bank was unknown.
The central bank does not comment on its monetary activities.
   ``The dollar's strength will probably last at least until it
reaches as high as 148.50 yen,'' he said. But the currency moved
little Monday as market players were almost evenly divided into
those buying at the 147.50-yen level and those selling for
profit-taking just below the 148-yen level, the trader said.
</TEXT>
