<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 4thLd-Writethru a0747 09-11 0805</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0747,0829</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven Palestinians Killed In Clashes In Occupied Territories</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with army saying troops killed
youth in Arab village. Picks up 6th pvs, `At least ...' ^By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least seven Palestinians were killed in the
occupied territories on Sunday, six by Israelis and one by a fellow
Arab as a suspected collaborator with authorities, the army and Arab
reports said.
   Twenty-nine Palestinians were reported wounded _ including an
18-month-old _ by soldiers dispersing stone throwers, hospital
officials said.
   Late Sunday, troops raiding the West Bank village of Kafr Quddum
six miles west of Nablus shot and killed a Palestinian youth and
arrested two Arabs, an army spokesman said.
   The spokesman said troops entered the village to make arrests and
opened fire after they were attacked by youths with metal bars and
stones.
   Arab hospital officials identified the Arab as Sahed Shetawi, 20.
   Arab reports said the raid was carried out by about 10 settlers.
They said the settlers, who usually carry army issued automatic
weapons for self-protection, entered the village in a Volkswagon
minibus and apparently opened fire when they were hit with stones.
   At least four other villagers were treated for gunshot wounds,
hospital officials said.
   At least 566 Palestinians have been killed by Israelis in the
22-month-old uprising against Israeli rule. Thirty-nine Israelis
also have been killed.
   Another 112 Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs during
the uprising as accused collaborators, prostitutes or drug dealers.
   Three prominent Palestinians will travel to Egypt this week to
urge the PLO to allow Arabs from the occupied territories to hold
peace talks with Israel, newspapers reported. Palestine Liberation
Organization chief Yasser Arafat will be in Cairo, Egypt's Middle
East News Agency reported.
   The daily Haaretz said Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak will
propose a Palestinian delegation of 12 people from the occupied
territories, including two deported by Israel.
   The proposal apparently gets around a PLO refusal to have
Palestinians represented only by negotiators from the occupied
territories, since the deported men could be seen as representing
Palestinians abroad.
   The Yediot Ahronot independent daily quoted Energy Minister Moshe
Shahal as saying Israel most likely would agree to meet such a
delegation about an Israeli plan to hold elections in the occupied
lands.
   In the occupied West Bank, three Palestinians were killed in
clashes with soldiers including a 19-year-old youth who was shot
trying to throw a firebomb at troops in Nablus, the army said.
   Sunday's unrest in Nablus, the occupied West Bank's largest city,
broke out after soldiers lifted a weeklong curfew that confined the
city's 120,000 residents to their homes.
   After the shooting, seven people were wounded by army gunfire as
rioting spread through Nablus and two nearby refugee camps, the army
said.
   Amid the shooting, an 18-month-old baby was reportedly shot in
the eye with a rubber bullet and seriously wounded, hospital
officials said. The army said it was investigating the report.
   In the Gaza Strip, soldiers clashed with Arabs near the El Farouk
Mosque in Rafiah, killing 20-year-old Attala el Mashrahe, the army
said.
   In a separate incident, Mohammed Salim Sharab, 17, was fatally
shot in the chest by an armed guard of a civilian fuel truck in Khan
Yunis, the army said.
   ``The guard opened fire after youths hurled stones and metal bars
at the truck and the matter has been handed over to the police,'' an
army spokesman said.
   Overnight, a lone Palestinian assailant reportedly stabbed to
death Abdullkah Hajeh, 27, near his home in Tal village outside
Nablus, hours after his house was hit with a firebomb.
   Hajeh had been accused of collaborating with the Israeli
authorities in helping to raze olive groves and recruiting
Palestinians for Israeli intellience, sources in Nablus said.
   The army confirmed the death but said the motive for the slaying
was criminal, not alleged collaboration.
   In Jerusalem, police said a Palestinian suspected of stabbing an
Israeli bus driver in an attempt to drive a passenger bus over a
cliff had slain a Jewish man three days earlier in Tel Aviv.
   The suspect, whose name is being withheld, led police to a
building site where the body of a 38-year-old Jewish man was found,
spokesman Uzi Sandori said. He told police he killed the man out of
``nationalist motives,'' Sandori said.
   The attempt to commandeer the bus Saturday night occurred as the
Jerusalem-bound vehicle was seven miles from Tel Aviv. On July 6, a
Palestinian forced a bus off a cliff, killing 16 Jews, including an
American tourist.
   On Saturday, a disaster was averted when several elderly
passengers grabbed and beat the assailant, witnesses said.
   The driver, Shlomo Assor, 40, was stabbed twice in the abdomen
and once in the arm, but managed to stop the bus safely.
</TEXT>
