<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 0335EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MorroCastle     09-11 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Morro Castle,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivors of Fatal Ship Fire Unite As Controversy Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAUL REYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It has been 55 years since a mysterious fire
aboard the luxury liner Morro Castle killed more than 130 people as
thousands watched in horror from the New Jersey shore.
   But the years have not erased the controversy over what really
happened in the blaze on Sept. 8, 1934.
   Six survivors met Saturday at the Maritime Museum to commemorate
the disaster and recall the sordid tale of arson, a dead sea
captain, gunrunning to Cuba, international intrigue and a
recalcitrant federal government unwilling to divulge all it knows
about the disaster.
   Ruth Coleman recalls the tragedy as a ``horrible thing.''
   ``It was a nightmare. I couldn't believe that this was happening.
It was something you read about; that happens to other people,''
says Mrs. Coleman, who was 23 at the time.
   Hours before the fire, Capt. Robert Wilmott was found slumped
across his bathtub. Flames broke out about 2:45 a.m., but it was 30
minutes after people on shore spotted the burning ship that the
acting captain, William Warms, ordered an SOS message be sent.
Already, people were jumping off the flaming decks.
   By sunrise, thousands along the coast saw the ship cast an eerie
glow as it drifted toward Asbury Park.
   While the tragedy led to an overhaul of maritime safety
guidelines, many believe the truth of what happened aboard the ship
has never been told.
   Thomas Torresson was an 18-year-old assistant purser on the ship.
He says news accounts through the years have been slanted against
the crew and the ship's owners.
   ``Thousands and thousands of words have been written that are not
true,'' Torresson said.
   The acting captain, he says, did the best he could under very
trying circumstances.
   The only safety violation that Torresson concedes is that the
captain did not conduct lifeboat drills.
   ``The truth is that when reporters wrote their stories, they
jazzed them up,'' Torresson said.
   But for Agnes Margolis, who was on the cruise with her sister,
Ruth Coleman, the truth may lie in records the government continues
to withhold.
   ``There has definitely been a coverup despite the fact that there
is a Freedom of Information Act,'' said Mrs. Margolis, who was 28 at
the time.
   ``There is even talk that the munitions which we took to Havana
were to be diverted to Germany,'' she said. ``Maybe that is one
reason they are withholding this information.''
   Robert McDonnell and Fred Rasmussen, who are researching a book
on the Morro Castle, have sued the government in federal court in
Trenton, N.J., to win release of records that might solve the many
of the mysteries.
   They say the ship's owners hired a man to burn the vessel to
collect insurance. Complicating the case is that the arsonist,
George Rogers, was probably a government operative or informant and
that the liner sometimes carried arms to the Cuban dictator at the
time, the researchers say.
   Rogers, who had a criminal record before he worked on the ship,
later was convicted of trying to kill his boss, who suspected Rogers
of setting fire to the ship. He was paroled but sentenced to life in
prison for the bludgeoning deaths of his neighbors.
   The Morro Castle, bound for Pier 14 in Manhattan, was returning
from a ``Forget the Depression'' cruise to Cuba.
   With Wilmott dead and the fire raging, acting captain Warms,
apparently trying to get the ship near shore, turned it into strong
winds that quickly stoked the fire out of control.
   Survivors claimed that the crew did little to help the
panic-stricken passengers. Lifeboats that arrived on shore were
filled with mostly crew members and few passengers.
   The ship's officers and an official of the Ward Line of New York
were convicted of willful negligence in a federal court trial but
their convictions were overturned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
