<FIRST>r i PM-Refugees-Crossing     09-11 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Refugees-Crossing,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tears, Champagne As East Germans Make It To West</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICKELSDORF, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``We're free! We're free! It's
unbelievable!'' shouted young East Germans who piled out of
Hungarian taxis early today in a wave of arriving refugees
celebrating with cheers, tears, champagne and honking horns.
   ``It's wonderful, it's terrific,'' refugees shouted to reporters
and border guards after Hungary opened up its Austrian frontier at
midnight to allow thousands of East Germans to go West, to the
dismay of East Berlin.
   Some of the cars stopped just inside Austria, disgorging laughing
and yelling East Germans swinging foaming champagne bottles.
   Several of the refugees, their nerves frayed after weeks of
waiting, broke into tears of joy on arrival in the West.
   One man, overcome with emotion, tried to smile as tears rolled
down his cheeks and couldn't speak as he arrived in this border town
50 miles southeast of Vienna.
   Crowds whistled, cheered and clapped as other East German cars _
some with sleeping toddlers oblivious to the commotion _ followed.
   In a rust-brown Lada, a Soviet-made car, the male driver, along
with another man and two women, grinned broadly at the Austrian
border booth and waved, transfixed in the glare of television camera
lights, before moving on.
   One group of youths, just before crossing the opened red and
white border barriers, held up a sign saying ``Give it up Erich'' _
a reference to East Germany's Communist leader, Erich Honecker.
   With open arms, Austrians met the new refugees whose mass
emigration to West Germany _ where citizenship is automatic _ is the
largest of East Germans since the Berlin Wall was built in 1961 to
stem the flow across the border.
   Some of the Austrians offered to feed or shelter those wanting to
rest before continuing their journey. One woman stood by the side of
the road with a hand-lettered sign offering room and board for a
refugee family with children.
   Red Cross workers in Nickelsdorf handed out steaming cups of tea,
crackers, maps _ and advice _ to the East Germans. Many of the
refugees said they planned to drive directly to the West German
border, 400 miles to the north, where tent communities awaited them.
   At the Nickelsdorf crossing, Austrian customs agents told
reporters that about 2,000 people crossed the frontier in cars alone
in the first five hours of the exodus.
   One veteran Red Cross volunteer told reporters the nighttime
border influx reminded him of the thousands of Hungarians who fled
over the same border in 1956, after Soviet tanks crushed the Soviet
bloc's bloodiest revolt.
</TEXT>
