<FIRST>r a PM-FaithDome     09-11 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Faith Dome,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Faith Dome, a `Stealth Bomber For Jesus,' Opens Doors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Declaring the futuristic church a ``Star Wars
system for the Lord,'' the Rev. Fred Price led 8,100 congregants
into the first service inside one of the nation's largest churches.
   ``Hallelujah! Jesus just hit a grand-slam home run! Oooh, you
look good!'' Price exclaimed Sunday as he marched into the $9
million geodesic building dubbed the Faith Dome.
   ``This place is breathtaking,'' said John W. Smith of Hawthorne.
   With room for 10,145 people in theater-style seats, the Crenshaw
Christian Center in south-central Los Angeles is among the most
spacious church sanctuaries in the nation. The congregation is Los
Angeles' largest with 16,000 members.
   Price announced plans for the building eight years ago when the
congregation bought the original 28-acre Pepperdine University
campus for $14 million.
   In defense of the amount spent on the project, Price pointed out
the U.S. government spends billions on arms. He said the
church-in-the-round is, in a way, ``a Star Wars program for the Lord
... a stealth bomber for Jesus!
   ``And instead of killing folk, we're going to show them how to
get life, and life more abundantly.''
   Price, 57, is an independent clergyman in the Pentecostal
movement. His weekly services are televised nationwide.
