<DOCNO> AP890911-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 0605EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Uranium     09-11 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Uranium,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Seize 8.8 Pounds of Uranium Allegedly Offered for Sale to
U.S. Embassy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said today that they seized the 8.8 pounds of
uranium that was offered for sale to the U.S. Embassy in a case that
has already netted seven arrests.
   The uranium was seized Sunday at a food dealer's house in in
Kurume, Fukuoka Prefecture, 560 miles southwest of the capital.
   It was contained in 41 glass bottles in six X-ray prevention
bags, said an official of the Tokyo Metropolitan Police Department,
who spoke anonymously.
   The official said police experts on chemical materials analyzed
the substance discovered and found it was natural uranium.
   On Sept. 1, police arrested five people on charges of illegal
possession of nuclear substances after they took a capsule
containing about 3.5 ounces of uranium to the U.S. Embassy in early
August and proposed to sell another 8.8 pounds of the same substance
for $83 million.
   Two more people were arrested on Tuesday and Friday and an eighth
person, Mitsuteru Tomoda, a 51-year-old antique art dealer, was put
on a wanted list.
   Another police official, also requesting anonymity, said the food
dealer told investigators Tomoda had asked him to keep the uranium.
   The first official said the food dealer, whose name was not
disclosed, reported the uranium case to local police after
consulting with a lawyer.
   He identified the arrested group's leader as Toshiko Nishijima, a
43-year-old woman who owns several small companies.
   Uranium, a radioactive element, can be used in concentrated forms
to make nuclear weapons and run nuclear power plants.
   Police have said analysis of the uranium seized earlier showed it
was refined natural uranium of 70.7 percent purity.
   The Science and Technology Agency's analysis said only 0.7
percent of the uranium was uranium-235, the element used for power
generation and for bombs, while the rest was uranium-238.
   Nuclear experts said nuclear power generation needs uranium
containing more than 3 percent uranium-235 and an atomic bomb
requires uranium that contains more than 90 percent uranium-235.
   Police still were investigating the source of the group's uranium
and why the group tried to sell it to the U.S. Embassy at more than
2,000 times its market value of $275 an ounce.
   In Japan, the handling of uranium is strictly regulated by law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
