<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 0606EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CattleDrive     09-11 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cattle Drive,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>End of Cattle Drive Prompts Pride, And a Little Longing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM LACEKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BILLINGS, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The big drive of '89 ended with a sigh as
well as a whoop.
   ``It was too soon,'' said wagon master Dave Stephens. ``I wish
the city limits would have been another 50 miles down the road.''
   Many of the 2,400 real and would-be cowboys who rode the six-day,
60-mile trail from Roundup to Billings with Stephens clearly felt
the same way. Hundreds lingered Saturday to savor the memories.
   The Great Montana Centennial Cattle Drive, celebrating Montana's
statehood anniversary, brought 2,700 cattle across open range with
the help of 2,400 horseback riders and 200 covered wagons.
   ``I feel proud,'' said trail boss Jay Stovall. ``I know there
were skeptics, but I knew we could do it all the time.''
   Two cattle died, one just before the drive began on Labor Day in
the town of Roundup. Two calves were born along the way. Five people
were injured seriously enough that they had to leave the drive. A
couple of wagons were disabled.
   Stovall's 105 drovers brought the herd through a huge welcoming
crowd along Billings' Main Street on Saturday as if they did it
every day. Police estimated the throng at 25,000 to 30,000 _ more
than a fourth of the city's entire population.
   The cattle, mostly longhorns, climaxed a spectacular parade of
the riders and covered wagons.
   ``It all went very well, although it didn't go according to
plan,'' said Police Chief Gene Kiser.
   Police said not only was there no huge traffic snarl, as feared.
There also were no traffic accidents, injuries, or arrests.
   Only some of the wagons were supposed to join the parade, but on
Friday night Barry McWiliams, one of the drive's originators,
announced in camp that all would go.
   ``Some bureaucrats said that it would cause too many problems,''
he told the assembly. ``I told them either we all go or none of us
go.''
   Latigo Corp., the non-profit company created to put on the drive,
turns now to tabulating the costs and incomes. Any money above
expenses is to go into an endowment fund to help finance a variety
of rural projects.
   Latigo officials had said earlier the drive would cost $400,000
to $1 million and that final figures could not be determined until
after the drive.
   An auction of Western memorabilia and art was held Saturday
afternoon, and the grand finale of the drive was a country music
concert Saturday night that drew 4,200 people to see such musical
stars as Lee Greenwood, Sheb Wooley and Hoyt Axton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
