<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 0639EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WVaElection     09-11 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-WVa Election,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>W.Va. Governor Blamed for Defeat of Three Referendums</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two state officials who campaigned
against a referendum that would have eliminated their jobs said the
results of the special balloting show voters are disenchanted with
Gov. Gaston Caperton.
   But that assessment by Secretary of State Ken Hechler and
Agriculture Commissioner Cleve Benedict, who fought hard against the
amendments, was disputed by Caperton and state Democratic Party
Chairman Lloyd Jackson.
   They maintained the amendments failed because voters were fooled
by an anti-amendment campaign that unfairly said Caperton was power
hungry.
   One of the amendments would have eliminated the jobs of secretary
of state, treasurer and agriculture commissioner. Eleven percent of
those voting supported that amendment. The results were 217,582
against and 28,095 for with 99 percent of the vote tabulated.
   The other amendments would have brought the state Board of
Education under Caperton's control and allowed county governments to
restructure.
   The education amendment was defeated 217,727 to 28,670, with 88
percent of the voters saying no. The county reorganization amendment
was defeated 199,507 to 46,573, with 81 percent voting against it.
   West Virginia House Speaker Chuck Chambers said the 30 percent
voter turnout showed that voters are fed up with state government.
   Chambers said Caperton is unpopular because of a record $392
million in tax increases the governor pushed through the Legislature
this year.
</TEXT>
