<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     09-11 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar opened higher but fell back on
profit-taking today in early European trading. Gold prices were
lower.
   Dealers said the dollar was higher at the opening but failed to
break the important psychological barrier of 2 German marks.
   They said the dollar retreated on short-term profit-taking and
position adjustments although they said it was likely to resume its
advance after the U.S. market opened.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.15 yen to a closing 147.77 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at a rate of 147.65 yen.
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.5408 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.5505 late Friday.
   Other mid-morning dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Friday:
   _ 1.9980 West German marks, up from 1.9795
   _ 1.7220 Swiss francs, up from 1.7080
   _ 6.6732 French francs, up from 6.6710
   _ 2.2480 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2320
   _ 1,429.75 Italian lire, up 1,421.70
   _ 1.1860 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1877
   Gold opened in London to a bid price of $357.65 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $360.00. At mid-morning, London bullion
dealers fixed a recommended gold price of $358.10 a troy ounce.
   In Zurich, gold was trading at a bid $358.10 compared with
$360.00 late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 21 cents to close at a bid
$358.90.
   Silver traded on the London market at a bid price of $5.06 a troy
ounce, compared with Friday's $5.12.
</TEXT>
