<SECOND>PM-Marcos, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0488,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Marks 72nd Birthday</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 5th graf, `It was ...' to CORRECT that it is Marcos' fourth
birthday in exile.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of supporters of Ferdinand Marcos
attended a birthday party for the former Philippine president as he
remained hospitalized in critical condition.
   The celebration was held outside his home Sunday, the day before
his 72nd birthday.
   Earlier Sunday, his wife, Imelda, attended Mass with him in his
room at St. Francis Medical Center.
   ``When we got to the hospital early this morning, the president
was without fever and his blood pressure was normal,'' Mrs. Marcos
told the cheering crowd.
   It was Marcos' fourth birthday in exile. The Marcoses were exiled
here in 1986 when a popular revolt led Corazon Aquino to take over
the presidency. She has refused to let Marcos return, citing
national security concerns.
   They face federal racketeering charges in the United States for
allegedly looting more than $100 million from their country to buy
art and real estate in New York.
   ``If it is the last thing that I will do in my life, I would try
to vindicate the sacred honor and the good name of Ferdinand Marcos
and the entire republic,'' Mrs. Marcos said.
   Among those at the party was Philippine singer Imelda Pappin, who
had a birthday wish for Marcos.
   ``I wish that he will live longer,'' Ms. Pappin said.
   Marcos, who was hospitalized in January, is suffering from lung,
heart and kidney failure. Marcos' medical condition has led him to
be seperated from the racketeering case.
</TEXT>
