<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 0744EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Norway-Election 1stLd-Writethru   09-11 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Norway-Election, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0472,0755</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brundtland Braces For Election Setback</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with prime minister, husband voting,
comment. Pickup 4th pvs, `Final results ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gro Harlem Brundtland's governing Labor Party
braced for an election setback as Norwegians cast ballots today in a
hard-fought parliamentary election.
   Pre-election surveys predicted the non-socialist opposition
parties would win a majority. But disagreements may prevent them
from negotiating a common program, and Mrs. Brundtland could
continue as prime minister by default.
   Mrs. Brundtland voted shortly after polls opened at 9 a.m. under
bright sunshine. ``It's a good day for an election,'' she said.
   The prime minister arrived with her husband Arne Olav Brundtland,
who was wearing a campaign badge for the opposition Conservative
Party. The political division in the Brundtland family is the butt
of much national humor.
   Asked if she won any new supporters over the breakfast table,
Mrs. Brundtland said she didn't eat breakfast this morning.
   The first election results, based on computer projections and
pre-election surveys, were expected shortly after the polls close at
9 p.m. (3 p.m. EDT).
   Final results may become clear only Wednesday because of a new
election system that adds eight seats, apportioned according to
nationwide results, to the 157 seats elected by 19 regional
districts.
   Some 3.2 million people are eligible to vote for parliament,
which sits four years. There is no mechanism for early elections.
   Based on the three latest polls, the NTB news agency on Sunday
forecast that the non-socialist parties would win 85 seats, while
Labor and the Left Socialist Party would take a total of 80 seats.
   ``There is a clear non-socialist majority. The question is
whether they can translate that into a clear majority in
parliament,'' said Bernt Ole Aardal, of the Institute for Social
Research.
   He said Mrs. Brundtland has regained some of her lost support
during the campaign, which some critics have described as unusually
dirty for this easy-going Scandinavian country. ``She has run a
strong campaign. If she ends up with 35 percent, that would be a
success,'' Aardal said.
   Campaigning was abruptly suspended after Friday's crash of a
chartered aircraft carrying Norwegian shipping company workers on a
celebration flight to West Germany to christen a new ship. All 55
people on board died.
   Mrs. Brundtland, who was briefly prime minister in 1981, has
headed a minority Labor government since a three-party non-socialist
coalition resigned in 1986.
   Her support has dropped from 40.8 percent in the 1985 election to
around 33 percent in some recent surveys, as she appeared to be
paying for the excesses she blamed on her predecessors in the
free-spending days when oil wealth poured in from North Sea fields.
   She has been hurt by public discontent with high taxes, high
prices and a social welfare system which seemed on the verge of a
breakdown.
   Norwegians pay as much as 62.7 percent income tax in the top
bracket, and international surveys list Oslo as the most expensive
city in Europe.
   At the same time, waiting lines for public hospitals have
lengthened, there is a shortage of day-care centers and critics say
education standards have plummeted.
   Economists have praised Mrs. Brundtland's tough wage-restraint
program, which helped halve inflation since 1987 to 4.8 percent and
turned a balance of payments deficit into a surplus.
   But unemployment nearly tripled to a record 5 percent in two
years and the benefits of an improving economy have not filtered
down to the public.
   Though she chaired the U.N. World Commission on Environment and
Development, the prime minister has come under sharp attack at home
for letting industries contaminate some of Norway's once pristine
fjords.
   To replace Mrs. Brundtland, Conservative Party leader Jan P. Syse
must rely on the support of the maverick Party of Progress, which
has made dramatic gains on a platform of sharply cutting taxes and
privatizing public companies and services.
   The Progress Party is led by Carl I. Hagen, a 45-year-old
British-educated former marketing executive who has become the star
of the political stage with his television good looks and
unrestrained attacks on the establishment.
   Hagen won just 3.7 percent in 1985, but he took 12 percent in
local elections in 1987 and had about 20 percent support in opinion
polls as late as last month. The most recent polls showed him
sliding back to below 15 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
