<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-11 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Hits Three-Month High Against Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar shot up to a three-month high against the
Japanese yen today despite the central bank's dollar-selling
intervention, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index fell
marginally.
   The dollar closed at 147.77 yen, up 1.15 yen from Friday's
146.62-yen finish. It opened at 147.75 yen and ranged between 147.50
yen and 148.03 yen.
   It was the dollar's highest close since 151.30 on June 15. It has
gained 4.69 yen since Aug. 30.
   Minori Takeuchi, a trader with Chemical Bank in Tokyo, said that
after its high opening, the dollar moved little, ``mainly because
Japanese participants who were afraid of central bank intervention
avoided major moves.''
   The Bank of Japan sold the U.S. currency to support the yen, but
the amount it sold was unknown. The bank does not comment on its
exchange market activities.
   ``The market is expecting the dollar to climb as high as 148.50
yen, but it won't happen overnight,'' Ms. Takeuchi said.
   ``Because of a steady dollar-selling drive among those who had
kept too many dollars, the currency will rise only slowly ... but
surely, because the dollar-buying demand is much stronger,'' she
said.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 2.15 points,
or 0.006 percent, finishing at 34,113.66. The market rallied in the
afternoon after losing 77.30 points in the morning and 36.75 points
last Friday.
   Dealers attributed the index's fall largely to the yen's recent
weakness against the dollar.
   Genjiro Sasaki, a stock dealer with New Japan Securities Co.,
said the index started to recover as foreign investors bought Nikkei
index issues as part of arbitrage deals.
   He added that some investors also helped the index's recovery by
picking up issues that had fallen earlier.
   ``The majority of market players, however, remained on the
sidelines, discouraged by the weak yen and falling bond prices,''
Sasaki said.
</TEXT>
