<FIRST>r a PM-Wedtech-Garcia     09-11 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wedtech-Garcia,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman to be Tried on Corruption Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Robert Garcia goes on trial this week
on charges he, his wife and her lawyer extorted $185,000, including
a diamond and emerald necklace, from Wedtech, the now-defunct
defense contractor.
   The 56-year-old Democrat is accused of using his position to
obtain the payoffs from Wedtech, once acclaimed as a model of
minority-owned businesses.
   This is likely to be the last of seven trials from the Wedtech
scandal. Already convicted were such figures as Rep. Mario Biaggi,
D-N.Y., and Stanley Simon, borough president of the Bronx.
   Jury selection was set to begin today in federal court; opening
arguments are scheduled a week later. Garcia faces up to 20 years in
prison.
   Garcia was indicted in November, three days after Biaggi drew an
eight-year sentence in a Wedtech racketeering case. Biaggi resigned
from the U.S. House and is in prison.
   Garcia, his wife, Jane Lee, and lawyer Ralph Vallone Jr. are
accused of a bribery-extortion scheme to get $185,000 from Wedtech
officials in checks, interest-free loans and, for Mrs. Garcia, a
jeweled necklace.
   Because of illness, Vallone's trial was postponed until the
spring, The New York Times reported today.
   The government is expected to present witnesses who will testify
that Garcia demanded payments from Wedtech that were routed through
his wife's political consulting business.
   The indictment said the payments were demanded to influence
Garcia's ``performance of official acts for and on behalf of
Wedtech.''
   Garcia, the son of a Pentecostal minister, since 1978 has
represented a a district that includes the South Bronx.
   Wedtech, once a small South Bronx machine shop, grew into a $100
million government contractor through a federal program that set
aside contracts without bidding for minority-controlled companies.
   Evidence at earlier trials showed Wedtech continued to receive
no-bid contracts through bribery even after it ceased to be
minority-owned. It went out of business in 1986 after allegations
about illegal activity were made public.
</TEXT>
