<HEAD>Becker Defeats Lendl in 110-Degree Heat for First U.S. Open Win</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CLARIFY that 110 was temperature on court.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserColor XNYF9</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boris Becker defeated top-ranked Ivan Lendl to
win his first U.S. Open and give West Germany a sweep of the singles
competition at the Grand Slam tennis tournament.
   In a struggle that lasted nearly four hours and with temperatures
on court climbing to 110 degrees, the second seed won 7-6, 1-6, 6-3,
7-6. The 21-year-old Becker won his third Wimbledon crown in July.
   ``This is much more exhausting,'' Becker said, comparing the Open
to his July victory at Wimbledon. ``It's even more exhausting than
the French Open, with the heat, the planes and the spectators.''
   Becker's Open victory earned him $300,000. Lendl, 29, a Czech who
now lives in Greenwich, Conn., earned $150,000.
   On Saturday, West German Steffi Graf came from behind to defeat
Martina Navratilova 3-6, 7-5, 6-1.
   In the women's doubles championship finals, Navratilova and Hana
Mandlikova defeated Pam Shriver and Mary Jo Fernandez 5-7, 6-4, 6-4.
Navratilova and Mandlikova split $104,000. Shriver and Fernandez
divided $52,000.
   ``This helps a lot,'' Navratilova said. ``(Saturday) was a
nightmare.''
