<HEAD>Newspaper: East German Leader's Condition Much Worse</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with West German TV report; picks
up 10th graf `In Bonn...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The condition of East German leader
Erich Honecker, who underwent gall bladder surgery last month, has
deteriorated badly, West German news media reported today.
   Government officials in Bonn declined comment on the reports.
   The ZDF television network today quoted Western diplomatic
sources in Hungary as saying Honecker's medical condition ``has
deteriorated considerably.
   ``According to information that allegedly comes from Communist
Party officials, Honecker has no mental verve and no wish to get
better,'' the network said. Honecker has been recovering from gall
bladder surgery he underwent last month.
   Honecker, 77, has staunchly resisted the reforms sweeping much of
the Soviet bloc. Tens of thousands of East Germans are fleeing their
country because of dissatisfaction with the political and economic
situation there.
   ``Critics in the Politburo reportedly are charging that Honecker
misjudged the meaning and scope of the wave of refugees,'' ZDF said.
   ZDF previously had said there were indications that Honecker was
``no longer fully able to reason.''
   Today, the mass-circulation Bild newspaper said in its front-page
headline: ``Honecker Wants to Die.''
   The Hamburg-based newspaper added: ``The condition of the
Communist leader has worsened badly.'' Citing unidentified sources
in East Berlin, Bild said that Honecker ``has lost the will to
live.''
   Bild is published by the giant Springer concern, which has been
bitterly at odds with Communist East Germany for decades.
   In East Berlin over the weekend, Communist party sources said
there were ``clear signs'' that Honecker's mental capacity was
failing and that his health problems had delayed several top-level
decisions.
   The sources, speaking on the condition of anonymity, also told
The Associated Press that it was difficult to gauge Honecker's exact
condition.
   In Bonn, Foreign Ministry spokesman Juergen Chrobog told the AP
in a telephone interview that reports on Honecker's condition are
``pure speculation. We have no first-hand information on this.''
   Western intelligence sources two weeks ago said Honecker's gall
bladder surgery had to be abandoned due to weakness of surrounding
tissue. News reports also speculated that Honecker has cancer.
   East Germany's state-run news agency ADN said early this month
that Honecker had been released from the hospital and taken a
vacation to recover. ADN has not carried any other recent reports on
the Communist leader's health.
