<FIRST>r a PM-ExxonValdez     09-11 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon Valdez,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Repairs to Begin on Exxon Valdez</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Volkswagen-sized rock lodged in the mangled
hull of the Exxon Valdez is among the obstacles workers face today
when they begin repairs on the tanker that caused the nation's worst
oil spill.
   During the nine-month repair job, 3,200 tons of steel will be
used to patch the hull of the 29,000-ton tanker that struck a reef
March 24 in Alaska's Prince William Sound.
   Reporters were allowed to view the hull Saturday for the first
time as workers at the National Steel and Shipbuilding Co. prepared
to start the repairs, estimated at $25 million.
   The Valdez is sitting 5 feet off the ground in a dry dock on
dozens of concrete pylons. Massive hydraulic shorings are also
supporting the tanker along its starboard side.
   By far, the largest visible damage was to a 300-by-80-foot
section of the starboard side. The area is a rusted patchwork of
scraped metal, tatered, gaping holes and twisted shards of steel.
   ``It's a very humbling experience to stand here and see what
Mother Nature can do to three-quarter-inch steel,'' NASSCO president
Richard Vortman said. ``There is damage to the structure in addition
to just the skin of the ship.''
   The Valdez was built by NASSCO in the same dry dock and launched
in 1986. It would cost up to $150 million to build a new tanker the
same size, Vortmann said.
   ``We have never done repairs to a ship anywhere near as
extensively damaged as this ship,'' he said. ``This will be a lot
more difficult than building a ship from scratch. It's harder to
build the bottom floors of a building when the upper floors already
exist.''
   One rock ``about the size of a Volkswagen Bug'' and another that
weighs an estimated 6,000 pounds are lodged in the torn hull,
Vortmann said.
   Both rocks are part of the reef that the Valdez struck while
loaded with nearly 53 million gallons of oil. The puncture sent
nearly 11 million gallons of crude pouring into the water.
</TEXT>
