<FIRST>r p PM-NYCMayoral 1stLd-Writethru a0462 09-11 0791</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NYC Mayoral, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0462,0807</SECOND>
<HEAD>Koch, Dinkins Grope for Crucial Votes in Election's Last Days</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13th graf pvs, `But while ...' to DELETE extraneous `the.'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six months ago Mayor Edward I. Koch was an
anyone-can-beat-him underdog. Now he's a comeback-of-the-year
contender in his quest for an unprecedented fourth term.
   Polls have the three-term incumbent running nearly even with his
prime opponent, Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins, in
Tuesday's Democratic primary. Strategists on both sides said their
ability to turn out voters would decide the election.
   ``I think it's going to be very, very close,'' said David Garth,
Koch's political and media adviser. Asked his plans for last-minute
appeals, he joked: ``We're going to ask the people to join us in
prayer.''
   ``It's neck and neck. I don't think you can ever count out an
incumbent who has been in office as long as Ed Koch,'' said Bill
Lynch, Dinkins' campaign manager. He claimed a slight lead,
confirmed by most polls.
   A survey conducted Friday and Saturday by WABC-TV and the Daily
News found 49 percent for Dinkins and 45 percent for Koch. But the
margin of error for that poll was 6 points, and previous polls
showed the race within the margin of error.
   Koch has declared: ``A big turnout, I win.'' But he also
expressed more anxiety about this race than any other in his career.
   Meanwhile, he presides over a troubled city.
   When Koch was elected to his third term in 1985, only a few
investigators were aware of city corruption scandals about to break
open. Crack was virtually unknown. The full devastation of the AIDS
epidemic was not yet generally apparent. There were fewer homeless
people. Crime rates had not hit the historic levels they're at now.
   The Democratic primary is about all those issues, said Rep.
Thomas Manton, Democratic leader of the borough of Queens and a new
Koch supporter. ``But more than anything, it's a question of the
incumbent and his record.''
   Whatever the primary's outcome, it will make history. Dinkins
would be the first black nominated by a major party for mayor in New
York; Koch would be the first mayor nominated for a fourth term.
   The Democratic nomination usually means election, because five
Democrats are registered for each Republican. But Rudolph W.
Giuliani, a popular former federal prosecutor, is front-runner for
the GOP nomination and could mount a serious challenge in the Nov. 7
general election.
   Attention for the moment was riveted on the Democratic race, a
contest of style as much as substance between the reserved,
unflappable Dinkins and the outspoken, occasionally outrageous Koch.
   But while he trailed badly in early polls, Koch appears to have
regained many of the voters who had left him for the now-faltering
candidacy of city Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin. Goldin and a
fourth candidate, former transit chief Richard Ravitch, trail badly,
as does Giuliani's only challenger in the Republican primary,
cosmetics company heir Ronald Lauder.
   ``Koch's campaign has been focused on his record. His TV ads are
about what Ed Koch has done,'' said Lee Miringoff, pollster at the
Marist College Institute for Public Opinion. ``The net effect of
that seems to be to have driven down his negative rating somewhat.''
   Dinkins got help recently from Jesse Jackson, who received 45
percent of the New York City vote in last year's Democratic
presidential primary.
   Jackson came back ``to energize our support,'' said Lynch, but he
has not played a major role because of his negative appraisal by
many Jews, another important voting group.
   Jews may make up 25 percent of the Democratic vote; blacks, up to
a third. Koch himself is Jewish.
   The greatest energizer of the black vote may prove to be the Aug.
23 killing of a black youth, Yusuf Hawkins, by a white gang. Koch
drew sharp criticism by suggesting that protest marches after the
killing had exacerbated racial tensions.
   Even before the killing, Dinkins stressed harmony and
conciliation as his themes, and since then he has maintained a
soothing response. But some analysts have suggested that the
protests by militant blacks may give Koch a white backlash vote.
   Said Lynch: ``I can make an argument for it hurting, or helping.''
   Certain help for Dinkins will come from a major get-out-the-vote
effort on his behalf by most of the city's largest unions, including
teachers, municipal employees and Teamsters.
   Koch, with less union support and fewer volunteers of his own, is
unlikely to approach Dinkins' strength on the streets. Koch's aides
express concern on this point, and Dinkins' campaign manager called
it crucial.
   ``In a race that's neck and neck,'' Lynch said, ``turnout is
going to be the issue.''
</TEXT>
