<FIRST>r a PM-GasPrices     09-11 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gas Prices,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gas Prices Show Another Drop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The retail price of a gallon of gasoline
dropped more than a penny in the past two weeks, but wholesale
prices are up, meaning an increase at the pump is possible this
fall, an industry analyst says.
   The nationwide average price for all grades at full- and
self-service pumps was $1.09.07 per gallon Aug. 25 to Sept. 9, a
drop of 1.37 cents, said Trilby Lundberg.
   Wholesale prices rose 0.33 cents as wholesalers' inventories,
stockpiled after the Exxon Valdez oil spill, returned closer to
normal, said Ms. Lundberg, director of the Lundberg Survey of 12,000
gasoline stations.
   Competition has dissuaded retailers from passing along the price
increase, but that could change, Ms. Lundberg said. ``It now appears
that gasoline retailers' operating margins are being squeezed and
that more of them may soon pass along the increases in the way of
higher street prices,'' she said.
   The average price of a gallon at the pump has dropped 9.33 cents
since it peaked May 19, Ms. Lundberg said.
</TEXT>
