<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1027EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Refugees     09-11 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Refugees,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan to Screen Economic Migrants From Vietnam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan will not grant refugee status to Vietnamese
and other Indochinese escaping to this country solely for better
economic prospects, officials said today.
   Beginning Wednesday, Japan will adopt a new screening process
based on an international agreement in Geneva in June, said Toshio
Tsunozaki, director of the Foreign Ministry's Human Rights and
Refugee Division,
   ``We are implementing the measures to exclude the pseudo-refugees
and distinguish genuine refugees,'' he said. ``We would like to
prevent abuse of very generous treatment by the Japanese side.''
   Many of the Vietnamese boat people who arrived recently in Japan
told officials they came to escape poverty, not because of
religious, political or racial persecution.
   Tsunozaki said those already granted refugee status would be
allowed to stay.
   Japan would not push arriving boats back out to sea, he added.
Those who are refused refugee status would be detained in
immigration centers until they can be repatriated, he said.
   More than 1.8 million Indochinese refugees have been settled in
some 30 countries, but more than 165,000 were still in camps in Asia
as of April.
   So far this year, 2,950 Vietnamese boat people have arrived in
Japan, compared with 219 in all of 1988.
   Justice Ministry officials have attributed the recent increase to
Japan's former refugee policy.
   Unlike the United States, as well as many Asian nations, Japan
has never distinguished between Indochinese fleeing political
persecution and those fleeing poverty.
   Tsunozaki said people from other nations fleeing political
persecution also could apply for refugee status, but would be
handled separately from Indochinese undergoing the screening process.
   The Geneva conference adopted a plan to screen all new arrivals
from Indochina to determine whether they should be granted refugee
status or repatriated. The conference also called for encouraging
voluntary returns.
   Meanwhile, 32 Chinese arrived by boat on Sept. 3 seeking refugee
status so that they could find jobs in Japan, Toshiki Eguchi, an
official of the Justice Ministry's refugee section, told The
Associated Press.
   ``None of them was a political refugee. They were illegal
aliens,'' Eguchi said.
   Chinese also have been found masquerading as Vietnamese refugees
on some of the boats that have arrived from Vietnam since May 29.
   So far, 639 Chinese, including the 32 who arrived Sept. 3, have
been detained in eight immigration centers waiting to be sent back
to China, Eguchi added.
   Some have said they fear punishment for fleeing if they are sent
back.
   Tsunozaki said, ``It's not discrimination toward the Chinese. We
don't want them to come to Japan by boat illegally.''
   Kyodo News Service reported that some of the 32 Chinese from
Fujian province had borrowed heavily to pay a broker in China to
arrange their trip to Japan.
   Quoting unnamed immigration officials, Kyodo said one of the 32
told of borrowing $4,865 at 36 percent interest to pay for the
passage.
   Also, each paid $1,215 to another Chinese broker for Japanese
immigration documents that turned out to be fake, Kyodo said.
   In the Geneva conference, Japan pledged to take 1,000 more
Indochinese refugees as permanent residents over the next three
years. So far, 6,222 Vietnamese have settled in Japan as permanent
residents.
</TEXT>
