<FIRST>r a PM-PaperMillViolence 1stLd-Writethru a0482 09-11 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paper Mill Violence, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0482,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Calm Returns to International Falls After Union Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS throughout to ADD comment from union official, move
up background on Guard decision. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF MEYER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INTERNATIONAL FALLS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor turmoil in which
protesters burned trailers, hurled rocks and overturned cars has
some officials questioning the state's commitment to squelching
violence.
   Residents in this town of 6,500 tried Sunday to rebound from
Saturday's rampage by pro-union activists, who for weeks have been
incensed at a contractor's use of non-union labor on a $535 million
expansion of Boise Cascade Corp.'s paper mill.
   Damage was estimated at $1.3 million in the biggest disturbance
since an estimated 150 union workers at the mill went on a wildcat
strike in July. Five people were injured and 32 arrested, and
officials criticized Gov. Rudy Perpich for not calling out the
National Guard.
   Authorities planned more arrests after reviewing videotapes, and
Perpich said evidence would be sent to the U.S. attorney's office
for possible federal charges.
   ``Yesterday was a sad day for us in International Falls,'' the
Rev. Robert A. Kitchen, pastor of Faith United Church of Christ,
said Sunday. ``It was a day of desperation, of anger, of
hopelessness, perhaps.''
   Kitchen described the unrest as ``an open wound that we know has
ripped our community apart,'' and he prayed that the community pull
together and denounce the violence.
   About 370 non-union workers in five buses entered the
construction site under police escort early Sunday. Police reported
no problems.
   On Saturday, about 45 police officers used tear gas to disperse
about 400 protesters, dozens of whom stormed housing trailers that
had been evacuated the night before.
   Law enforcement officials requested the National Guard. The
governor put troops on alert but decided not to deploy them after
calm was restored.
   Perpich acknowledged Sunday that intelligence reports a few days
earlier indicated potential trouble over the weekend. But Perpich
said the state could not send in the Guard simply in anticipation of
trouble.
   ``The only place where there is complete safety is in East
Europe, because the army's there all the time. That way you have
perfect control,'' Perpich said in St. Paul. ``This is a free
society. ... And you do not use the National Guard for law
enforcement. It's a military organization.''
   Union officials have not sanctioned the strike and say they have
tried to dissuade protesters from violence or mass demonstrations.
   Bill Peterson, head of the Minnesota Building Trades Council,
said Sunday that his union group planned a rally for next weekend in
the capital, St. Paul.
   ``We think any rally at International Falls ought not be held
because we were sure that, tensions running as high as they were,
there could be some problems,'' he said.
   Boise spokesman Andrew Drysdale said the Guard should have been
called out because violence could erupt again. ``I think it's highly
likely this won't be the last thing they'll pull,'' he said.
   And Sheriff William Elliott said he's unsure local law
enforcement agencies have the manpower to quell future disturbances.
   ``The problem we have in northern Minnesota is we're so far away
from help,'' he said. ``We need an early response and the law
enforcement agencies are so spread apart we may have difficulty
getting that.''
   Mark Shields, superintendent of the state Bureau of Criminal
Apprehension, said eight agents were sent to International Falls a
few days ago based on reports of potential violence.
   ``We were present,'' Perpich said. ``And it's because of our
presence that those people who were responsible are all going to be
brought to justice.''
</TEXT>
