<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1113EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DuckCarnage     09-11 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Duck Carnage,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Game Officials Alarmed at Killings of Ugly Ducklings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The homely Muscovy duck has exposed a
cruel streak among Floridians.
   Muscovies in recent weeks have been beaten to death, shot with
steel-tipped darts, and, in one instance, kicked and hacked to
pieces in front of a group of children.
   ``Something needs to be done uniformly to stop the mutilation,''
said Cindy Mosling, who heads the Bird Emergency Aid &amp; Kare
Sanctuary, or BEAKS.
   Normally found around the ponds of parks and apartment complexes,
the heavyset Muscovies are best known for waddling after children,
eating huge amounts, hissing like snakes and breeding like rabbits.
They grow up to 15 inches high and have dark feathers with white
splotches and red wattling above their beaks.
   The Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish Commission is drafting a
policy on how the state should deal with the Muscovies as well as
other ``nuisance fowl,'' which include urban mallards.
   Officials say they suspect property owners are killing the ducks
because of their droppings. There are ``records and records and
records'' of violence against the ducks, said Ms. Mosling.
   ``We as a society wouldn't condone it if dogs and cats were
mutiliated on the streets,'' she said. ``For some reason, people can
justify cruelty if it's a homely victim.''
   Muscovies, which can fly short distances, are native to Latin
America. Twenty to 25 years ago, they were brought to Florida as an
ornamental species to liven up the ponds and lagoons around
residental communities, said Rich Turnbull, a state waterfowl
biologist.
   Because they are not native to Florida, the Muscovies are not
protected by state wildlife laws. But they are protected under laws
against cruelty to animals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
