<DOCNO> AP890911-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1116EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CapitalGains     09-11 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Capital Gains,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Will Try to Amend Capital-Gains Tax Cut Measure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House Ways and Means Committee member said
today he will attempt to amend a capital-gains tax cut that the
panel is expected to approve this week so none of the benefit would
go to people with incomes over $200,000 a year.
   ``If we are going to offer a capital-gains exclusion, we should
offer it to those wno need it,'' Rep. Byron L. Dorgan, D-N.D., told
a news conference. ``Those who have incomes in the millions can well
afford the modest top tax rates under today's tax system.''
   Dorgan's limited capital-gains reduction would be financed by
raising from 28 percent to 33 percent the maximum tax rate that
applies to all types of income earned by wealthier taxpayers.
   The Ways and Means Committee will resume consideration Tuesday of
a plan, endorsed by President Bush, that would allow investors to
avoid tax on 30 percent of capital gains, which are profits from the
sale of stock and other assets. Congressional staff experts estimate
that 80 percent of the benefit of such a reduction would go to those
with annual incomes above $100,000.
   That proposal, sponsored chiefly by Reps. Ed Jenkins, D-Ga., and
Bill Archer, R-Texas, apparently has the support of a bare majority
of the Ways and Means Committee.
   Dorgan said he would prefer no change in taxation of capital
gains, which now are taxed at the same rates as other income. He is
offering the alternative, he said, only because it appears the
committee will approve a capital-gains cut.
   Under Dorgan's proposal:
   _Thirty percent of capital gains would be excluded from taxation
for couples with total income of $100,000 or less.
   _The portion of the gain that would be excluded from taxation
would decline gradually as income rises between $100,000 and
$200,000. At $150,000 income, the exclusion would be 15 percent.
   _No exclusion would be allowed once total income exceeds $200,000
a year.
   _A quirk in the 1986 tax law that has some people paying a lower
rate as income rises would be eliminated. For example, a couple with
two children and taxable income of $300,000 now paying a 28 percent
rate on all above $201,500 would have to pay 33 percent on all above
that level.
   That rate change would affect only the wealthiest 1 percent of
taxpayers, Dorgan said.
 
</TEXT>
