<FIRST>r a PM-DoomsdayClock 1stLd-Writethru a0424 09-11 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Doomsday Clock, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0424,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Doomsday Clock' Changes Face to Depict Environmental Focus</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to CLARIFY new factors will be calculated
in setting clock. PICKS UP 10th graf, `We need ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bulletin of Atomic Scientists, whose clock has
ticked a few minutes before nuclear midnight for 42 years, says it
will begin taking environmental dangers, poverty and other threats
into account in moving the hands.
   During the Cold War and detente, the clock represented the
world's proximity to nuclear annihilation. With the easing of
U.S.-Soviet tensions, the clock will also reflect other dangers to
survival, said editor Len Ackland.
   ``It's a recognition that international security has to be
thought about in more than simple military terms,'' Ackland said.
``It doesn't mean in any way that military security is less
important.''
   The ``clock'' isn't a real timepiece; it is a logo of a clock
face printed in the bulletin. Beginning this week with the October
issue, the ``Doomsday clock'' logo will soon consist of the clock
face superimposed on a globe.
   The clock, which first appeared in 1947, has represented an
estimate by the editors and an international board of scientists of
the world's proximity to the nuclear destruction. The hands have
been reset 12 times.
   The closest it ever got to midnight, 11:57, was in 1951, after
the Soviets exploded an atom bomb, and again in 1983, when
U.S.-Soviet arms talks were suspended.
   The clock has remained at 11:54 since January 1988, when the
United States and Soviet Union signed a treaty to eliminate
intermediate-range nuclear weapons.
   ``In the past year and a half, we have certainly seen progress in
improving the U.S.-Soviet Union arms control negotiations,'' Ackland
said in a telephone interview from his suburban Oak Park home.
``Once tensions dropped down, it enabled us to take a look around
and recognize there are many other dangers that threaten our
survival, and environmental concerns are probably the most
conspicuous.''
   ``We felt this was a very important time to redefine what
national security is,'' Ackland said Sunday.
   ``We need to also recognize there are a lot of connections with
environmental issues, economic depression and poverty around the
world because those are the kinds of things that could escalate
quickly.''
   John Peoples, director of the Fermi National Accelerator
Laboratory near Chicago, said the change in focus is necessary and
important, if not tardy.
   ``Irrespective of whether the Cold War is dissolving, one has to
pay attention to the environment,'' he said. ``Certainly things like
Chernobyl ... and Bhopal, they have to have equal priority.''
   In 1986, the Chernobyl nuclear power plant in the Soviet Union
exploded, spewing radiation that killed at least 32 people and
eventually swirled around the globe. A gas leak from a Union Carbide
pesticide plant killed more than 3,400 people in Bhopal, India, in
1984.
   The journal began as a newsletter among scientists of the
Manhattan Project _ the top-secret U.S. effort during World War II
to develop the atomic bomb before the Axis powers.
   The first six-page Bulletin was published in 1945. Today's
journal, about 50 pages long, is published 10 times a year. Though
paid subscribers are relatively few _ about 20,000 in 70 countries _
they have included members of of lawmaking bodies around the world.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890911-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1228EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     09-11 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspected Sinhalese Radicals Kill University Official</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen believed to be radicals of the
Sinhalese majority killed the security chief at a university Monday
and then stormed the vice chancellor's office and shot him to death,
military officials said.
   Police said they believed the attackers, who escaped on a
motorcycle, belonged to the People's Liberation Front, a Sinhalese
extremist group trying to overthrow the government.
   Military officials who cannot be identified under briefing rules
said two men entered the office of Chandraratne Patuwathavitane at
Moratuwa university in southern Sri Lanka and opened fire.
Patuwathavitane, a 60-year-old engineering professor, was hit in the
head and killed, they said.
   The gunmen shot the university's security chief at the campus
entrance before entering the vice chancellor's office, the officials
said.
   A total of 55 people were reported killed since Sunday in ethnic
violence on this Indian Ocean island.
   The victims included nine members of a former Tamil rebel group,
the Eelam People's Liberation Front, who died Monday in an ambush by
a rival rebel group, military officials said.
   The attackers were believed to be members of the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam, which is fighting for a separate nation for
the Tamil minority.
   Also reported killed were five Indian peacekeeping soldiers and
three Sinhalese militants shot by security forces, a government
statement said. It did not release details.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa has called a meeting Wednesday
aimed at resolving the ethnic problems, which have claimed more than
16,000 lives in the past six years.
   Premadasa sent invitations to all 23 recognized political
parties, but three opposition parties _ the Trotskyte Lanka Peoples'
Party, the Communist Party and the New Peoples' Party _ said they
will boycott the meeting.
   The two main Tamil guerrilla groups, the Liberation Tigers of
Tamil Eelam and the People's Liberation Organization of Tamil Eelam,
plan to attend.
   ``The decision to participate in the all-party conference is
prompted by our desire to cooperate with the government of Sri Lanka
in its genuine efforts to find solutions to the complex problems
that beset the island,'' said a statement released by the Tigers,
who held separate peace talks with the government earlier this year.
   The Tigers, who are demanding an independent homeland in the
north and east for the Tamil minority, have been fighting Indian
soldiers sent to the island two years ago to enforce an accord aimed
at ending the Tamil war.
   The accord offered the Tamils limited autonomy if they would
surrender their weapons. The Tigers rejected the accord, saying it
did not meet their expections.
   Sinhalese militants said the accord granted too many concessions
to the Tamils and began fighting the Sinhalese-led government.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of the island's 16 million people and
claim they are denied jobs and education by the Sinhalese, who
comprise 75 percent of the population and dominate the government
and military.
</TEXT>
