<FIRST>r i AM-Malaysia     09-11 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Malaysia,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslem Students Protest Pop Concert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Moslem students opposed
to pop music clashed with police outside a concert, and at least 22
were arrested, officials said Monday.
   Police Superintendent Salleh Gomu told reporters the 22 students
were released on $185 bail each and could be charged with taking
part in an illegal demonstration.
   The placard-carrying students demonstrated Sunday night outside
the University of Malaya's main hall, where popular singer Sheila
Majid was performing. They told reporters the pop and other songs
she was singing were un-Islamic and that only holy songs or cultural
songs should be allowed.
   When the students refused orders to disperse, about 25 police
charged them with batons. Some cars were damaged as students
scrambled over them while fleeing, but no injuries were reported.
   The students were mainly from the Islamic Undergraduates
Association.
   The school's deputy vice chancellor, Abdul Rashid Ahmad, said the
students had sent a memorandum demanding cancellation of the
concert, held to raise funds for the university's cultural fund.
   Despite the protests, he said, more pop concerts would be held.
   He said all shows are screened by university authorities. ``We
just don't allow heavy metal and such groups, as they are a bad
influence,'' he added.
