<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--BostonLatin     09-11 0147</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Boston Latin,0151</SECOND>
<HEAD>School Gets $1 Million Gift</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boston Latin School, the oldest public college
preparatory school in the country, was given $1 million from a New
York businessman, which the school says it will use for scholarships
for needy students.
   The gift from alumnus Marshall S. Cogan, was the largest personal
gift the school has received since it was founded in 1635.
   Cogan, 52, is chairman and chief executive officer of Knoll
International Holdings Inc., which makes home products. He is a 1955
graduate and a trustee of Boston Latin.
   He said the school ``gave me a shot at the world,'' making it
possible for him to go to Harvard College and Harvard Business
School.
   Most of the money is earmarked for scholarships for students from
moderate income families, and $100,000 will to to a language
laboratory, The Boston Globe reported Monday.
</TEXT>
