<SECOND>AM-New Zealand-US,0144</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Zealand Prime Minister Says U.S. Won't Talk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Geoffery Palmer of New
Zealand said relations between the United States and New Zealand
have deteriorated because of New Zealand's non-nuclear policy, a
newspaper said Monday.
   The newspaper, Ilta-Sanomat, quoted Palmer as saying U.S. leaders
had ``systematically'' refused to engage in normal talks with New
Zealand.
   ``This is rather strange treatment toward a nation which in the
American view is, after all, friendly and democratic,'' Palmer said.
   Palmer said political relations between the United States and New
Zealand had cooled since a decision in 1984 by then-Prime Minister
David Lange's government to only allow maritime visits by vessels
that verifiably carry no nuclear arms.
   Palmer, who was Lange's right-hand man in the previous Cabinet,
was elected prime minister a month ago after Lange resigned.
