<FIRST>r w PM-MinorityHealth     09-11 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minority Health,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Passing Healthy Lifestyles from One Generation to the Next</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major key to good health is good lifestyles
passed from parent to child, a top federal health official said
today.
   ``I urge you to return to your communities with the message that
a major component of the family's legacy ought to be the example of
lifestyle and personal behavior that, in today's world, can be the
keys to good health,'' said Dr. James O. Mason.
   ``How ... can a father who smokes teach his children to avoid
cigarettes, or a mother who abuses alcohol teach her children not to
drink?'' he asked.
   Mason, assistant secretary for health at the Department of Health
and Human Services, spoke at the opening session of the first
National Conference on Access and Health Care Financing Alternatives
for Minority Populations.
   The HHS Secretary, Dr. Louis Sullivan, was outlining
administration initiatiaves on minority health later at a hearing of
Sen. Edward Kennedy's health committee after joining the
Massachusetts Democrat at a news conference.
   Sullivan also was addressing the minority health conference on
its closing day Wednesday.
   Mason recited an array of statistics showing minorities in
general have poorer health and less access to care than whites.
   One thing that would help for all groups, he said, is strong
family involvement.
   ``Physical and mental well-being, education, perspective and a
sense of self all begin in and are nurtured by the family,'' he
said. ``In the family are the first examples of how we should
conduct ourselves.''
</TEXT>
