<FIRST>u a PM-BakkerTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0537 09-11 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bakker Trial, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0537,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witnesses Outline Lavish Spending By Bakker, Including Diamonds,
Boats</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with morning testimony. PICKS UP
4th graf pvs, `A former ...'; DELETES 7th graf pvs, `Bakker is...', now
redundant. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Bakker once bought a 12-carat, $22,000
raw diamond to provide for his retirement and took out insurance on
a series of ever-larger boats, witnesses said at the evangelist's
trial today.
   Ernest Perry, owner of Perry Jewelry Emporium in Charlotte, said
Bakker told him that the 12-carat stone, as well as an eight-carat
diamond Bakker purchased, would be ``a good investment for his
retirement.''
   Another witness, Carolyn Smith, of the Jerry Tuttle Insurance
agency in Charlotte, testified the Bakkers' homeowners policy valued
their personal property at $134,000 for the period June 1, 1986,
through June 1, 1987.
   The policy covered such things as a $45,000 diamond ring, a
$27,000 diamond ring and a $29,000 diamond bracelet, and the premium
was paid by PTL, she said.
   Ms. Smith said Jim and Tammy Bakker also insured successively
larger boats: in 1978, an 18-footer valued at $8,600, in 1984, a
19-footer valued at $10,000, and in 1986, a 22-footer valued at
$29,000.
   Bakker is charged with 24 counts of fraud and conspiracy and
faces 120 years and prison and more than $5 million in fines if
convicted. Prosecutors say he used nearly $4 million in ministry
funds to finance a lavish lifestyle.
   Mrs. Bakker, in an interview broadcast on the ``Donahue'' show
this morning, denied the couple did anything wrong. She has not been
charged in the case.
   ``We know inside we are not guilty,'' she said in an interview
with Phil Donahue taped in Charlotte on Friday and broadcast today.
``If I was guilty, I'd hide my head, but when you're not guilty
you're not guilty.''
   The growing evangelical empire, which included the Heritage USA
theme park near here as well as their nationally televised religious
program, ``got to where it didn't even feel a part of us,'' Mrs.
Bakker said. ``We almost couldn't catch up with it. ... I felt like
a little girl who didn't know where she was supposed to be.''
   A former top executive at the TV ministry was scheduled to
testify this week against Bakker. Until Richard Dortch pleaded
guilty Aug. 8, prosecutors were planning to try him with Bakker.
Dortch was sentenced to eight years in prison.
   In cross-examining other witnesses, Bakker's attorney, Harold
Bender, has sought to create an impression that Dortch directed some
of PTL's most excessive spending.
   Dortch, who was released from a Florida hospital last week after
five days for treatment of an undisclosed ailment, is expected to
testify that Bakker called the financial shots.
   Bender and co-counsel George T. Davis aren't saying whether
Bakker will take the stand, and neither is Bakker, who quit PTL in a
sex and money scandal in 1987.
   Also expected to testify this week against Bakker is former aide
James Taggart, who, with his brother, David, was convicted in July
of tax evasion and conspiracy over their use of PTL cash advances
for personal purchases.
   On Friday, David Taggart was sentenced to more than 18 years in
prison and James to more than 17 years.
   Mrs. Bakker will not testify, lawyers said.
</TEXT>
