<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Wise     09-11 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Wise,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Oilman Wise Dies At 89</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYLER, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Watson William Wise, a Texas oilman and
philanthropist who was appointed a United Nations delegate by
President Dwight D. Eisenhower, has died. He was 89.
   Wise died Saturday at Mother Francis Hospital, but officials
there would not release a cause of death.
   A native of Ohio, Wise graduated from Yale and moved in 1925 to
Texas, where he started Wise Operating Inc., Wise Drilling Inc. and
Watburn Oil Co. He later wrote three books about his world travels.
   Wise funded dialysis centers in several Texas cities, Paris and
Seoul in memory of his father, William A. Wise, who died of kidney
failure in 1946.
   In 1984, he donated the Watson W. Wise Medical Library at the
University of Texas Health Center at Tyler.
   Wise also funded the Watson W. and Emma Wise Cultural Arts Center
and Wise Auditorium at Tyler Junior College, where he served on the
board of trustees from 1950-70. He also donated a wing to a library
at Yale University.
   In 1958, President Eisenhower appointed Wise a delegate to the
United Nations' 13th General Assembly. He later served as special
counsel to NATO.
   Survivors include his wife, Emma Wise, of Tyler, a son, daughter
and several grandchildren.
   A funeral service is scheduled for Tuesday at First Presbyterian
Church.
</TEXT>
