<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--NewLake     09-11 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--New Lake,0148</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Lake Discovered In Siskiyou National Forest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRANTS PASS, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A landslide that sent 25,000 cubic yards
of rock tumbling into a gorge has caused the formation of a lake in
the Siskiyou National Forest.
   The unnamed lake apparently was formed last year and was
discovered three weeks ago by U.S. Forest Service surveyors.
   ``It's pretty impressive,'' said Galice Ranger District
hydrologist Patricia Carroll, who estimates the lake may be 40 to 50
feet deep and 2,000 feet long when Silver Creek is high.
   The lake is one mile downstream from Silver Falls and about 25
miles west of Grants Pass. It probably too small and shallow to
provide prime fish habitat. But Carroll and others think it can
become a fine recreation area. Nearby falls, rich vegetation and the
dramatic sheer rock and cliff formations make for striking scenery.
</TEXT>
