<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1310EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     09-11 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top-Ranking Guerrilla Leaders Return</HEAD>
<UNK>By HEIDI VON EGIDY_ ^Associated Press Writer_</UNK>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two top-ranking officials of the
South-West Africa People's Organization returned from exile in
Angola on Monday and were expected to be joined later in the week by
Sam Nujoma, president of the once-outlawed group.
   Secretary-General Andimba Toivo ya Toivo and National Chairman
David Meroro, accompanied by dozens of other officials from the
organization, arrived at the Windhoek airport on a flight from
Luanda.
   ``Home, sweet home,'' ya Toivo said after kissing the tarmac.
``It is very sweet to be back.''
   The group waged a 23-year bush war against South African rule of
Namibia. Late last year, South Africa agreed to grant independence
to Namibia, which it has ruled since World War I.
   As part of the transition to independence, elections are
scheduled in November for an assembly that will draft a constitution
for a new nation. SWAPO is favored to win the most seats in the
assembly.
   No independence date has been set, but it is likely to be early
next year.
   Registration for voting ends Friday, and Nujoma is scheduled to
end his 30 years of exile Thursday so he can participate in the
polls.
   Ya Toivo, considered the group's second-ranking official, was one
of its founders in the late 1950s and early 1960s.
   He was convicted of terrorism under South African laws in 1967
and served 17 years in South African prisons until his release in
1984. Ya Toivo, 65, returned briefly to neighboring Namibia, then
left under self-imposed exile.
   Meroro has been the organization's national chairman since 1964
and has lived outside Namibia since 1975.
</TEXT>
