<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1314EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NursingHomeDeaths     09-11 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nursing Home Deaths,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial Opens in Deaths At Nursing Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection began today in the
trial of a former nurse's aide accused of smothering five nursing
home patients in a pact with her lesbian lover.
   Circuit Judge Roman Snow rejected defense requests to move the
trial outside the county and to dismiss the charges based on a
private polygraph test.
   Gwendolyn Graham, 25, is accused of smothering five women
patients in 1987 during her overnight shift at Alpine Manor Nursing
Home in suburban Walker. She is charged with five counts of murder
and one of conspiracy and could be sentenced to life in prison.
   The key witness is expected to be her alleged accomplice and
former lover, Catherine Wood. Last week, she pleaded guilty to one
count each of murder and conspiracy. Other charges were dropped in
exchange for her testimony.
   In previous court appearances, Wood has said she and Graham
discussed killing as many as 20 patients. She described how Graham
chose patients whose poor condition would leave no signs of a
struggle and used a washcloth she carried in her back pocket to
suffocate them.
   Wood said Graham told her that killing the patients helped her
relieve tension. Wood, 27, said she agreed to go along with the
killings, sometimes acting as a lookout, because she hoped it would
bind her with her lover.
   ``She was always happy when one of them died,'' Wood testified.
   Wood also said that Graham took a souvenir from each victim _
including earrings, anklets and handkerchiefs _ and that the two had
planned to select victims whose initials spelled ``murder,'' but the
plan failed because some victims struggled too much.
   Graham's attorney said he believes Wood is a pathological liar
and made up the story to get even with Graham for leaving her for
another woman.
   Police began investigating late last year after Wood's ex-husband
reported she told him she took part in the slayings.
   The deaths of the five patients, ages 60 to 97, had been
attributed to natural causes and no autopsies were performed. Three
of the five were cremated; the two other bodies were exhumed, but
autopsies found no definitive evidence of suffocation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
