<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1322EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-UndergroundTesting     09-11 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Underground Testing,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Agency Looking Beyond Texas For Testings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Nuclear Agency says it will look
beyond Texas for a site to conduct deep-underground explosions,
after abandoning its preferred location at a Del Rio ranch, the
state's senators said Monday.
   After local residents complained the tests might affect the only
source of water in the border community, the DNA said last month it
would discontinue studying the Buck King Ranch site, but that it
would evaluate other sites in Texas.
   In a letter released today by Sens. Lloyd Bentsen and Phil Gramm,
the DNA's new director, Maj. Gen. Gerald G. Watson, said the
Pentagon agency has stopped all test drilling operations at the
site, is shutting down the drilling rig and has begun clean-up
operations.
   ``Currently, we are re-examining our geologic and hydrologic data
base outside Texas for the purpose of finding the next best site for
the program,'' Watson said in a letter dated Sept. 8.
   The Pentagon agency had spent two years before chosing the Buck
King Ranch for additional evaluation to determine its suitability
for the non-nuclear explosions. The tests are designed to simulate
the impact of nuclear blasts on subterranean missile silos and to
evaluate the hardness of U.S. and Soviet deep underground command
and control facilities.
   ``This is a good decision, easing our concerns about possible
damage to the water supply in an area where water is scarce and
responding to the strong community opposition,'' said Bentsen, a
Democrat.
   Gramm, a Republican, said he was ``delighted that the DNA has
reached a final decision to pack up and look elsewhere for a test
site. It's clear from the director's latest letter that the
unanimity of local opposition had a strong specific impact on the
DNA's decision.''
</TEXT>
