<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1323EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Inmates'Infection 1stLd-Writethru a0550 09-11 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inmates' Infection, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0550,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bacteria Afflicts Jail Inmates; Two Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with details of illnesses.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten Harris County Jail inmates remained
hospitalized Monday, eight with flu-like symptoms and two with the
same bacterial infection that has killed two other prisoners,
authorities said.
   The eight inmates' symptoms, which included fever, dizziness and
nausea, could be early signs of the same deadly bacteria or they may
just be indications of the flu or a mild infection, Ben Taub
Hospital spokeswoman Nora Shire said.
   One of the two inmates who has the bacterial infection was in
very critical condition, Ms. Shire said. He has a fever, congestion
and is on a respirator.
   Jail inmates say they have been in near panic since the outbreak
began last week, with guards reportedly shunning anyone with a runny
nose or other symptom of the pneumococcus bacteria infection.
   ``This thing is either going to kill us, or we're going to kill
each other,'' inmate Mike Reese told the Houston Chronicle. He was a
cellmate of one of the men who died of the illness Thursday.
   Preliminary autopsy results indicate the two dead men had
pneumococcus or pneumococcal sepsis, a bacterial infction that
affects the lungs.
   Neither of the men who died had a spleen and that is believed to
be a contributing factor in their deaths. Removal of the spleen,
which helps clean the blood, can impair the immune system.
   The inmate in critical condition also does not have a spleen,
said jail medical administrator Lanny Chopin.
   Chopin said county authorities have not found a common source of
the infection. The dead inmates were in separate cellblocks on the
ninth floor, officials said.
   At least two representatives of the federal Centers for Disease
Control were to fly to Houston to help investigate the illnesses,
Ms. Shire said.
</TEXT>
