<HEAD>Two Killed, 13 Injured in Train Collision</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New thruout to update death toll, add background on other train
crash. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two passenger trains collided head-on
Monday after being directed onto the same track, and two people were
killed and 13 were injured, railway officials said.
   The accident occurred near Willendorf, a town 31 miles south of
Vienna, said a railway spokesman. There was no word on how many
people were aboard the trains or how fast they were going when they
crashed.
   The driver of one of the trains was killed instantly, the
spokesman said, and a passenger died of her injuries at a hospital.
Nine of the injured were in serious condition.
   The railway said the crash was the result of human error because
one of the trains was mistakenly directed onto the track the other
was using.
   News reports said human error also was to blame for a crash Aug.
30 of two express trains that killed one man and injured 27 people
in Austria's Voralberg province.
