<FIRST>u a PM-TireFire 2ndLd-Writethru a0555 09-11 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tire Fire, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0555,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Huge Tire Pile Catches Fire; Could Burn For Days</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with hazards of burning tires.
PICKS UP 8th graf pvs, `An environmental ...'; SUBS last graf to ADD background
on EPA role.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ADOLPHE V. BERNOTAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DANVILLE, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pile of more than 1 million used tires
caught fire for the second time in five years and spewed acrid,
black smoke today.
   John Gifford, spokesman for the state Office of Emergency
Management, said it could take days or even weeks to put out the
blaze at the seven-acre dump.
   Gov. Judd Gregg this morning called the fire ``a disaster waiting
to happen, and it happened.''
   Another fire burned at the site for days in 1984, and state
officials later seized the dump in an attempt to clear it. The blaze
broke out as a company hired by the state in July was about to get
rid of the tires, said Gregg, who earlier this summer declared the
gargantuan pile ``a plague on Danville and the state.''
   About 175 firefighters from 48 communities removed tires from the
fire's path and dug trenches. About one-third of the pile was on
fire.
   The fire, whose cause had not been determined, broke out about
7:30 p.m. Sunday. At midmorning, flames were visible a mile away and
smoke could be seen from eight miles.
   About 50 people were evacuated from their homes Sunday and early
today, and several roads in the rural area 40 miles north of Boston
were closed.
   Amy Juchatz, a toxicologist in the state Division of Public
Health Services, said smoke from burning tires could contain harmful
lead and zinc, as well as chemicals that can cause cancer.
   An Environmental Protection Agency team was being rushed from New
Jersey to assist, Gifford said.
   The state sued Ernest Hunt, who began collecting the tires about
15 years ago, after the 1984 fire, and later seized control of the
dump from him.
   At one point, Hunt was declared financially unable to clean up
the dump, but he was later indicted on perjury charges stemming from
what he said during that hearing, authorities said. His whereabouts
are unknown, officials said.
   After seizing the dump, the state contracted with Integrated Tire
of Buffalo, N.Y., to shred the tires and ship them to Greece to fuel
a cement plant.
   The blaze was so severe that firefighters quit using water on it
this morning, because even at 2,500 gallons per minute, it vaporized
immediately.
   Instead, a hastily assembled fleet of 22 large trucks began
dumping 25-ton loads of dirt onto the fire from a nearby
sand-and-gravel pit.
   Fire Chief Bill Timmons said the dumping would continue for at
least a couple of days.
   Paul Groulx of EPA's regional office in Boston said $500,000 from
the agency's Superfund program was allocated this morning to help
pay for the firefighting because of the potential for contamination
of the air and ground.
</TEXT>
