<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1426EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NursingHomeDeaths     09-11 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nursing Home Deaths,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Selection Begins in Nursing Home Murder Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection began Monday in the
trial of a former nurse's aide charged with killing five nursing
home patients in a bizarre pact with her lesbian lover, who has
pleaded guilty.
   Gwendolyn Graham is charged with five counts of first-degree
murder for allegedly smothering the women at Alpine Manor Nursing
Home in suburban Walker. She also is charged with one count of
conspiracy to murder.
   Kent County Chief Circuit Judge Roman Snow denied defense motions
to move the trial to another county and to dismiss the charges based
on results of a private polygraph test.
   Prosecutors are basing most of their case on the confessions of
Graham's alleged accomplice and former live-in companion, Catherine
Wood.
   Wood pleaded guilty last week to one count each of second-degree
murder and conspiracy to commit murder. Two counts of first-degree
murder against her were dropped in exchange for her testimony
against Graham. Wood faces up to life in prison, with a chance of
parole in 10 years.
   Wood has said she and Graham discussed killing as many as 20
patients during their overnight shifts at Alpine Manor in 1987.
   Graham, 25, is accused of smothering the victims with washcloths,
choosing those patients whose poor physical condition would leave no
signs of a struggle. Almost all of the patients were bedridden, and
many suffered from Alzheimer's disease.
   Wood, 27, said Graham told her killing the patients helped her
relieve stress. She said she agreed to go along with the killings,
sometimes acting as a lookout, because she hoped it would bind their
love.
   Graham and Wood allegedly took souvenirs from each victim _
including earrings and handkerchiefs _ and had planned to spell
M-U-R-D-E-R with the victims' initials. That plan failed because
some targeted victims struggled too much, Wood testified.
   Graham's attorney, James Piazza, has said he believes Wood made
up the story to get even with Graham for leaving her. Graham left
Michigan for her hometown of Tyler, Texas, after the two split up in
July 1987.
   Walker police began investigating late last year after Wood's
ex-husband told them his former wife had confessed to her part in
the slayings.
   When the five patients died from Jan. 18 to April 7, 1987, their
deaths were listed as natural and no autopsies were performed. Three
of the alleged victims were cremated; the two other bodies were
exhumed, but autopsies revealed no definitive evidence of
suffocation.
   Nursing home administrators had given both employees high marks
and Wood had been promoted to nursing aide supervisor. Both women
quit their jobs before the investigation began.
   The trial is expected to last about two weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
