<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1411EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Bush-Drugs 3rdLd-Writethru a0590 09-11 0967</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Drugs, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0590,950</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Says No Combat Role Envisioned in Latin America War on
Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs pvs grafs 2-4, Presidential spokesman, with new grafs 2-10
DeConcini comments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A secret directive signed by President Bush
dealing with U.S. military involvement in the war on drugs does not
envision using U.S. forces in any combat role in Latin America, the
White House said today.
   A member of the Senate Intelligence Committee, however, said the
military will provide protection to U.S. drug enforcement agents and
other law enforcement officials operating in such nations as Bolivia
and Peru.
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater confirmed Bush
recently signed a directive outlining the goals and limits of
military involvement in the war on drugs, but he said it does not
authorize the use of U.S. troops in combat.
   Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., said the directive authorizes the
military ``to be physically involved with units in the field where
we have been invited to have our law enforcement people.''
   He said such protection is designed to prevent incidents similar
to the torture and murder of U.S. drug agent Enrique Camarena, in
Guadalajara, Mexico, in Febuary 1985.
   ``We can't afford another Camarena,'' said DeConcini, a member of
the intelligence committee.
   Presidential spokesman Fitzwater also threw cold water on a
statement by drug enforcement administrator John Lawn that the
administration is reconsidering whether to ban the sale of assault
weapons produced in the United States.
   ``We aren't aware of any reconsideration,'' Fitzwater said. ``By
that I mean there's none in the White House. ... I know the White
House position has been given to me by the highest authorities.
   Fitzwater declined to give details of the secret directive on the
drug war.
   ``These documents do not contemplate the use of troops,''
Fitzwater said.
   However, he refused to disclose what the documents actually
authorize. Asked if the directive left the door open for the use of
troops under some conditions, Fitzwater said, ``I really can't go
beyond that it doesn't contemplate the use of troops. I think the
interpretation can fairly be made that it doesn't authorize troops,
either.
   ``We can argue about words, we can argue semantics, but the fact
is, it doesn't not contemplate the use of troops,'' he said.
   Fitzwater said the approximately 30 U.S. advisers involved in
anti-drug efforts in Colombia do have the right to defend
themselves. He said that is the standard policy for U.S. troops
anywhere in the world.
   ``They are there. There is a risk. Colombia is a very dangerous
place to be these days,'' Fitzwater said.
   Bush sent security advisers to Colombia as part of a $65 million
package designed to help that nation fight cocaine, and he said last
Tuesday that an additional $261 million in security aid could go to
Colombia, Peru and Bolivia for the drug war.
   Drug czar William J. Bennett said in a televised interview Sunday
that Bush is willing to send Special Forces advisers to the Andean
nations.
   ``There is no plan for any Special Forces to accompany troops in
Peru or Bolivia into combat missions,'' Bennett said in the ABC-TV
program ``This Week with David Brinkley.''
   ``That is not in the plan. ... There is no such plan,'' Bennett
said.
   Bennett said ``we see now in Colombia the presence of American
trainers working with the Colombians, giving them advice, training
them on equipment. This is the kind of thing we would anticipate if
Peru and Bolivia take the steps.''
   On the issue of assault rifles, the administration has banned
their import, but Bush has said he opposes a ban on domestic weapons.
   Lawn, appearing on CBS' ``Face the Nation,'' was asked about
Colombia's request that the United States stem the flow of U.S.-made
assault weapons to that country.
   ``We must look now at our own procedures here in the United
States,'' Lawn said. ``...I believe it is something that is under
review, and certainly citizens feel very strongly about the gun
issue ... We in the law enforcement community feel very strongly
when we're out there on the firing line, and our view isn't always
necessarily the view of our leaders.''
   About two dozen members of the U.S. Special Forces based in
Panama have been rotating into Bolivia's Chapare Valley, training
anti-narcotics police there, but they have been barred from patrols.
   The Washington Post, in its Sunday editions, said the directive
would allow the advisers to accompany Bolivian drug forces on
patrol. However, an administration source said ``the military is not
allowed to go out into the jungle on patrol. That is the way it has
been and the way it remains.''
   The Post report quoted an unidentified senior administration
official as saying that ``several hundred'' U.S. military advisers
could be sent to the three nations under the ``Andean initiative''
announced by Bush.
   Bennett said the military advisers in Colombia, although they
were barred from combat, were in ``a dangerous environment. They are
not going to seek out combat or conflict. And we just all hope that
nothing befalls them.''
   A possible expanded U.S. military role in Latin America received
mixed reviews from Democrats in Congress.
   ``It could be a good idea,'' said Sen. Joseph R. Biden, D-Del.,
who has emerged as Democratic spokesman on Bush's plan for a war on
drugs. ``I can say that I do not dismiss the notion of using U.S.
troops in certain circumstances in the Andean effort.''
   But Rep. Charles B. Rangel, a Democrat who represents New York
City's Harlem section, which is plagued by drug-related violence,
said, ``It outrages me to think that every time there is an
international problem, we have to talk about the introduction of
American troops.'' Biden and Rangel appeared on the ABC-TV program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
