<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1441EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Mrs.Bush-Literacy     09-11 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mrs. Bush-Literacy,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mrs. Bush Struggles With Computer Literacy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush, long a champion of efforts to
teach adults to read, confessed Monday that she's struggling to
overcome a literacy problem of her own _ computer literacy, that is.
   At a White House fete for participants in the Second National
Adult Literacy Congress, the first lady told the dozens of adult
learners that she understands what they're going through.
   She said that this summer, on the theory that ``you never stop
learning in life ... I decided to take up the computer.''
   ``That's just like taking up literacy,'' she said. ``They speak a
language I don't know. There seems to be some code in there I don't
understand. And young people say to me, `Oh, that's easy.'''
   The 150 people in the East Room of the White House laughed.
   The weekend conference attracted literacy experts and adult
students.
   Mrs. Bush said she hadn't mastered the computer, but when she
gets ``really discouraged'' she remembers ``there are a lot of
people out there trying to learn how to read and it's just as
complicated for them, and they're learning so I guess I can.''
   For Estel Sizemore, 58, a great-grandfather who sought help three
years ago, it was his second visit to the White House in less than a
year. The one-time sheet-metal worker was among those honored at a
November ceremony.
   Sizemore, a farmer's son who never got beyond first grade,
attends one-on-one classes at Scarlet Oaks High School in Cincinnati.
   ``It's all free,'' Sizemore said. ``It's embarrassing to get
there, but once you get inside the door, it's like a family.''
   Judy Sawyer, 48, of Pringle, S.D., didn't know the meaning of
``literacy'' until last year when she sought help in Custer, S.D.
   Mrs. Sawyer, a homemaker who has worked as a truck driver and
waitress, said she never learned to read growing up in Moab, Utah.
   ``I finished the ninth grade. How I got there I'll never know,''
said Mrs. Sawyer, who now reads at nearly a fifth-grade level.
   Her goal is to get a high school equivalency diploma and become a
school volunteer to ``find the small children that are having the
hard time and help them so they won't have to go through what I went
through.''
   ``This is like a miracle,'' she said, looking around the
glittering ballroom. ``I used to feel like I was the dumbest thing
that ever walked, that I couldn't do anything.
   ``I didn't know there was so many like me. I thought I was the
only one in the world like me. It felt so good not to be dumb no
more.''
   The conference was sponsored by Laubach Literacy Action, Literacy
Volunteers of America, the International Reading Association and
other groups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
