<FIRST>u a PM-Martinez 3rdLd-Writethru a0546 09-11 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Martinez, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0546,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reputed Drug Financier Jailed Without Bail</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with possible sentence, no further
hearings, gag order. PICKS UP 13th graf pvs, `Weldon Kennedy ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Medellin Trial, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The reputed finance chief of the Medellin cocaine
cartel pleaded innocent to money laundering today and was jailed
without bond after prosecutors argued he might flee the country no
matter how high his bail.
   Eduardo Martinez Romero _ the first of Colombia's
``Extraditables'' to be brought to the United States for trial _
entered the plea before U.S. Magistrate Joel M. Feldman. Martinez,
36, was extradited under heavy guard on Thursday.
   ``Colombia is hardly the only country in the world where Mr.
Martinez could live, and live quite comfortably with the millions of
dollars to which he has access,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Wilmer
Parker III said in arguing against bail.
   Martinez is accused of helping launder $1.2 billion in drug
profits through U.S. banks for the Medellin cartel, which supplies
80 percent of the cocaine in the United States. It is based in the
Colombian city of Medellin.
   He is the first suspect extradited to the United States in a drug
crackdown begun in Colombia last month. Martinez is among the
so-called ``Extraditables,'' a list of drug figures wanted in the
United States.
   Defense attorney Ed Garland said that Martinez, under an apparent
agreement between the U.S. and Colombian governments, could face 30
years in prison if convicted, the maximum under Colombian law. Under
U.S. law, the maximum would be life in prison and a $4 million fine.
   Garland and co-counsel Oscar Rodriguez of Miami told the
magistrate their client has a graduate degree in marketing, has been
married 15 years, has four children and has held legitimate jobs at
Medellin banks.
   ``He has never come to the United States other than to bring his
children to Disney World on a vacation,'' Rodriguez said.
   Garland asked the magistrate to put Martinez under house arrest.
He argued that Martinez was accused only of laundering drug money, a
``financial transaction'' not serious enough to keep him without
bail.
   But the magistrate disagreed. ``It is well recognized that money
is what oils the machine that allows these unlawful activities such
as cocaine distributing ... to go on,'' he said. ``It is a very
serious offense.''
   Rodriguez said Martinez is being held in solitary at an
undisclosed location. The hearing was postponed to today after
Martinez said last week that he speaks only Spanish and did not
fully understand the charges.
   The case was assigned to U.S. District William C. O'Kelley, who
imposed a gag order on lawyers on the case. Garland had complained
that American anti-drug hysteria might prevent a fair trial.
   No further proceedings were immediately scheduled.
   Weldon Kennedy, agent in charge of the FBI office in Atlanta, has
said agents are on ``an increased state of alert'' against any
retaliation from the cartel. Latin America's drug barons have
carried out bombings and shootings in Colombia in recent weeks.
   Drug traffickers are said to fear extradition to the United
States because they believe they will not be able to escape
conviction and prison.
   Martinez was indicted in March as a result of a 2{-year
investigation dubbed Operation Polar Cap. The investigation resulted
in charges against 127 people and two Latin American banks. Martinez
is reputed to be the cartel's coordinator of a complex, competitive
business that has laundered at least $15 billion.
   The Atlanta-based undercover operation used Drug Enforcement
Administration agents to act as Americans interested in laundering
cocaine profits from Colombia. Court documents said the agents had
an informant who provided details of cocaine and marijuana smuggling
from within the cartel's higher ranks.
   Martinez was arrested during the first weekend of Colombia
President Virgilio Barco's crackdown on drug traffickers. That
crackdown was triggered by the Aug. 18 assassination of a
presidential candidate who was a foe of the drug trade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
