<DOCNO> AP890911-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1522EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     09-11 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korean President Proposes Unification Steps With North</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C. W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo on Monday
proposed new steps toward North-South Korean reunification and said
he hoped a charter for a ``Korean Commonwealth'' could be signed by
next August by the long-divided and hostile sides.
   ``I hope that a South-North summit will take place as quickly as
possible to successfully launch joint efforts ... for opening an era
of full-fledged inter-Korean cooperation and unification,'' Roh said
in a televised address to the National Assembly.
   But, he added, ``the reality is that it will be impossible to
achieve unification overnight.'' He urged North Korea to ``abandon
its policy of unification through communization of the South.''
   Roh said he wants a charter for the commonwealth, an interim
stage for merging the two Koreas, signed by next August. He also
called for measures to build confidence and control arms in an
effort to end the arms race between North and South.
    There was no immediate response from the Communist North, and
South Korea's leading opposition group, the Party for Peace and
Democracy, said Roh's peace gesture failed to reflect the views of
all South Koreans, some of whom demand the removal of U.S. troops
from the South.
   The opposition party called for a ``detailed and active''
government role in easing military confrontation with North Korea.
   North Korea has demanded the withdrawal of U.S. forces stationed
in South Korea, contending American troops are a major obstacle to
unification talks.
   It has called for a confederation under which there would be one
Korea for military and diplomatic matters but each side would
maintain its own political and social system.
   Over the past several decades, unification talks have been held
on and off, but little progress has been made.
   In recent years, South Korean dissidents have called for stronger
efforts toward unification. They want free travel across the heavily
guarded border and the immediate withdrawal of the 43,000 American
troops in the South.
   A radical student, a dissident clergymen and an opposition
lawmaker are in jail for making unauthorized visits to the North.
   Roh's new proposal calls for interim governmental bodies equally
divided between the two Koreas, changing his earlier position that
the South should have a larger representation because it has twice
the population of the North.
   The first step in his plan calls for establishing a Korean
National Community, with the holding of a summit and the signing of
a National Community Charter.
   The second step would be formation of a ``Korean Commonwealth,''
made up of a council of presidents, a 20-member council of
ministers, a 100-member council of representatives and a joint
secretariat.
   The secretariat, perhaps stationed in a border ``Peace Zone,''
would help handle routine commonwealth business, with liaison
offices operating in the capitals of the two nations as
quasi-diplomatic missions, Roh said.
   In the final step, the commonwealth would draw up a constitution
and set up elections for a united nation, he said.
   Five years after Korea was divided in 1945, the North invaded the
South, starting the 1950-53 Korean War. A cease-fire ended the war,
but no peace treaty has been signed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
