<FIRST>r i AM-Refugees-EGermany     09-11 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees-EGermany,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Staying Home: East Germans Who Spurned Freedom Train Fear Crackdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By INGOMAR SCHWELZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germans expressed fear Monday that the mass
migration of thousands of their countrymen will mean more hardships
for the millions who stayed behind.
   ``I have this feeling that I have missed the last train to the
West,'' a worried student in East Berlin told The Associated Press.
   Other East Berliners, all speaking on condition their names not
be revealed, expressed the same fear.
   ``Somehow or another those up above (government officials) must
react,'' said a teacher.
   A pastor said conditions in East Germany would become
``unbearable'' if the hard-line Communist government decides to
close off its border with Hungary to stem any future flow of
refugees to the West.
   After Hungary's decision to allow all East Germans vacationing
there to go West, more than 2,000 East German refugees arrived in
West Germany on Monday and more were on their way.
   News reports say the final number of East Germans arriving from
Hungary could top 10,000.
   It was the first time a Warsaw Pact country had aided a mass
exodus of refugees from another East bloc nation.
   The refugees point to repression and the East German government's
staunch resistance to reforms as their reasons for leaving.
   The East German government on Monday angrily denounced Hungary's
actions.
   ``The Hungarian government has chosen to illegally allow German
Democratic Republic citizens (East Germans) to travel to the Federal
Republic (West Germany),'' state-run news media said.
   It said Hungary ``under the guise of humanitarianism is engaging
in organized smuggling of humans.''
   The criticism appeared in East Germany's Neues Deutschland and
Junge Welt newspapers and was broadcast on radio and television.
   Junge Welt, the East German Communist youth newspaper, also
charged that Western media were misinterpreting the defection of
East Germans ``as a judgment against socialism.''
   On Sunday, the Communist-run news agency ADN charged Hungary had
violated a 1969 agreement with East Germany that forbids allowing
each other's citizens from crossing their borders to go West without
official permission.
   Hungary is one of the most popular places for East German
tourists, especially since that East bloc country has been adopting
political reforms.
   East German citizens can easily cross into Hungary, but many are
denied the right to visit the West.
</TEXT>
