<FIRST>u p AM-PrimaryRdp Bjt   09-11 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Primary Rdp, Bjt,0748</SECOND>
<HEAD>Koch Battles for Survival; Candidates Vie for Wright, Coelho Seats</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY26</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the nation's longest-serving mayors face primary election
challenges Tuesday, and while Detroit's Coleman Young is expected to
glide into a November runoff, New York's Edward Koch is fighting for
his political life.
   In Texas and California, voters will fill House seats left vacant
by the resignations of two tainted but popular Democratic leaders,
Speaker Jim Wright and Majority Whip Tony Coelho.
   There also are mayoral primaries in Minneapolis and St. Paul,
Minn., Buffalo, N.Y., and New Haven, Conn., among other places.
   Koch, who was written off as a political has-been a few months
ago, has battled back to within striking distance of his main
Democratic primary challenger, David Dinkins. Both men are out to
make history, Koch as the city's first four-term mayor and Dinkins
as its first black mayor.
   Their paths crossed Monday at a school dedication, where Koch
pulled Dinkins aside to call for a unity rally on Wednesday, no
matter who wins.
   ``I think that's a nice gesture,'' said a smiling Dinkins. ``I
mean, he recognizes that the likelihood is that I'm going to
succeed, and he offers to help me, I think that's fine.''
   Koch, who thinks a big turnout of mainstream Democrats will carry
him to victory, said it was important for his party to work on
defeating Republican Rudolph Giuliani, the former federal prosecutor
who leads cosmetic heir Ronald Lauder in the GOP race.
   ``We gotta get started on Giuliani,'' Koch said. ``This guy's got
clay knees, and the reporters are only up to his ankles.''
   In both Texas and California, Democratic congressional candidates
are basking in the support of the disgraced congressmen they are
trying to succeed.
   Although Wright and Coelho resigned because of alleged ethics
violations, both remain popular in their old districts and have been
central figures in the special election campaigns to fill their
seats.
   Wright has campaigned for Fort Worth lawyer Pete Geren, a former
aide to Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas. The Republican candidate, Dr.
Bob Lanier, a television medical commentator, has countered with
endorsements from two other prominent Texans _ President Bush and
former Dallas Cowboys coach Tom Landry.
   Lanier said he initially worried that Wright's endorsement of
Geren would be a major factor in the race, but now believes ``it
hasn't been quite as much as we anticipated.''
   Still, he conceded that he's ``swimming upstream'' as a
Republican in a district with a long history of sending Democrats to
Congress.
   In California's San Joaquin Valley, Coelho has endorsed
Democratic state Assemblyman Gary Condit in a low-key race against
Republican Clare Berryhill, a former assemblyman and state
agriculture chief.
   Berryhill and Condit are considered the leading candidates in a
field of six. Unless one candidate gets more than 50 percent of the
vote, there will be a runoff between the top two vote-getters.
   In Detroit, Young is trying to brush off challenges to his bid
for a record fifth term in office.
   His challengers include Rep. John Conyers, a brash 12-term
Democratic congressman who says Young has been in office too long.
Conyers, who like Young is black, has benefited from the vocal
support of the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who exhorted a crowd on Monday to
``keep hope alive'' by voting for Conyers.
   A poll released Sunday showed Young well in front of the pack of
13 candidates, with Conyers running neck-and-neck with accountant
Tom Barrow for second place. The top two finishers advance to the
November general election.
   Nine candidates are battling to succeed St. Paul Mayor George
Latimer, who is quitting after 12 years in office to become a law
school dean. Across the river in Minneapolis, Mayor Don Fraser is
facing six challengers.
   The top two vote-getters in each city will advance to the Nov. 7
general election.
   Buffalo Mayor James Griffin is assured of appearing on the
November ballot. The maverick Democrat, who is being challenged by
two other candidates in the Democratic primary, is also running
unopposed for both the Republican and Conservative party nominations.
   In New Haven, state Sen. John Daniels is trying to become the
first black mayor of the mostly white Connecticut city. Daniels is
locked in a tough fight with John DeStefano Jr., the hand-picked
candidate of Mayor Biagio DiLieto, who is retiring.
</TEXT>
