<FIRST>r a AM-Frank-Bar     09-11 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Frank-Bar,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bar Official Says Review Of Complaint Against Congressman Would Be
Automatic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state agency that disciplines lawyers would
automatically review any complaint filed against U.S. Rep. Barney
Frank, who recently admitted paying a male prostitute for sex, an
official said Monday.
   But Daniel Klubock, bar counsel for the Commonwealth of
Massachusetts, refused to confirm or deny if a complaint against
Frank had been received.
   George Washington University Professor John F. Banzhaf III last
week said he had filed a complaint against Frank, D-Mass., with the
state's Board of Bar Overseers, which investigates complaints
against lawyers.
   Klubock said the board's proceedings are confidential. But
Klubock, who said his position is roughly similar to that of a
prosecutor with the board acting similar to a court, said his office
reviews all complaints.
   ``Our investigation can be limited to reading it and saying this
is nonsense,'' Klubock said, or it can evolve into a full-scale
investigation.
   He said the board, if it decides to take action against an
attorney, can issue a private reprimand itself. He said the most
severe disciplinary action, such as disbarment, is done by the state
Supreme Judicial Court on recommendation from the board.
   Frank has never practiced law and is listed as an inactive lawyer
by the board.
   Banzhaf has asked Frank to agree to a public hearing. ``He says
the matter should be cleared up,'' Banzhaf said.
   Frank himself has called for an investigation into the matter by
the House ethics committee, saying he wants to clear the public
record.
   Frank, who is homosexual, last month said he paid Stephen Gobie
for sexual services, then hired the man as his personal aide. Frank
said he did not know Gobie was running a prostitution service from
the congressman's Capitol Hill apartment. He said he fired Gobie in
1987 when he found out.
   Frank also said he wrote several letters to Gobie's probation
officer and used his congressional immunity to void Gobie's traffic
tickets.
</TEXT>
