<FIRST>r a AM-LionDeath     09-11 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lion Death,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mountain Lion Kills Youngster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVARO, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 5-year-old boy last seen riding his
tricycle near his home was killed by a mountain lion that was later
tracked down and killed, authorities said Monday.
   The body of Jake Gardipe was found Sunday night just 30 yards
from his home, said Missoula County Sheriff's Lt. Greg Hintz.
   Tracking dogs later found a female mountain lion nearby that was
then shot, said Rick Schoening, a game warden for the Montana
Department of Fish, Wildlife and Parks. The animal had blood in its
mouth and claws, he said.
   Jake was last seen at 3 p.m. Sunday, playing near his rural home
two miles north of the tiny community of Evaro in mountainous
western Montana. He was reported missing shortly before 7 p.m. and
his body was found a short time later.
   Fish and Wildlife officials for the Confederated Salish and
Kootenai Tribes, whose reservation boundary runs through Evaro,
joined Missoula County Search and Rescue members in looking for the
boy.
   Residents have spotted two mountain lions in the area recently
and reported that two dogs have been killed.
   Efforts were made Monday to catch the other lion, Hintz said.
   Two fatal lion attacks have been reported in recent years in
California, Kerry Murphy of the Wildlife Research Institute at
Yellowstone National Park said.
