<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1859EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     09-11 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Declare Cease-Fire for Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas said Monday
they will observe a cease-fire for 11 days to create a favorable
climate for peace talks with the government.
   The Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front said in a a
communique that the cease-fire, which it termed unilateral, would
begin at 12:01 a.m. Wednesday and end at midnight September 23.
   Representatives of the rebels and the government of President
Alfredo Cristiani, who took office June 1, are to meet in Mexico
City beginning Wednesday. The exchange will be the first peace
discussions between the government and the insurgents since October
1987.
   The FMLN is waging a nearly decade-old revolution against a
succession of U.S.-backed governments. An estimated 70,000 people
have been killed in the conflict.
   The rebels Thursday declared a halt to sabotage of the
electricity distribution system and the national telephone network.
They also suspended the use of land mines and booby traps.
   The guerrillas said Monday the cease-fire and suspension of
sabotage, along with the naming of a high-level rebel dialogue
comission and the acceptance of a venue outside El Salvador, are
clear indications of their good faith.
   ``But we note with concern that Mr. Cristiani and his government
are placing obstacles in the way of the upcoming meeting by opposing
the logical and necessary presence of international witnesses, a
moderator and national and international observers, and in so doing,
are trying to establish a closed dialogue,'' said the communique.
   The government has refused a rebel request that U.N.
representatives attend the talks, saying it is not yet time to
include international observers.
   The FMLN on Monday announced an eight-member delegation to the
talks headed by commanders Joaquin Villalobos and Schafik Jorge
Handal.
   Cristiani last week named a commission that includes two Cabinet
members. The president said he considers this week's sessions
preparatory and that the mechanism for proceeding with talks, rather
than substantive issues, will be discussed.
   ``Everything is developing normally for the meeting and the
reaching of agreements. You must remember that this is the beginning
of a series of conversations so you cannot expect to resolve a
10-year-old problem in a single meeting.''
   Monsignor Gregorio Rosa Chavez, auxiliary bishop of El Salvador,
was shuttling between Mexico City and El Salvador to work out
details of the talks with the two sides.
   He arrived in Mexico City in the early morning hours Monday, met
with the rebels and was to return to San Salvador in the afternoon,
carrying a message from the rebels to Cristiani, said Mercedes del
Carmen Letona, a rebel commander in Mexico City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
