<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1912EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DrugHearing 1stLd-Writethru a0581 09-11 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Hearing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0581,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witnesses Say Bush Anti-Drug Plan Inadequate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs at end to UPDATE with comments from Kohl, district
attorney.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's new anti-drug plan focuses too
much on lengthy prison terms and too little on treating drug
abusers, witnesses told a U.S. Senate hearing Monday.
   ``If I'd received (a stiffer penalty), I wouldn't be sitting
before you right now,'' said Michael Vann, a drug convict and now
director of a treatment center in Milwaukee. ``I wouldn't be a
productive citizen, I would still be in prison.''
   Vann, who spent 27 months in prison, testified before a field
hearing of the Senate Judiciary and Government Affairs committees,
conducted by Sen. Herbert Kohl, D-Wis.
   The hearing at Marquette University was the first since Bush
unveiled his $7.9 billion anti-drug plan last week, which allocates
about 30 percent toward treatment and prevention and 70 percent
toward law enforcement.
   Witnesses told the hearing tougher penalties would be ineffective
unless the demand for drugs disappears.
   ``No one has addressed why are Americans such heavy abusers,''
said Francine Fineberg, director of a home for mothers who are
addicted to drugs. ``We have to look at the moral fiber.''
   Vann and Queen Hyler, a Milwaukee activist whose son was severely
beaten by street gang members last year, agreed that drug abuse is a
product of poverty.
   ``It's hard to tell a 15-year-old boy living in a family of eight
to stay in school when he can go on the corner and get $1,000 a day
selling drugs,'' Ms. Hyler said.
   ``The U.S. is losing the war on drugs and will continue to lose
it as long as we have a policy that treats drug abuse as a crime,
not as a disease,'' she said. ``We must make the war on drugs a
moral crusade.''
   Vann, a recovering heroin addict, said he underwent 10 months of
treatment and education in prison and that the program _ more than
his punishment _ helped him change his ways.
   ``For many years I thought I only had potential to be a pimp or a
drug dealer,'' he said. ``I have status now because I'm doing
something positive.''
   Kohl noted that Bush's plan contains no additional funds for
treatment and education beyond what has been proposed by Congress.
   ``I'm afraid the president's plan falls short,'' he said. ``It
doesn't give us enough resources. It doesn't make wise spending
choices, and it doesn't focus on mobilizing and empowering
communities to fight the problem.''
   Milwaukee County District Attorney E. Michael McCann, who has
seen drug-related crime rise dramatically in Milwaukee over the past
year, also said the president's program is underfunded.
   ``I, for one, am willing to pay higher taxes to fully support the
programs needed, not just to fight the war, but to win the war on
drugs,'' McCann said.
</TEXT>
