<FIRST>r w AM-US-Cambodia     09-11 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cambodia,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Calls for Strenghtening Cambodian Anti-Communists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Monday that
non-communist forces in Cambodia should be strengthened as a means
of encouraging the pro-Vietnam government in Phnom Penh to agree to
a ``reasonable power sharing arrangement.''
   Spokesman Richard Boucher also said that a strenghtened
non-communist resistance would be better able to hold its own
against any attempt by the Khmer Rouge to seize unilateral control
in Cambodia.
   The Khmer Rouge is one of three rebel groups opposing the
Hanoi-backed government. The United State opposes a return to power
by the Khmer Rouge based on its 3{ years of repressive rule in the
late 1970s.
   Boucher declined to say whether the United States is attempting
to strengthen the two non-communist rebel groups with the help of
military aid.
   Congress has given the administration the green light to provide
these groups with military aid if it so wishes. But the chairman of
the House and Senate subcommittees on Asia last week said in
separate interviews with The Washington Post that the Bush
administration should hold off on any plan to provide such aid to
the non-communist resistance.
   Last Friday, Assistant Secretary of State Richard Solomon said
that to facilitate a solution in Cambodia, China should restrict its
military aid to the Khmer Rouge and the Soviet Union should curtail
its support for the Phnom Penh government.
   Cambodia has become a high priority issue for the administration
because of the pending completion later this month of the withdrawal
of the remaining Vietnamese troops in Cambodia.
   Efforts to reach agreement on a new Cambodian government once the
Vietnamese troops are gone have not prospered, raising the prospect
of a four-way armed conflict among government forces and the three
resistance groups.
</TEXT>
