<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1915EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TireFire     09-11 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tire Fire,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massive Tire Pile Catches Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CR5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ADOLPHE V. BERNOTAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DANVILLE, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plume of smoke from a huge pile of
burning used tires rose 1,000 feet into the air Monday and was
visible 25 miles away, and firefighters dumped tons of dirt to
smother the flames.
   ``We cannot put this thing out today,'' said David Tordoff of the
federal Environmental Protection Agency. ``We can suppress it and
then in a few days put it out.''
   Tordoff estimated that about 2{ acres of the 7-acre pile of tires
about 30 to 40 feet deep was on fire, the second fire in five years.
   William Toland, the state fire marshal, said the cause of the
fire was undetermined. ``It was out of control right from the
beginning,'' he said.
   Tordoff said the fire's heat controlled the firefighters' methods.
   ``We switched from water because even at 2,500 gallons a minute
the water was vaporizing,'' Tordoff said. ``Instead, we will smother
it.''
   About 200 firefighters from 48 communities cleared tires from the
path of flames and dumped water, then dirt, on the fire.
   By mid-morning, 22 large trucks began dumping 25-ton loads of
dirt onto the fire from a nearby sand and gravel pit. Danville Fire
Chief Bill Timmons estimated that the dumping would continue for at
least a couple of days.
   Tordoff said his agency earmarked an emergency $500,000 from the
hazardous waste Superfund for the effort.
   The dump is at the sparsely populated junction of three rural
southeastern New Hampshire towns _ Danville, Kingston and Hampstead
_ about 40 miles north of Boston.
   Soon after the fire broke out Sunday night, neighbors said flames
reached up to 40 feet and could be seen 1{ miles away.
   At daybreak Monday, the smoke could be seen in Massachusetts
communities 25 miles away.
   About 35 people living within a half-mile of the dump were
evacuated and took shelter at a church, with an additional dozen
residents staying with friends and relatives, authorities said.
Several nearby roads were closed.
   Tordoff said EPA scientists were monitoring the air and
underground water near the site for possible harmful contaminants
from the fire.
   The dump was the scene of a spectacular fire that burned for
weeks in 1984.
   Ironically, Gov. Judd Gregg in July had announced that the state
had contracted with a Buffalo, N.Y., firm to remove the tires.
   ``It was a disaster waiting to happen, and it happened,'' Gregg
said.
   Gregg said he hoped Integrated Tire of Buffalo could begin
removing tires in two weeks and shredding them to make fuel for a
cement plant in Greece.
   Ernest Hunt, who began collecting the tires about 15 years ago,
was sued by the state after the 1984 fire, but was declared
financially unable to clean up the dump, the state attorney
general's office said. The state seized control of the dump. Hunt's
present location is unknown.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
