<FIRST>r a AM-People-Folse     09-11 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Folse,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gumbah or Gumbo: It Was a Hit at the Vatican</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DONALDSONVILLE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Folse, the Cajun chef who
prepared a Vatican state dinner last week for Roman Catholic bishops
and cardinals, says he plans to send the pope a monthly bucket of
seafood gumbo.
   ``To be able to stand up face to face with the Holy Father and
discuss gumbo, there's no topping that. Then to send him a gallon of
gumbo a month!'' Folse said after his return to Louisiana.
   ``Here's a guy from Poland running the Vatican and he loves
seafood gumbo from Louisiana,'' Folse said. ``Gumbah, that's what he
called it.''
   Folse said Pope John Paul II did not attend Wednesday's dinner,
but he said he met the pope during a private audience.
   He and Ed LeBlanc, executive chef at Lafitte's Landing Restaurant
in Donaldsonville, prepared the meal for 90 church officials of
gumbo, catfish, alligator sausage, grilled duck and some other Cajun
originals.
   ``When you're planning a menu like this, you try to plan
something indicative of Louisiana and something to make people say,
`Gee, I've never heard of something like this,''' Folse said. ``All
of a sudden you've got people from all over the world eating
alligator and loving it.''
   The food was shipped from Louisiana, with help from the State
Department because the Italian government usually blocks imports of
alligator and pork.
   It was not Folse's first trip as ambassador of Cajun food. He
went to Moscow for the summit not long before President Reagan left
office.
</TEXT>
