<FIRST>r w AM-Democrats-Taxes     09-11 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democrats-Taxes,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democratic Chairman Urges Caution on Taxes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic National Chairman Ronald H. Brown,
saying ``let's not lead with our chin,'' told Democrats Monday they
should decide on their goals before talking about raising taxes.
   Brown spoke at a one-day conference called by a group of
Democratic political consultants to discuss ways to win the White
House in 1992.
   ``When we entangle ourselves in talk about taxes before we lay
out clear long-term goals and objectives, we dampen the
public-spirited response of Americans who want to believe that we
can act together to make a difference,'' Brown said.
   ``In fighting with the president for our vision of America's
future, let's not lead with our chin,'' he said.
   President Bush, who has persistently vowed not to raise taxes,
said last week that no tax increase is needed to finance his war on
drugs.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the House Ways and
Means Committee, said that ``unless the president supports the tax
increases that will be necessary to fight this war, the drug dealers
are going to win.''
   Brown also touched on remarks by Molly Yard, president of the
National Organization for Women, who has raised the possibility of
supporting a third party in pressing for abortion rights and other
women's issues.
   ``We are the party that believes women should make their own
choice when it comes to reproduction,'' he said. ``We believe that
government should protect the right of a woman to make that choice
herself. That's a clear contrast between our parties, and one that I
intend to underscore as our chairman.''
   ``But we also tolerate diversity of opinion, especially on
matters that are so morally complex,'' he said. ``I'm not willing to
let those on the fringe of this debate define the Democrat party's
center of gravity. If Molly Yard doubts the commitment and integrity
of our party on the issue of choice, if she insists that every
Democrat toe her line to every last detail, then maybe we'll have to
win this one without her.''
   Brown urged Democrats to ``starting preaching the Democratic
gospel'' by calling for ``a newly vigorous public spirit,'' but
added that ``programmatic liberalism is not the gyroscope that
guides the national Democratic Party.''
   He said rank-and-file Democrats ``believe that the New Deal
shaped our history and message as Democrats over four decades _ but
now they are ready for something more.''
</TEXT>
