<FIRST>r i AM-DrugConference     09-11 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Conference,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Nations Anti-Drug Conference Opens</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<UNK>By VIOREL URMA_ ^Associated Press Writer_</UNK>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. conference on strategies and
preventive measures against drug dealing opened Monday with
delegates calling the anti-cocaine war launched by the Colombian
government an ``act of immense courage.''
   ``With worldwide traffic in drugs now second only to that in
armaments, we are forced to face the sobering fact that humankind is
predominantly engaged in the commerce of self-destruction,''
Margaret J. Anstee, director-general of the U.N. Office in Vienna,
said in an opening statement.
   Praising the recent offensive unleashed by the government of
Colombia against cocaine producers, she said, ``The Colombian
government has been faced with a stark choice: it had either to
declare an all-out war on the traffickers, or, in effect, to
surrender.
   ``In an act of immense courage it has unequivocally chosen the
former course and by so doing has earned itself a place in the
history of what has become, for all of us, a world against drugs,''
Ms. Anstee told delegates.
   ``If Colombia were to lose this war, we should all be lost.''
   Colombia is represented at the five-day conference by a
three-member delegation headed by Miguel Antonio Gomez Padilla,
director-general of national police.
   The conference, attended by top government and law enforcement
officials from about 100 countries, is to help police and
enforcement officials formulate new measures against drug
traffickers and addicts.
   ``It is patently clear that there are no simple solutions to drug
abuse control problems. But that emphatically does not mean that
there are no solutions, that all we can do is surrender,'' Ms.
Anstee said.
   ``We must fight and we must win. The cost will be high. But the
cost of surrender would be a catastrophe,'' she said.
   Statistics scheduled to be presented at the conference indicate
drug seizures rose in 1988.
   Opiate and morphine seizures soared by 78 percent and 104 percent
respectively, while heroin and cocaine seizures steadily increased,
the United Nations said in a press release.
   The delegates will examine special law enforcement techniques
against drug abuse and illicit trafficking, with emphasis on
detection, investigation, search and seizure techniques.
   The meeting will also try to identify ways of enhancing law
enforcement effectiveness in seizing drugs, arresting drug offenders
and breaking up criminal syndicates.
</TEXT>
