<FIRST>r i AM-Refugees-Kohl     09-11 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees-Kohl,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chancellor Calls on West Germans to Welcome Refugees</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<UNK>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS_ ^Associated Press Writer_</UNK>
<DATELINE>BREMEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl appealed
Monday for a friendly welcome to thousands of East German refugees
pouring into West Germany and said murmurs of discontent in the
country were ignorant and shortsighted.
   ``We in West Germany have been able to live on the sunny side of
German history over the past 40 years,'' Kohl said in a speech at
the national convention of the Christian Democratic Union. ``We have
no right to resist the search for personal happiness of our
countrymen from East Germany.''
   The dramatic opening of the Hungary-Austria border to East German
refugees has not found total approval in West Germany, where many
allege that migrants are more in search of better economic prospects
than freedom from political persecution.
   Kohl dismissed such complaints as ``ignorant bar banter.''
   ``They don't see that these people have left their homes, their
jobs, their friends and their loved ones in order to live here,'' he
said. ``How great the oppression must be for them to give up
everything.''
   At least 2,000 East Germans poured into Bavaria, in West Germany,
from Austria after Hungary opened its border to the West at midnight
Sunday. The number of emigres from East Germany is expected to reach
100,000 by the end of the year.
   East Germans, as well as ethnic Germans from other nations, are
entitled to immediate West German citizenship and social security
under the 1949 constitution that also sets as a goal the eventual
reunification of East and West Germany.
   Kohl said the flow of East Germans to the West is testimony that
the dream of a unified Germany has not died in the Communist state.
   ``The opposite is the case,'' Kohl said. ``Precisely among these
young people is the dream of a common freedom for all Germans kept
alive. And this is a reminder to us in West Germany that our
prosperity cannot be allowed to drag on our hearts.''
   ``Unity, justice and freedom for the German fatherland,'' Kohl
declared. ``That is not an outmoded slogan, but one that belongs to
the future.''
</TEXT>
