<FIRST>r p AM-NYCPolitics     09-11 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NYC Politics,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Handshake, Pledge by Mayor And Leading Opponent</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Primary Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the eve of the closest mayoral primary in 12
years, Mayor Edward I. Koch crossed paths Monday with rival
Democratic candidate David Dinkins and they pledged their mutual
support no matter who wins.
   They also agreed on a unity rally Wednesday for the winner of
Tuesday's Democratic primary.
   ``I think that's a nice gesture,'' said Dinkins, the Manhattan
borough president. ``I mean, he recognizes that the likelihood is
that I'm going to succeed, and he offers to help me, I think that's
fine.''
   Koch _ who said a big turnout would carry him to victory _ said
it was important for the party to work on defeating Republican
front-runner Rudolph Giuliani in the November general election.
   ``We gotta get started on Giuliani,'' Koch said. ``This guy's got
clay knees, and the reporters are only up to his ankles.''
   A WABC-Daily News poll conducted Saturday and Sunday found
Dinkins supported by 50 percent of likely Democratic voters and Koch
by 43 percent, with a margin of error of six points. The other two
Democratic mayoral candidates, city Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin
and former transit chief Richard Ravitch, are stalled in single
digits.
   ``We have never dropped _ save maybe a point here or there _ but
we have gone constantly upward,'' Dinkins said. ``It seems to
indicate a solidifying of support.''
   But turnout, considered crucial in this race, is difficult to
predict in primaries.
   ``I'm No. 2,'' Koch said at a lunchtime rally. ```Mayday' is a
signal of distress for those who are nautically minded.
   ``I'm saying to everybody who understands that expression, I need
you. Come out tomorrow. Vote for me. Mayday! Mayday!''
   Koch hasn't faced a battle like this since 1977, when he won the
office after a close primary, followed by runoff and general
election races against Mario Cuomo, now the governor. Koch handily
won his primaries in 1981 and 1985.
   ``My supporters are in the tradition of Hubert Humphrey and Harry
Truman, and they don't normally come out in primaries, they come out
in general elections,'' Koch said at a school dedication. ``So if I
can get them to come out in the primary with a large turnout, I
believe I'll win.''
   Dinkins, who enjoys extensive labor support, said: ``We recognize
that we are, at worst, even. And if that be true, then what I think
to be a superior field operation should win for us.''
   The federal Justice Department will have 92 observers monitoring
voting to ensure that minority citizens _ notably Hispanics _ are
not denied the right to vote.
</TEXT>
