<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1903EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-Papandreou     09-11 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Papandreou,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Proposes Former Premier Go Before Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A committee investigating allegations that
former Premier Andreas Papandreou was involved in widespread
wiretapping while in office proposed Monday that the case be given
to a special court for possible prosecution.
   The parliamentary committee said in a report that Papandreou
``willfully instigated through national intelligence chief Costas
Tsimas and intelligence service employees ... the decision to commit
illegal acts and carry out the tapping of telephones,'' committee
chairman Theodoros Anagnostopoulos told reporters.
   Anagnostopoulos said the committee proposal called also for
Tsimas, who is now a member of the European Parliament, to go before
the special court.
   Legislators are due to debate the committee's proposal next week.
If they accept it, the former premier will be sent before the
special high court.
   The special court consists of the Supreme Court president and 12
Supreme Court judges. It would be given the task of conducting a
further investigation and formally trying Papandreou and Tsimas if
it decides to indict them.
   Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist Movement, or PASOK, was
succeeded by a conservative-leftist coalition in the June national
elections when no party won an outright majority. He was not present
when the committee's report was handed to Parliament President
Athanasios Tsaldaris.
   The 70-year-old veteran politician is accused of tapping the
telephones of his political opponents and party members from May
1987 to mid-April of this year.
   Anagnostopoulos said targets of the wiretapping included the
leader of the opposition New Democracy Party, Constantine
Mitsotakis; the Communist Party's offices; former President
Constantine Karamanlis; several newspaper publishers; journalists
and three of Papandreou's ministers and members of his security
guard.
   New Democracy and the Communist-led Coalition of the Left and
Progress formed an alliance after the June elections vowing to bring
to trial those accused of scandals in the former administration.
   In a memorandum to the investigating committee last week,
Papandreou questioned the legality of the probe and denied the
allegations.
   The five PASOK deputies on the 12-member committee released a
statement Monday saying the charges against Papandreou ``are totally
unclear and prefabricated.''
   The PASOK deputies said the intelligence service had always
tapped telephones for national security but that no witnesses had
presented any evidence Papandreou was aware of illegalities possibly
committed by the intelligence service.
   Another committee is investigating Papandreou and four of his
former ministers in connection with an alleged $210 million
embezzlement of the Bank of Crete. It is expected to present its
findings to Parliament on Sept. 14.
</TEXT>
