<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1937EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;LWithdrawals     09-11 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;L Withdrawals,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>July Outflow Smallest in 9 Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Net deposit withdrawals at the nation's thrift
institutions fell to a nine-month low of $183 million in July, the
government said Monday.
   The outflow was the smallest since October and followed a $4.6
billion withdrawal in June.
   The Office of Thrift Supervision attributed the decreased outflow
to competitive deposit rates and growing public assurance following
passage earlier in the summer of the new savings and loan law, which
includes $50 billion for the industry over the next 26 months.
   ``The moderation in deposit outflows reflected a further
narrowing in the spread between deposit rates offered by thrifts and
their non-depository competition, as well as less concern about
thrifts following enactment of FIRREA (Financial Institutions
Reform, Recovery and Enforcement Act),'' said James Barth, OTS chief
economist.
   Until passage of the new law, the OTS was the Federal Home Loan
Bank Board.
   The OTS had attributed the June outflow to intentional shrinkage
as thrifts prepared to meet the new law's tough new capital rule.
   Roughly one in four of the nation's 2,933 S&amp;Ls do not meet the
new standard _ $1.50 in tangible capital for every $100 in lending _
which becomes effective in three months. The only way thrifts that
cannot attract new capital can comply is to sell off assets such as
loans and pay off liabilities such as deposits.
   Barth said S&amp;Ls in July reduced their assets by $7 billion, a
monthly total exceeded only by $7.6 billion in June and $8 billion
in January.
   Most of the July reduction was accounted for by a record $7.4
billion in mortgage holdings, including $7 billion in mortgage pool
securities, one of the most easily sold assets in a thrift portfolio.
   For the first seven months of the year, a net $39.8 billion have
flowed out of thrift accounts compared with an inflow of $11.5
billion in the first seven months of 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
