<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1939EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     09-11 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conference on Poverty Begins, New Tax Program Draws Complaints</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ A five-day National Conference on
Poverty began Monday, almost two weeks after the government decreed
unpopular tax measures that included raising the cost of imported
goods by 30 percent.
   Organized by the Ministry of Social Affairs, the conference drew
350 local delegates to discuss the causes of poverty in Haiti, one
of the world's poorest nations.
   About 80 percent of Haiti's nearly 6 million inhabitants live in
absolute poverty and there is 55 percent unemployment, according to
government figures.
   On August 29, the government cut tax deductions for home loans,
lowered the amount merchants must make before they have to pay a 10
percent value-added tax, and raised the declared value of imports by
nearly one-third.
   Politicians, labor leaders and local businessmen protested the
tax measures _ allegedly imposed by the International Monetary Fund
_ saying they would cut purchasing power and cause social upheaval.
   Some delegates said the conference, which hopes to provide
possible remedies to Haiti's grinding poverty, contradicts the
government's economic policy.
   ``The conference is pure demagoguery. The government is trying to
temper the people's discontent while it imposes its austerity
policy,'' said Sylvio Claude, leader of the Haitian Christian
Democrat Party.
   In July, the government decided to cut spending by 15 percent and
to control the flow of foreign currency. But a $60 million budget
deficit has accelerated depreciation of the national currency, the
gourde.
   The projected 1990 budget will be around $280 million, 75 percent
will go to pay government salaries and 13 percent to meet payments
on the $800 million national debt.
   A steady decline in agricultural and industrial production has
dramatically affected state revenue.
   In the meantime, the demand for imported goods has increased
while bureaucratic mismanagement and political instability have
dissuaded both foreign and local businessmen from investing in the
economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
