<FIRST>r w AM-Solicitor'sDebut     09-11 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Solicitor's Debut,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Solicitor General to Debut in Appellate Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kenneth W. Starr's courtroom debut as solicitor
general will take place before three appellate judges instead of the
Supreme Court, the usual forum for the government's chief legal
advocate, the Justice Department said Monday.
   Starr will make a rare appearance for a solicitor general in a
lower court this week when he argues a random drug testing case
before the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco, the
department said.
   He is scheduled on Friday to defend the Federal Aviation
Administration's random drug-testing order.
   An appearance by a solicitor general, whose primary job is to
represent the Justice Department before the high court, before a
circuit court of appeals is highly unusual, according to department
officials and court watchers who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The case involves an FAA order that by December the nation's
airlines devise and implement procedures to randomly test pilots,
flight attendants and ground crews for illegal drug use.
   The FAA rules are being challenged by airline employee unions,
who contend that the random drug testing is an unconstitutional
search. The unions also argue that the FAA violated administrative
law when it promulgated the regulations.
   The FAA order, issued last year, is part of the Reagan
administration's initiatives for a drug-free workplace. Random
drug-testing of certain groups of federal employees has been upheld
by federal appellate courts but the issue has not been decided by
the Supreme Court.
   The Bush administration is continuing the initiative.
   Starr declined to comment about his scheduled appearance in San
Francisco. But Justice Department spokesman Daniel Eramian said that
when Starr took office ``he told the staff it was his intention to
do more actual representation in the courtroom.''
   Starr had said this would would include appearances before
appellate courts because ``what was happening in the circuit courts
of appeal was very important,'' Eramian said.
   When the Supreme Court opens its fall term on Oct. 2, Starr is
scheduled to make his first high-court argument when he is to defend
contempt-of-court fines against four Yonkers, N.Y., city councilmen
for defying a court order to adopt a housing desegregation plan.
</TEXT>
