<FIRST>r w AM-FamilyPlanning     09-11 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Family Planning,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Schroeder Pushes Birth Control Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., said Monday
that Congress can quell the fury that surrounds the abortion issue
on both sides by funding birth control research.
   ``If you had safe available family planning, the abortion issue
would almost be moot,'' Schroeder said in a speech to the Woman's
National Democratic Club.
   The nine-term congresswoman, who began her law career as counsel
to the Rocky Mountain Planned Parenthood chapter, has introduced two
bills that would give a federal push to birth control and fertility
research and development.
   The legislation is co-sponsored by Rep. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine.
   One bill is a resolution that ``expresses the sense of Congress
that the United States should make birth control and fertility
research, development and education a national priority'' by calling
for creation of population centers to do such research, she said.
   The other measure would amend the Public Health Service Act to
provide for the development and operation of three birth control
research centers and two fertility research centers, emphasizing
clinical study of new drugs and devices.
   The bill also contains a grant and loan repayment program
designed to attract scientists to work at the centers.
   It authorizes funds for five years for a total of $78 million.
   Schroeder assailed the Republican administrations of the last
nine years for working against family planning internationally.
   She pointed out that U.S. policy established by President Nixon
tied U.S. foreign aid to birth control programs in the applicant
country. But under President Reagan it was changed to oppose U.S.
involvement in family planning in other nations.
   ``In the last decade only Iran and the United States have been
marching backward on family planning,'' said Schroeder.
</TEXT>
