<FIRST>r w AM-Poindexter     09-11 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poindexter,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Says Poindexter May be Entitled to Certain White House Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge said Monday that John
Poindexter is entitled to any documents that might show former
President Reagan and President Bush knew of the ex-national security
adviser's activities in the Iran-Contra scandal.
   U.S. District Judge Harold Greene directed Poindexter's attorneys
to explain to the court by next week how presidential and vice
presidential documents would corroborate his claims that Reagan and
Bush were aware of actions which later led to Poindexter's
indictment.
   ``Neither a president nor his papers are beyond the reach of the
law,'' Greene said.
   The judge ordered independent counsel Lawrence Walsh to file
court papers saying what responsibility, if any, he has to secure
presidential and vice presidential documents and turn them over to
Poindexter.
   Under indictment for allegedly covering up Oliver North's
assistance to the Nicaraguan Contras, Poindexter says he had no
motive to conceal North's and his own activities because Reagan
authorized them, leading Poindexter to believe they were legal.
   ``If these claims (of authorization by Reagan and knowledge by
Bush) are literally correct,'' said Greene, ``the documents which
would support them would be material to the preparation of
Poindexter's defense.''
   Poindexter ``worked directly for the former president ... met
with him on an almost daily basis; and the alleged violations
occurred while he was so employed,'' said the judge.
   Poindexter's lawyers have asserted that Reagan authorized
Poindexter's responses to congressional inquiries about North's
activities. Poindexter later was indicted for those responses, which
referred to letters written in 1985 by then-national security
adviser Robert McFarlane denying that the National Security Council
was supplying military advice or raising money for the Nicaraguan
Contras.
   McFarlane later pleaded guilty to withholding information from
Congress in connection with the letters.
   The judge said the court ``has a special obligation to act with
prudence and restraint'' in seeking documents, including personal
diaries and notes from the heads of the executive branch of
government.
   But he said that ``neither a president nor his papers are beyond
the reach of the law that requires the production or the giving of
evidence; and where a defendant in a criminal case needs that
evidence, this court will enforce his right to its production.''
   Greene noted that many of Reagan's records are in his personal
possession or with the National Archives and that access to them
might depend on the Presidential Records Act of 1978. The
independent counsel may not be responsible for producing documents
from a former president, noted the judge.
</TEXT>
