<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Treasury     09-11 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Treasury,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Praises Treasury Role in Fighting Drug Abuse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush helped the Department of the
Treasury observe its bicentennial Monday with a speech emphasizing
its current part in the war on drugs, not its historical role in
forging the American banking system.
   Bush, addressing a sun-baked crowd of 1,000 Treasury workers and
others, paid tribute to ``the long, illustrious history of your
institution.''
   It was exactly 200 years ago that Alexander Hamilton took the
oath of office as the first treasury secretary, presiding over a
department with six employees.
   Today it has 150,000, most of them helping collect taxes, but
others engaged in tasks from the president's protective Secret
Service detail to customs agents to overseeing the nation's savings
and loans.
   ``Treasury has been in some ways the birthplace of the federal
bureaucracy,'' said Bush, noting that the U.S. Postal Service, the
Public Health Service, the Coast Guard, the departments of Interior,
Commerce and Labor as well as the Office of Management and Budget
all were once part of Treasury's domain.
   Bush used the address on the Treasury portico overlooking the
White House to declare that he does not contemplate using ``American
armed forces in any combat role'' in the Andean nations where the
United States is supporting government efforts to break the drug
cartels.
   The president said Treasury ``is making an outstanding
contribution to our nation's fight against drugs.''
   He said the Customs Service's capabilities of interdicting drugs
``have never been better,'' and agents from the Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Fireams are ``on the front lines investigating the
violent gun-running organizations allied with the drug lords.''
   Bush said money laundering was ``another front in the battle,''
and he credited Treasury, the IRS and Customs with ``first-rate work
tracing the path of drug profits in the world's banking system.''
   He promised to ``track every lead that we receive from whatever
source to separate the drug barons from the drug money. ... We've
got to hit the drug lords where it counts. It's time to take the
profit out of the drug trade.''
   He also lauded Treasury's role in ``sustaining our long-running
economic expansion, restructuring our savings and loans'' and
helping solve the Third World's debt problems.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady said his department has
responded to different challenges throughout its history, from
printing the first paper currency in 1862 to help Abraham Lincoln
pay for the Civil War to current efforts to find ways ``to preserve
our standard of living by encouraging savings and long-term
investment.''
   The event was held in blistering 91-degree heat that caused at
least one spectator to faint. Bush began his remarks by saying, ``I
notice one lady just passed out and I hadn't even begun to speak
yet.''
   To mark the occasion in a more monetary way, the Treasury put
more than $1 billion in currency, gold and silver bullion on display
in its Cash Room for visitors to gape at.
</TEXT>
