<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Ligachev     09-11 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Ligachev,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ligachev Cleared of Corruption Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet prosecutor said Monday an investigation
has proved that corruption charges against Politburo member Yegor K.
Ligachev are untrue.
   The official news agency Tass quoted Deputy Prosecutor Vladimir
Kravtsev as saying the allegations that Ligachev accepted a bribe
were ``an attempted frame-up and an invention not supported by any
objective evidence.''
   The charges surfaced in May, when an investigator in the
prosecutor's office said in a televised debate among parliamentary
candidates that Ligachev's name came up in a probe of corruption in
the Central Asian republic of Uzbekistan.
   The investigator, Nikolai Ivanov, did not detail Ligachev's
involvement.
   The probe into the corruption charges against Ligachev has been
dropped, Kravtsev told Tass.
   According to Tass, former Uzbek Communist Party chief Inamzhon
Usmankhodzhayev initially claimed to have bribed Ligachev, ``but
later withdrew the testimony.''
   Usmankhodzhayev is under investigation in a sweeping corruption
probe involving high-level officials in Uzbekistan, Tass said.
   He named Ligachev under pressure from investigators and the
threat that his relatives would be arrested, Tass reported. Ivanov's
boss, investigator Telman Gdlyan, ordered Usmankhodzhayev to testify
that he bribed law enforcement officials and members of the party's
policy-making Central Committee, according to Tass.
   On May 15, Ligachev dismissed the accusations as slander and
provocation and asked for an investigation.
   Ivanov and Gdlyan have been pulled off the Uzbek case, which led
to the conviction of former President Leonid I. Brezhnev's
son-in-law, Yuri Churbanov, on corruption charges.
   Both investigators were elected to the new Soviet parliament, the
Congress of People's Deputies in spring balloting.
</TEXT>
