<HEAD>Soviets Condemn Campaign on German Refugees; British Praise Exodus</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with U.S., West German reax. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union came to the defense of its
embattled ally East Germany on Monday by condemning what it called a
campaign to spur illegal East German emigration.
   The United States, Britain and West Germany welcomed the exodus
Monday of thousands of East Germans from Hungary through Austria to
new homes in West Germany.
   In Washington, State Department deputy spokesman Richard Boucher
praised Hungary, which boldly opened its borders to the West in
defiance of a Warsaw Pact ally.
   ``We also commend Austria for its help and support and we admire
the efforts of (West Germany) to offer a home to fellow Germans
seeking freedom,'' Boucher said.
   The Soviet news agency Tass made the criticism in a commentary on
the historic exodus that followed the Hungarian government's
decision Sunday to allow all East Germans to leave for West Germany.
   ``A number of press bodies, television networks and radio of the
F.R.G. (Federal Republic of Germany) instigate G.D.R. (German
Democratic Republic) people to unlawful actions, while missions of
the Federal Republic abroad, in violation of generally recognized
norms of international law, assume protection of those persons and
supply them with West German documents,'' Tass said.
   Several hundred East Germans, seeking safe passage to the West,
are holed up in West Germany's embassy in Prague, Czechoslovakia.
   Tass said Western news outlets have been waging a ``tendentious
campaign'' based on the illegal departures of some East Germans.
   It was the first comment on the greatest flood of East German
refugees since 1961, the year the Berlin Wall halted the flow to the
West. State television, in its evening news broadcast ``Vremya,''
showed some of the refugees Monday.
   Tass said the campaign and ``propaganda hullabaloo'' were
conducted by those who have ``the absurd idea of `engulfing''' East
Germany.
   The commentary reiterated the Kremlin's loyalty to its East bloc
ally.
   East Germany ``is an inalienable part of the Warsaw Treaty'' and
``our true friend and ally,'' Tass said.
   Hungary's action marks the first time a Warsaw Pact country has
aided an exodus of refugees from an allied communist nation.
   Britain's foreign secretary, John Major, said Monday that the
thousands of East Germans left for the West because the government
failed to provide for its citizens' basic needs.
   ``The clearest conclusion we can draw from the backdrop of the
German refugees is the extent to which the East German government
has failed in the job it should have done over recent years to
provide a reasonable standard of living,'' said Major in an
interview with the Independent Television Network from Washington,
where he met with President Bush.
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, during a speech in Bremen,
said that until East Germany adopts reforms, West Germany will be
seen as a Mecca for unhappy East German citizens.
   Klaus Bolling, former head of the West German mission to East
Germany, said there was a danger the situation was overheating. He
told ITN that urgent reforms were need in East Germany but that they
were unlikely since he could not see a ``German version of (Soviet
President Mikhail S.) Gorbachev.''
   Bolling was referring to the freer climate in the Soviet Union
under Gorbachev.
   ``I listened to a member of the Central Committee in East Berlin
a few weeks ago,'' Bolling said. ``He was saying, `Who could have
imagined that the Soviet Union would be the place where the
counterrevolution would start?'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
