<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1809EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Auschwitz     09-11 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Auschwitz,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Congress Asks Groups to Suspend Formal Contact With Catholics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 17-nation European Jewish Congress said Monday
it asked Jewish organizations worldwide to cease formal contact with
the Roman Catholic Church because of the dispute over a convent at
the Auschwitz death camp.
   ``At issue is the word of the church. It is difficult to speak
with someone when you have this kind of problem,'' said Theo Klein,
who led the French delegation to the two-day annual meeting.
   Klein, a former president of the European Jewish Congress, said
he has appealed to Jewish organizations to suspend official contacts
with the Catholic Church. He said there had been no dissent.
   ``Each organization is free to make its own policy, so I cannot
say to you that all organizations have stopped dialogue, but I think
so,'' said Klein, who helped negotiate a 1987 agreement with
Catholic representatives to remove the Carmelite convent.
   The meeting was dominated by the convent issue, which has split
Catholics and revived debates about lingering anti-Semitism in
Europe. Many Jews regard the convent at the camp _ where at least
2.5 million Jews were among the estimated 4 million victims during
World War II _ as offensive.
   Under the 1987 accord negotiated in Geneva between international
Jewish organizations, and a representative of the Polish Catholic
Church, Cardinal Franciszek Macharski, it was agreed the convent
should be removed by Feb. 22.
   But the Polish primate, Cardinal Jozef Glemp, continues to back
the convent, which is in a hut where the Nazis stored gas used in
the mass murder of Jews. He has said the Geneva agreement was not
negotiated by ``competent people.''
   Two French cardinals and a Belgian cardinal who helped negotiate
the 1987 agreement have rejected Glemp's stance.
   Klein said he wrote to French Cardinal Albert Decourtray in July
announcing that all formal Jewish-Catholic contacts would cease
until the convent issue is resolved.
   Since then, Klein said, he has refused all invitations from
Catholic organizations, including a recent invitation to address a
French Catholic student body.
   ``The Catholics themselves understand it is very difficult to
have a dialogue now without having solved this problem of the
Carmelites,'' said Klein.
   Informal contacts will continue with the European Catholic
cardinals who want to stick to the agreement, Klein said.
   ``It seems to me that in the Vatican some people will try to find
a solution, but if it will be the boss, I don't know,'' said Klein,
referring to Pope John Paul II, who has not publicly expressed his
opinion on the issue.
   Lionel Kopelowitz, president of the European Jewish Congress,
said the meeting endorsed the suspension of formal contacts.
   In a resolution, the congress urged swift removal of the convent
and said it hoped ``that the hitherto fruitful Jewish-Catholic
dialogue, strongly affected by the situation ... will not suffer
lasting damage.''
   ``Auschwitz itself is holy ground,'' said Kopelowitz. ``It needs
no memorial of any sort to any faith ... it is soaked in the blood
of all those who died.''
   Glemp has canceled a U.S. visit scheduled to start on Sept. 21,
the Polish news agency, PAP, reported over the weekend.
   The announcement came after U.S. Jewish leaders said they planned
to sue Glemp for defamation, claiming he implied that Jewish
protesters sought to harm the nuns during a July 14 demonstration at
the camp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
