<FIRST>r w AM-MinePenalties     09-11 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mine Penalties,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Report: May Be Impossible for Government to Collect Overdue Millions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government may have to write off much of
the $38 million owed by violators of federal mine reclamation laws,
the General Accounting Office said Monday.
   The money may not be collectable because many of the companies
that failed to restore mining sites and then failed to pay their
penalties ``are either bankrupt or no longer mining,'' said a report
by the investigating arm of Congress.
   About 99 percent of the money owed by penalized mining companies
was considered delinquent as of the end of the last fiscal year; 83
percent had been in the delinquent column for an entire year, the
report said.
   The government ``may never be able to achieve a high rate of
collection,'' the investigators concluded.
   The federal Office of Surface Mining has been criticized for
about five years by Rep. Morris Udall, D-Ariz., and other members of
Congress for poorly tracking cases after imposing penalties. The GAO
said the agency had improved its procedures and has a better system
for collecting the money owed by mine law violators.
</TEXT>
