<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1819EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-Drugs     09-11 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Drugs,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sen. Byrd Proposes $3.9 Billion Increase for Drug Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate Appropriations
Committee said Monday he will introduce legislation increasing next
year's anti-drug spending by $3.9 billion, paying for it by cutting
most domestic and defense programs.
   The proposal by Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., would mark a concrete
response from Democrats who have said President Bush's own new
drug-fighting proposals are inadequate and underfunded.
   In particular, a number of Democratic leaders have said Bush's
$7.9 billion program would be difficult to finance without raising
taxes _ an option Bush has steadfastly rejected.
   ``The president says, `Read my lips,''' said Byrd, whose panel
oversees about half of all federal spending. ``He says he won't
support any increase in taxes. So I have to do what I can do.''
   His proposal would bring spending for federal drug initiatives to
$10.1 billion in fiscal 1990, which begins Oct. 1 _ $2.2 billion
more than Bush has sought.
   Byrd not only topped the dollars Bush would spend, but said his
proposal of 0.575 percent across-the-board cuts to pay for the extra
spending was fairer than what the president proposed.
   Last Tuesday, Bush asked Congress to increase anti-drug efforts
by $717 million. He said he would pay for it by paring a handful of
programs, including immigration aid, rural development, housing and
a Defense Department radio system.
   ``The drug epidemic facing this country is a crisis that affects
us all,'' Byrd told reporters. ``In my view it is critical that we
look for solutions that will seek to spread not only the pain but
also the gain in a fair and evenhanded manner.''
   Byrd said 53 percent of the additional money would be spent on
law enforcement efforts, and 47 percent would be for education,
treatment and prevention programs.
   His proposed cuts would not effect Social Security or other
federal benefit programs.
   Bush has reacted to the quick Democratic criticism of his
proposals by dismissing it has partisan ``carping.''
   Democratic leaders have responded by accusing Bush of
recommending expensive programs _ the manned space mission to Mars
was another they cited _ while giving little indication how Congress
was supposed to find the money.
</TEXT>
