<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-11 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>West, Midwest Get Snow, Cold</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MIN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Northern sections of the West and Midwest got a taste of winter
Monday as snow fell in Colorado and North Dakota and low-temperature
records up to 100 years old were broken or tied in nine cities.
   Frost or freeze advisories were issued Monday night for much of
the Dakotas and Nebraska.
   In northern and eastern Texas, thunderstorms dumped 2} inches of
rain north of Abilene in just 90 minutes. Heavier rainfall in the
six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT included 3.14 inches in Abilene,
Texas and 1.3 inches in Dallas.
   The storms produced gusts up to 35 mph in Waco and winds that
tore off tree limbs in Carlsbad, Texas. Hail as big as quarters fell
in Temple, Okla., and Jefferson County, Okla.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered from the lower
Mississippi Valley to the Tennessee Valley and the southern and
central Appalachians. Light showers fell in northern Minnesota, and
low clouds and drizzle covered the central Rockies and the central
High Plains.
   A large dome of high pressure anchored over southern
Saskatchewan, Canada, produced the cool weather Monday morning in
much of the northwest and north-central sections of the United
States.
   Light snow fell across higher elevations of the Front Range in
Colorado, including up to half an inch in Woodland Park, Colo. Snow
also fell in Minot, N.D.
   It was 26 degrees in Glasgow, Mont., 1 degree lower than the
record for Sept. 11 set in 1955, and 27 degrees in Casper, Wyo.,
where the old mark of 33 degrees was set in 1974.
   Low-temperature records were also set in Billings, Mont., (28
degrees, 32 in 1949); Valentine, Neb. (29, 30 in 1940); Pocatello,
Idaho, (31, 33 in 1916); and Goodland, Kan., (38, 40 in 1955).
Records were tied in Havre, Mont. (23 degrees, 1889); Great Falls
(29, 1921); and Rapid City, S.D. (29, 1921).
   By early afternoon, temperatures were only in the 40s and 50s
from the northern and central Rockies to the northern and central
Plains and the upper Mississippi Valley.
   By contrast, the Atlantic Coast had another hot, sultry day. The
mercury climbed into the 90s from New Jersey to the southern coast.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 39
degrees in Denver to 100 degrees in Beeville, Texas. The low in
lower 48 states Monday morning was 17 degrees in Livingston, Mont.,
and West Yellowstone, Mont.
   The forecast for Tuesday called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from Florida to the southern and central Appalachians,
the Tennessee Valley, much of the lower and middle Mississippi
Valley, the northern half of Texas, Oklahoma, Kansas and eastern
Colorado; scattered showers from Illinois to the upper Great Lakes.
   High temperatures were expected to be in the 60s and 70s across
much of the nation; the 50s from the upper Mississippi Valley to the
northern Plains, Nebraska, western Kansas and eastern sections of
Colorado and Wyoming; the 80s and 90s on the Pacific Coast and in
the southern Rockies, all of Texas except the Panhandle, the lower
Mississippi Valley, the Tennessee Valley and the middle and southern
Atlantic Coast; and between 100 degrees and 110 degrees in the
desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
