<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     09-11 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jaruzelski Expresses Approval of Eve of Formation of New Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament wound up four days of hearings
on nominees for a Solidarity-led government on the eve of Tuesday's
vote to install the first non-communist Cabinet in Poland in 40
years.
   President Wojciech Jaruzelski expressed his ``greatest approval''
of the government-formation efforts as the Sejm, or lower house,
ended hearings Monday night by approving Marcin Swiecicki as the
proposed foreign trade minister and Wladyslaw Baka as national bank
chairman. He will not be a Cabinet member.
   Three nominees failed to win approval during the hearings, but
the opinions are not binding.
   The Solidarity government will face triple-digit inflation, a $39
billion foreign debt, a shortage of many basic commodities and a
work force demoralized by long lines for those scarce, poor quality
goods that are available.
   The outlines of its economic program emerged during weekend
hearings when Solidarity's Leszek Balcerowicz, nominated for finance
minister, recommended lower taxes on profits, coupled with
progressive income and value-added taxes; wage controls;
liberalization of foreign trade rules, and unification of the
government-set and free-market currency exchange rates.
   Solidarity lawmakers and communist deputies met separately Monday
afternoon. The Peasant Party, a Solidarity coalition partner, met to
discuss what the party considers an unsatisfactory choice for the
Agriculture Ministry.
   The Peasants prefer the incumbent agriculture minister over the
nominee, also from their party, who was rejected at a committee
hearing Friday.
   But Solidarity deputy Jacek Szymanderski said Prime Minister
Tadeusz Mazowiecki would stand by his choice of Peasant Party
candidate Czeslaw Janicki.
   The state PAP news agency said Peasant Party Chairman Roman
Malinowski resigned on Monday at a meeting of the party's main board
and was replaced by Dominik Ludwiczak, a farmer and member of the
party presidium.
   Ludwiczak later told reporters that party members ``were not
happy with radical changes in our party.''
   He also said the party passed a resolution obliging Peasant
lawmakers to vote for the government proposed by Mazowiecki ``for
the good of the country.''
   Mazowiecki will outline his government's program at Tuesday's
session.
   Solidarity is to receive half the 24 seats on the Council of
Ministers, or Cabinet. The communists have four ministries, but keep
the strategic posts of defense and interior. The Peasants get four
posts, the Democratic Party three.
   Both Peasants and Democrats switched from long communist alliance
to a Solidarity-led parliament majority.
   The nominee for foreign minister is considered neutral.
   Jaruzelski, the communist president, ``reacted with greatest
approval in connection with the actions of Premier Tadeusz
Mazowiecki aiming at forming a government representing the forces of
a broad coalition,'' Jaruzelski spokesman Wlodizimierz Lozinski told
reporters Monday.
   He said Jaruzelski ``expressed hope this government will be able
to implement a program of socio-economic reforms adequate to the
needs of the nation and the state.''
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa told a news conference in Gdansk
that having Communist Party members in the government may help
Poland.
   ``There are a lot of people there well prepared in political and
professional terms,'' PAP quoted Walesa as telling reporters. ``You
keep imagining (communists) with knives in their teeth. Communists
are not the problem in Poland ... The problem is the nonsense they
have introduced.''
   He said he does not believe the course of communist reforms can
be reversed, and Poland has a chance to lead other East bloc nations
while Poles are obliged to make most of the new opportunities.
   ``I don't believe that one can turn the course of events back.
You can pay for it more, you can do it longer, it can last longer,
but the direction of perestroika reforms must continue and must
achieve success,'' he was quoted as saying.
   Perestroika is Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's term for
the social and economic reforms he has initiated in the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
