<DOCNO> AP890911-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 2024EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey     09-11 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ozal's Candidate Re-elected Parliament Speaker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ZEYNEP ALEMDAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deputy from the governing Motherland
Party was re-elected speaker of Parliament on Monday in a vote seen
as a preview of the election of a president by the legislators in
November.
   Yildirim Akbulut, Premier Turgut Ozal's hand-picked candidate,
was elected on the third ballot. He got 250 votes in the 450-seat,
single-chamber Parliament where the Motherland Party holds 289 seats.
   Under the constitution, in the first two ballots a two-thirds
majority of 300 votes is needed to elect a speaker.
   On the third ballot the winner needs only a majority _ 226.
   Akbulut, 54, failed to get the required majority on the first two
ballots because four other candidates from the Motherland Party
divided the votes and he received no support from opposition parties.
   Three Motherland candidates withdrew after the first two ballots
leaving only Akbulut and Ilyas Aktas in the contest. Aktas received
173 votes.
   The Motherland deputies, including Aktas, said they entered the
race to show opposition to Ozal's deciding on Akbulut's candidacy
without consulting his party's parliamentary group.
   The same balloting procedure will be followed for November's
presidential election in which Ozal may be a candidate. The premier
has not announced his candidacy but has not denied news reports that
he may run.
   The opposition parties in Parliament, the Social Democrat
Populist Party and the conservative True Path Party, say Parliament
is no longer representative because the Motherland Party has lost
substantial support since the last general elections.
   In local elections in March, the Motherland Party won only 21.8
percent of the vote, finishing third after the two major opposition
parties.
   The next general elections are scheduled for 1992.
   Political analysts have said Ozal may use his party's
parliamentary majority to become president and cap his political
career rather than face possible defeat in 1992.
   Ozal told a news conference last week that Parliament would elect
a civilian president through its own free will.
   President Kenan Evren, a leader of the former military junta,
will retire at the end of his seven-year term as president.
   The armed forces have for decades taken an active part in
selecting the president and six of the last seven presidents have
been former military men.
   Akbulut, a lawyer, was elected to Parliament in 1983 and became
speaker in 1987. The speaker of Parliament becomes acting president
in the absence or illness of the president. He can call Parliament
back from recess.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
