<FIRST>r i AM-Marcos     09-11 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aquino Wishes Marcos a Happy Birthday _ Somewhere Else</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino on Monday
wished her exiled predecessor Ferdinand Marcos a happy birthday _ as
long as he spends it outside of the Philippines.
   ``As a Christian, I pray that God will give him his blessings
from this day,'' Mrs. Aquino told reporters on Marcos' 72nd
birthday. ``I am holding fast to what I believe is for the national
interest, and that is not to allow Marcos and his family to return
at this time.''
   Mrs. Aquino has cited national security for refusing to allow
Marcos to return from Hawaii, where he has lived since his ouster in
a civilian-military uprising in February 1986.
   Marcos has been hospitalized in Honolulu since January with
heart, kidney, liver and lung ailments and is reported in critical
condition.
   Nearly 1,000 Marcos supporters held a peaceful rally Monday to
mark the ex-president's birthday.
   His followers published a full-page advertisement Monday in the
nationally circulated Philippine Daily Inquirer extending birthday
greetings and calling for his return ``in the interest of true
national reconciliation.''
   Also on Monday, airports in Manila and Cebu were alerted to
prevent a Marcos supporter, who also is related to Mrs. Aquino, from
slipping back into the country from the United States.
   Bienvenido Alano, acting commissioner of immigration and
deportation, said the alert was ordered because of reports that
businessman Eduardo Cojuangco might enter the country.
   ``We have information that Mr. Cojuangco has a plan to return,''
Alano said in a radio interview. ``So I alerted immigration officers
in Manila airport and in Cebu because the report is he will come in
via Cebu. In any case, when we find out that he came in, we will
detain him at the airport.''
   Cojuangco, a first cousin of Mrs. Aquino, fled the country
shortly before Marcos was ousted and has been living in Santa
Monica, Calif. He has been linked to previous attempts to topple the
Aquino administration.
   In another development, the official in charge of recovering
Marcos' alleged ``hidden wealth'' said his agency will need an
increase of more than $500,000 in its budget to continue the search.
   The government claims Marcos and his backers embezzled up to $10
billion during the 20 years that Marcos ruled.
   Mateo Caparas, chairman of the Presidential Commission on Good
Government, asked the House Appropriations Committee to increase his
budget from $950,000 to $1.5 million for 1990.
   Caparas also said the commission needs more than $2 million to
pay American lawyers representing the Philippines in civil suits
pending against Marcos in U.S. courts.
   The government has said that so far it has recovered about $133
million in cash and the money has been turned over to the land
reform program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
