<FIRST>r i AM-Honduras-Contras     09-11 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras-Contras,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Mission Arrives to Prepare for Contra Demobilization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An advance mission for the U.N. team
that will supervise demobilization of Nicaraguan rebels met on
Monday with President Jose Azcona Hoyo and other officials to
prepare for visits to camps near the border.
   A peace agreement signed on Aug. 7 by Central American countries,
including Honduras, calls for disbanding and disarming the rebels,
known as Contras, and relocating them in Nicaragua or third
countries. The United Nations and Organization of American States
were asked to oversee the effort.
   About 11,000 Contras and 12,000 dependents are in Honduran camps.
   Gen. Pericles Ferreira of Brazil, who heads the 16-member
mission, said its task is to lay the groundwork for future U.N.
envoys and establish contact with all governments and organizations
involved in the regional peace process.
   The mission plans to visit camps of the Contras and Nicaraguan
and Salvadoran refugees in southeastern and southwestern Honduras on
Tuesday and Wednesday.
   The government estimates more than 40,000 Nicaraguans and 35,000
Salvadorans who fled wars in their countries over the past 10 years
are in U.N.-sponsored camps.
   The delegation arrived after visits to Costa Rica and Guatemala
and will travel to El Salvador and Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
