<FIRST>u a AM-HospitalGirl     09-11 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hospital Girl,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toddler With Intestinal Disease to Leave Hospital for First Time</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GABRIELLE GLASER</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Nigerian toddler who must be fed through tubes
because of an intestinal disease will leave the hospital center
where she has lived since her birth nearly three years ago, her
doctors and nurses said Monday.
   Ogechi Anyanwu, wearing a ruffled pink dress with matching socks
and sneakers, waved and smiled to reporters and called frequently
for her pacifier at a news conference.
   ``Her progress has been excellent and her prognosis for leading a
normal life is terrific,'' said Dr. David Dudgeon, Ogechi's
pediatric surgeon at Johns Hopkins Children's Center.
   Ogechi will move to a hospital in Columbia, Mo., where her
parents, who are from Nigeria, plan to live.
   When she was born prematurely in October 1986, Ogechi weighed a
little more than 2 pounds. Within 10 days, she developed neonatal
necrotizing enterocolitis, which kills bowel tissue and causes short
gut syndrome.
   The condition, which strikes one premature baby in 100, spread
rapidly and doctors had to remove 80 percent of her small intestine
and 50 percent of her colon.
   Without a normal intestine, which absorbs nutrients, Ogechi
cannot eat solid food. She has been intravenously almost
continuously since birth.
   Wherever she goes, she is trailed by a machine holding three
plastic bags of nutrients and several tubes.
   She's fed by two pumps that deliver a mixture of fats, proteins
and sugars intravenously and by another pump connected to a tube to
her stomach. The child gets 80 percent of her calories through the
stomach tube.
   She suffers diarrhea and frequent infections. Ogechi must take
antibiotics regularly, and has undergone surgery more than a dozen
times for repairs to her intestinal tract and insertion of
intravenous lines.
   Despite her ailment, Ogechi has developed normally, doctors said.
She weighs a robust 35 pounds, walks and rides a tricycle for
exercise and has a relatively advanced vocabulary.
   ``How many 3-year-olds do you know who know how to say
`stethoscope?''' asked Dudgeon.
   ``She is full of joy, love, very rambunctious and very giving,''
said nurse Maura Mahon, who cared for Ogechi her first year.
   ``Aside from the fact that normal 3-year-olds don't get their
temperatures taken every four hours around the clock, we try to give
her as normal a life as possible,'' said nurse Mary Kay Alford, who
has cared for Ogechi the past year and will escort her to University
Hospital in Columbia.
   Ogechi's parents, Longinus and Edith Anyanwu, recently moved to
Columbia. Her father teaches computer science at Columbia College.
   Doctors expect the youngster to be released from the Missouri
hospital within several months.
   Her intestines recently doubled in length and have widened, which
will soon allow her to eat food normally, Dudgeon said.
   ``I expect that within a matter of months she will be eating
solid food, although she might have to stay away from real spicy
pizza,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
