<FIRST>r i AM-Australia-Bridge     09-11 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Australia-Bridge,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Order Visa for American Bridge Player</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PERTH, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Immigration Department on Monday
ordered that an American with the AIDS virus be granted a visa so
that he can compete in the Bermuda Bowl world contract bridge
championship in Perth.
   Australia's consulate in San Francisco had refused to issue a
visa to Peter Pender of San Francisco on grounds he had tested
positive for the AIDS virus even though he did not have symptons of
the fatal disease.
   The action by the Immigration Department means the United States
will have its full complement of players when the semifinals of the
bridge championahip begin next Monday.
   The United States won the world team title in 1985. As the North
American champion the team qualified for the semifinals.
   AIDS _ acquired immune deficiency syndrome _ is a disease in
which a virus attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims
susceptible to a wide variety of infections and cancers.
