<FIRST>u a AM-PaperMillViolence     09-11 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paper Mill Violence,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor's Handling of Paper Mill Violence Criticized</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Asscociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INTERNATIONAL FALLS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI on Monday joined the
investigation of a riot at a paper mill by hundreds of pro-union
demonstrators, and six people were charged in the violence,
authorities said.
   Union leaders condemned Saturday's riot over BE&amp;K Construction's
use of non-union labor on the $535 million expansion of Boise
Cascade Corp.'s mill, but said violence could break out again.
   ``People will do anything when their livelihood is threatened,''
said Joint Labor Council President Bob Walls.
   About 400 people set fire to vacant trailers, overturned cars and
hurled rocks. Law enforcement officers used tear gas to break up the
crowd, and arrested 31 people. Five people were injured, and damage
was estimated at $1.3 million.
   Tires have been slashed and windows have been broken since
Saturday, but otherwise this Canadian border town of 6,500 people _
more widely known for its cold-weather claim to be ``Icebox of the
Nation'' _ has been quiet, officials said Monday.
   About 500 non-union workers returned to work on the expansion
Monday, the second day of work on the expansion project since the
violence. Two or three people picketed but there were no incidents,
said Boise Cascade spokesman Andrew Drysdale.
   An FBI agent arrived in International Falls because some rioters
crossed state lines to get to the Boise Cascade site; Two of the six
charged Monday are from Michigan; the others from Minnesota, said
Koochiching County Attorney Dave Johnson.
   The charges included riot, criminal damage to property, arson,
trespassing and assault, Johnson said. They appeared before county
District Judge Peter Hemsted, who set the maximum bail for each
case, ranging from $13,000 to $30,000.
   All six remained in the county jail, along with 18 others who
will be charged Tuesday, Johnson said.
   Four International Falls residents arrested Saturday have been
released on their own recognizance and are expected to be charged
later, he said. Three cases involving lesser charges are being
handled by the city attorney's office. Those people have also been
released.
   Police in various municipalities have identified five or six more
people from videotapes police made Saturday, and those people are
expected to be charged and arrested, Johnson said.
   Authorities may send a copy of the tape to police in Iron
Mountain, Mich., where one busload of demonstrators is believed to
have originated, said Police Chief Tom Hardy.
   ``We want to send a message that it will cost them dearly to do
this type of thing here,'' he said.
   Officials earlier said 32 people were arrested, but revised that
figure to 31.
   The mill, which employs about 800 union workers and 150 salaried
workers, is beefing up security, Drysdale said.
   ``Given the governor's delayed reaction, we will take the steps
necessary to protect the property and our people,'' he said.
   Gov. Rudy Perpich put 275 National Guardsmen on alert, but did
not send the Guard into International Falls. His decision not to
send in the Guard was criticized Monday by company officials and
political foes.
</TEXT>
