<FIRST>u a AM-MissAmerica-Marks 1stLd-Writethru a0631 09-11 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miss America-Marks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0631,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Pageant Director Has Heart Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-9, `Even after ..., to UPDATE with comment from
pageant director.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOMERS POINT, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former director of the Miss America
Pageant was hospitalized in critical condition Monday after
suffering a heart attack, just days before this year's pageant,
officials said.
   Albert A. Marks Jr., 76, arrived at the emergency room of Shore
Memorial Hospital at 11:46 a.m., said hospital spokeswoman Margie
Barham.
   ``He is in the intensive care unit,'' she said Monday afternoon.
``I can't give a prognosis.''
   Marks retired in 1988 after directing the pageant for 35 years
and handing over his duties to Atlantic City attorney Leonard Horn.
   However, he has not completely left the pageant. He sat in a seat
of honor near Horn at last year's final night production.
   ``I am very saddened and very worried,'' Horn said Monday
afternoon. ``I love Al Marks. I love him dearly, and I'm obviously
very concerned.''
   Even after retirement, Marks was accorded much respect for
leading the pageant through rough times. He defended the pageant
when it faced criticisms from the women's liberation movement, the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, labor
organizations and a segment of the public that considers Miss
America an outdated symbol.
   Marks, a Margate resident, was also the man who fired Bert Parks,
replacing him first with actor Ron Ely and then with the current
host, Gary Collins.
   In the 1960s, Marks was the first to suggest dropping the
controversial swimsuit competition. He was overruled by state
pageant directors and fans. Horn has since tried to downplay the
significance of the swimsuit contest by lowering its value in the
judging.
   He also handled hordes of reporters when nude photographs of Miss
America 1984 Vanessa Williams appeared in a men's magazine.
   When not directing the pageant, Marks was an investment broker at
Advest Inc.'s Atlantic City office.
   ``Of course, the pageant will go on,'' Horn said of this week's
preliminaries and the finals Saturday night. ``Al, above all, would
understand that.''
</TEXT>
