<HEAD>Bay Of Pigs Military Commander Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `Jose Alfredo ..., with 2 grafs to add detail,
first reference to Batista. Pick up 3rd graf pvs: `San roman, whose...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILL LESTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of the 1961 Bay of Pigs invasion of
Cuba was found dead at his home, a possible suicide, more than 28
years after the failed mission that haunted him, police and friends
said Monday.
   Jose Alfredo Perez San Roman, 58, led the 1,500-man brigade of
Cuban exiles in the abortive assault on their island homeland in
April 1961. They were defeated by troops loyal to the communist
government of Fidel Castro, who had seized power in 1959 after
dictator Fulgencio Batista fled amid guerrilla fighting.
   San Roman and more than 1,000 of his followers were imprisoned
nearly two years.
   San Roman, whose body was discovered at 9:20 a.m. Sunday at his
mobile home, spent much of his own imprisonment in solitary
confinement.
   He reportedly had a history of depression in the years that
followed.
   Police were considering the death a suicide, pending the results
of an autopsy. ``A note was found on the scene and will be compared
with Mr. Roman's handwriting,'' said Metro-Dade police spokesman
George Reyes.
   Col. Ramon J. Ferrer-Mena, San Roman's chief of staff at the Bay
of Pigs, said his commander took the defeat personally and didn't
accept the mission's failure, even as it collapsed around the small
exile invasion force.
   ``By the middle of the invasion, I was convinced that everything
went wrong,'' Ferrer-Mena said Monday. ``But he never accepted that
_ even when we were in the swamps.''
   ``He took it quite personally,'' said Ferrer-Mena. ``He felt
responsible for every man who died there and every widow and child
left without a father.''
   Robert Kennedy, then U.S. attorney general, said San Roman told
him after his repatriation from Cuba that ten times as many troops
would have been needed to succeed.
   Failure of the invasion plan has been attributed to limited
support from the U.S. government and almost no air support.
   Veterans of Brigade 2506, the exile military detachment that
landed on the central southern Cuban beaches, still meet in Miami
and discuss what might have been.
   The invasion cost almost 100 lives and the more than 1,000
prisoners were held until December 1962 when they were freed in
exchange for food and medicine.
   Col. Humberto Olivera, another veteran of the Bay of Pigs,
described San Roman as a hero in the exile community.
   ``During his trial, he behaved as a commander,'' said Olivera.
``He never said `no'' and he was a man who faced a firing squad and
never turned his back on his principles. He was a brilliant man.''
   Olivera said San Roman was an honor student and graduate of
Managua Military Academy, the Cuban equivalent of the U.S. Military
Academy. He also was one of the youngest captains of the Cuban army,
Olivera said.
   During the final days of the Batista regime, San Roman opposed
Batista and was put in jail, said Olivera. Later, he saw the new
Cuban goverment was communist and joined the exile opposition.
   ``He was the man who led the invasion. He refused to leave the
beach when he had a chance,'' Olivera said Monday. ``He said the
famous words: `We came here to fight.' ''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
