<SECOND>AM-Salcido Hearing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0727,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Preliminary Hearing Opens For Accused Mass Murderer Ramon Salcido</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf, `Salcido, 28, ..., with 5 grafs to UPDATE with
testimony the blood found on two victims appears to be Salcido and comment
from prosecutor. Picks up 12th graf, `The hearing ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>By JENNIFER McNULTY</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sheriff's deputy, testifying at a
hearing for Ramon Salcido on Monday, fought back tears Monday when
identifying a photograph of the former winery worker's young
daughters found with their throats slashed.
   Salcido is accused of killing seven people in a killing spree
April 14.
   Sonoma County Sheriff's Deputy Mike McManus spoke haltingly as he
described finding the bodies of Sofia, 4, and Teresa, 1, lying near
their sister, Carmina, 3, who survived the attack.
   McManus, the first officer to arrive at the county dump where the
girls' bodies were discovered, testified in the opening day of a
preliminary hearing for Salcido.
   Salcido is accused of killing his wife, two daughters, his
mother-in-law and her two daughters, and a co-worker during the
rampage; he also is accused of attempting to murder Carmina, another
co-worker and the co-worker's wife.
   Sonoma County Judge Knoel Owen denied a defense motion to
continue the hearing for 30 days to assure the appearance of two
U.S. drug agents who help captured Salcido in his native Mexico five
days after the rampage.
   Salcido told the agents he killed his wife and a co-worker in a
jealous rage believing they were romantically involved, federal
officials have said.
   Salcido's defense attorney, Marteen Miller, has accused Mexican
authorities of coercing a confession. He said it would take 30 days
for authorities in Washington, D.C., to ensure the agents'
appearance.
   Owen said he would reconsider Miller's motion if at the end of
preliminary hearing the agents had not testified.
   Dr. William Vogel, an administrator with the California Forensic
Medical Group who examined Salcido in custody, testifed that he
found no physical evidence of torture.
   Also testifying was Richard Waller, a criminalist with the
California Department of Justice Laboratory, who said that blood
found on the body of Salcido's mother-in-law and her 12-year-old
daughter appears to be Salcido's.
   The finding, based on tests of genetic markers in blood, also
linked a sample found on a .22-caliber semiautomatic pistol to
Salcido, said Waller.
   Salcido, 28, who has pleaded innocent to the charges, sat quietly
throughout the hearing.
   After Monday's session, Assistant District Attorney Peter Bumerts
called the physical evidence in the case ``as conclusive as it
gets.''
   ``I don't think this is a who-done-it, and I don't think (Miller)
has ever indicated it would be,'' said Bumerts.
   The hearing is expected to last two weeks, and then the judge
will decide whether enough evidence exists to hold Salcido over for
trial.
   On Aug. 31, Owen ordered the prosecutor to turn over to the
defense all information about Salcido's arrest. Authorities also
must cooperate in the release of details surrounding Salcido's
arrest in Mexico, Owen said.
   Salcido allegedly confessed voluntarily to the slayings to
Mexican authorities before being turned over to Sonoma County
deputies.
   Miller, in asking for release of arrest information, argued that
any challenge to that confession will have to go into the original
arrest in Mexico, not just the arrest by the Sonoma County Sheriff's
Department during a flight from Mexico City to Santa Rosa.
   Miller also hinted that Salcido may been right in suspecting his
wife of infidelity, but Miller refused to reveal any evidence to
support his claim.
</TEXT>
