<HEAD>Two More Brazilian Jetliners Make Emergency Landings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with third incident in eight days.
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two domestic Boeing 737s made emergency
landings at Amazon jungle airports in the eight days since a Varig
airliner got lost and crashed in the rain forest, according to
reports Monday.
   Three passengers suffered minor injuries when a Varig plane
carrying 42 people made an emergency landing Monday at the Porto
Velho airport in the western Amazon, according to Globo television.
   The jetliner, on a regularly scheduled run from Porto Velho to
Manaus, was forced to turn back shortly after takeoff when the
craft's wingflaps failed to operate properly, said Globo, the
nation's largest private network.
   Varig would neither confirm nor deny the reports.
   Earlier, the company said in a statement a plane on a regular
flight from Rio Branco to Cuiaba, also in the western Amazon, made
an emergency landing Sunday when it developed trouble in the right
engine's oil filter.
   The pilot was forced to make an emergency landing in the city of
Vilhena, Varig said. The 56 passengers and six crew members were
unhurt and spent the night in the city while the plane was repaired,
the airline said.
   On Sept. 3, another Boeing 737 belonging to Varig went off course
and crashed in the Amazon jungle near Sao Jose do Xingu, about 1,100
miles from its intended destination of Belem at the mouth of the
Amazon River. Twelve of the 54 people aboard were killed.
   Passengers later said the pilot, Cesar Garcez, was listening to a
soccer match during the flight. Garcez denied the accusation.
</TEXT>
