<HEAD>Vietnam to Turn Over Three Sets of Remains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Socialist Republic of Vietnam plans to
repatriate three sets of remains believed to be those of American
servicemen killed during the Vietnam War, the U.S. Pacific Command
announced Monday.
   Arrangements have been made to pick up the remains in Hanoi and
fly them to the U.S. Army Central Identification Laboratory in
Honolulu, a Navy news release said.
   In addition, the U.S. government plans to repatriate nine remains
believed to be those of Southeast Asians, CINCPAC said.
   This is the 12th such repatriation since a mission to Hanoi
headed by presidential emissary Gen. John W. Vessey Jr. in Aug. 1987.
   The remains were expected to arrive at Hickam Air Force Base on
Tuesday.
