<SECOND>AM-Tunisian,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minister Urges US to Grant Arafat a Visa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Tunisian minister urged the Bush
administration Monday to grant a visa to Yasser Arafat so the
chairman of the Palestine Liberation Organization could address the
U.N. General Assembly.
   But a State Department spokesman, Richard Boucher, said Arafat
had not applied. Last week, Arafat told a Saudi Arabian newspaper he
planned to attend the U.N. session which opens in two weeks.
   In a meeting with reporters, Habib Boulares, the Tunisian
minister of culture and information, said issuing a visa should not
be a problem. ``We consider he has the right to go to the U.N.,''
Boulares said.
   The Tunisian said he did not think the Bush administration would
want to see the United Nations shift its deliberations to Geneva in
order to hear Arafat.
   He referred to the transfer to the Swiss city of a special
session on the Palestinian issue after the Reagan administration
denied Arafat a visa for New York last year. Subsequently, the
administration concluded Arafat had renounced terrorism and opened a
dialogue with the PLO.
   It is being held in Tunisia, where the PLO maintains its
headquarters. The talks have not helped to break a stalemate in
addressing the Arab-Israeli dispute.
   But Boulares said the dialogue should go on. ``When people talk
together they can find a good way to solve pending problems,'' he
said.
   On another subject, Boulares urged the Bush administration and
the World Bank to ease Tunisia's $5 billion debt burden by
stretching out repayment of loans and lowering interest rates.
   He said the North African country had undertaken political
reforms that included abolition of forced labor and restricting
pre-trial custody.
   Boulares said a drought and infestation of locusts contributed to
Tunisia's difficulties.
   He is in the United States in connection with an exhibition of
mosaics to be exhibited on Thursday in Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
