<FIRST>r i AM-Egypt-PLO     09-11 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-PLO,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mubarak, Arafat Hold Talks in Cairo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak and Palestine
Liberation Organization leader Yasser Arafat met Monday to discuss
plans for peace in the Middle East.
   Neither leader talked to reporters following the talks.
   Arafat arrived in Cairo early Monday. It was not clear how long
he would stay in Egypt.
   Last week, Mubarak met with Arafat during a brief visit to
Tunisia and said the Palestinian leader would travel to Cairo for
talks on Egyptian ideas for Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
   Egypt is the only Arab country on speaking terms with Israel. The
two countries signed a peace treaty in 1979.
   On Saturday, Mubarak told reporters that Palestinian leaders had
offered no objections to his supplement to an Israeli peace plan,
but still were considering their final position.
   Mubarak's 10-point initiative was sent to Israel in July and
Jerusalem over the weekend offered tentative support for the
measures.
   The initiative seeks to clarify Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir's plan for elections in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip
to choose representatives to negotiate limited autonomy for the
territories.
   The 10 points include acceptance by Israel of the U.S.-backed
concept of trading land for peace, participation in the vote by the
140,000 Palestinians in Israeli-annexed East Jerusalem and an end to
building Israeli settlements in the occupied territories.
   In Israel, newspapers said three prominent Palestinians from the
occupied territories were traveling to Cairo this week to urge
Arafat to allow Arabs from the West Bank and Gaza to hold peace
talks with Israel.
