<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 2242EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Immigration     09-11 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Immigration,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Wants 125,000 Next Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITS a0749 to change keyword line, avoiding duplication
with a0686 and sidebars thereto on East German refugees in Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration has decided to hold
refugee admissions to the United States to 125,000 in the next
fiscal year, an increase of slightly less than 8 percent from this
year, a congressional source said Monday night.
   The figure would include slots for 50,000 from the Soviet Union,
no change from this year's allocation. The current Soviet figure is
almost double what it was during the start of the current fiscal
year last Oct. 1.
   But the administration, with congressional support in both
parties, has decided it cannot handle any more refugees from the
Soviet Union, according to several recent reports and the source.
   Israel has also expressed concern that Jewish refugees from the
Soviet Union were increasingly choosing to head for the United
States once out of their homeland, depriving the Jewish state of
needed settlers.
   The congressional source, affiliated with the immigration
subcommittee of the Senate Judiciary Committee, said, ``The issue is
not the numbers but the backlog.'' He estimated there are 20,000
Soviet emigres in Rome and Vienna awaiting U.S. decisions on their
eligibility to enter the United States.
   Under a revision of regulations ordered last year by Attorney
General Ed Meese, each person applying must prove individual
eligibility for refugee status, which means government aid in
resettlement and admission outside the normal immigration rules.
Previously, Jews from the Soviet Union were automatically considered
refugees.
   The new decision has made the backlog grow faster than it can be
processed.
   Overall, this year's refugee quota, arrived at by the
administration each year in consultation with the House and Senate
judiciary committees, is 116,000 persons, up from 94,000 at the
start of the fiscal year.
   The 125,000 figure for next year would include 10,000 whose
resettlement would be paid for by private organizations.
   ``To take more people, we'd have to find more money, and in the
current budget situation, that would mean robbing Peter to pay Paul,
doing things like taking money from famine relief in Africa. Nobody
wants to do that,'' the source said.
   Administration representatives, scheduled to make a formal
presentation to the subcommittee on Friday, gave informal briefings
to staff members on Monday.
</TEXT>
