<FIRST>r i AM-Pakistan     09-11 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pakistan,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Bhutto Promises More Police to Counter Ethnic Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IQBAL JAFFERY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto told
hundreds of thousands of Pakistanis at a rally on Monday that she
will provide more police to counter ethnic violence in southern
Sindh province, her home province.
   Journalists estimated at 500,000 the crowd who turned out at a
rally supporting her Pakistan People's Party to commemorate the
anniversary of the death in 1948 of Mohammad Ali Jinnah, founder of
Pakistan. Organizers said the crowd exceeded 1 million.
   Hundreds of thousands of Pakistanis joined flag-waving
processions and political rallies around the country for the
anniversary.
   In Karachi, Pakistan's largest city, throngs of peasants jammed
streets and chanted ``Long live democracy'' and ``Long live Bhutto.''
   It was Ms. Bhutto's first public rally in Karachi since she
became government leader last December.
   ``The government has decided to provide more police forces and
more equipment to counter the ... situation in Karachi in particular
and Sindh (province) in general,'' she told a cheering crowd in the
shadow of the mausoleum where Jinnah lies.
   Hundreds of people have been killed and thousands injured since
1986 in clashes in Sindh between native Sindhis and Moslem
immigrants from India, called mohajirs.
   Authorities there complain that the past decade also has seen
rising heroin trade, robbery and kidnappings.
   The People's Party colors of red, black and green fluttered from
light poles lining the boulevards of the sprawling seaport.
   Posters bearing images of Jinnah, Ms. Bhutto and her late father,
Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, appeared throughout the city.
   In Lahore, provincial capital of Punjab, the colors were the
green and white of her political opposition, a nine-party
conservative grouping called the Islamic Democratic Alliance.
   No reports were made of political violence in Monday's
observances.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
