<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 2301EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Freighter-Cocaine     09-11 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Freighter-Cocaine,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Arrests Seven Danish Crewmen In Cocaine Seizure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard intercepted a freighter in the
Bahamas, found 15 bales of cocaine bobbing alongside the ship and
arrested seven Danish crewmen, according to a federal affidavit
filed Monday.
   Authorities seized 1,100 pounds of cocaine in the capture Sunday
of the freighter Nerma north of the Berry Islands, about 40 miles
northwest of Nassau, officials said.
   The Coast Guard also seized three speedboats found near the ship.
Speedboats are often used to carry cocaine shipments from ship to
shore.
   The Nerma was detected on radar Saturday, according to the
affidavit filed in U.S. District Court by Drug Enforcement
Administration agent Robert Rowland.
   A cutter was sent to intercept the ship, which is registered in
Vanuatu, a South Pacific archipelago nation between Fiji and New
Caldedonia.
   Coast Guardsmen boarded the Nerma after seeing the bales of
cocaine, each weighing about 70 pounds, floating alongside, the
affidavit said. Each bale consisted of smaller plastic packages of
cocaine arranged so they would float together.
   After the cutter escorted the Nerma to Miami Beach, another bale
was found aboard the freighter, the affidavit said.
   The seven men arrested were identified as Bent Nissen, 55; Carl
Jensen, 55; Jans Madsen, 63; Bent Mortensen, 47; Carsten Pederson,
32; Brian Rasmussen, 31; and Martin Rasmussen, 41.
   They appeared Monday before U.S. Magistrate William C. Turnoff,
and were ordered held without bond in pretrial detention.
   Authorities said it was unusual for Danes to be arrested in drug
cases in the area.
   ``At first I couldn't find a Danish interpreter,'' said the head
of federal court interpreters for Miami, Irene King-Tomassini. She
said a friend suggested the Berlitz language school, ``and they put
me on to an employee of a cruise ship line who spoke the language.''
   During the hearing, Turnoff asked Assistant U.S. Attorney William
Jung about the ship's registry.
   ``I have been told that its flag is the nation of Vanuatu,'' Jung
replied. I understand that's north of the Australian coast.''
   Asked if he could elaborate, Jung said, ``That's all I can tell
you. My geography in that area is limited to McHale's Navy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
