<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Collins Adv22-24   09-11 0846</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Collins, Adv 22-24,0865</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 22</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv 23</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv 24</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 22-24, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: Mother of Four Unaccustomed to Showbiz Spotlight</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Film is in platform release through fall.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shirley Valentine has her moment of blossoming in
the new film with that title, and Pauline Collins had hers at
Montreal's 13th annual World Film Festival.
   Of the 250 movies from 52 countries shown at the 10-day festival,
Paramount's ``Shirley Valentine'' was chosen for the premiere at the
Theatre Maisonneuve of the Place des Arts.
   At the reception afterward, Collins was the center of attention,
a new experience for the pert, round-faced mother of four, making
her film debut in the new movie.
   ``It was very traumatic to see the film for the first time,'' the
English actress observed in an interview after the screening.
   ``I tried to detach myself and sit back and enjoy the film. I
tried to pretend it was somebody else up there and not me. Maybe
because it's 3 o'clock in the morning for me right now, I can feel
that way. (She had flown from London that morning.)
   ``What is curious is to come to the film having done the play
recently; I only finished on Broadway eight weeks ago. Some things
have changed, and sometimes my ear would say, `Oh that's different.'
But I really enjoyed it, especially the Greek part. All that
beautiful water.''
   Collins performed ``Shirley Valentine'' four months in London,
winning the Olivier award for best actress in a new play. In New
York, she was awarded the Tony in the play written by Willy Russell,
who provided Julie Waters with a star-making role in ``Educating
Rita.''
   ``When I first read the play, I thought it was a very long
speech,'' she recalled. ``Then I discovered that it was all one
speech! Nobody told me I would be on stage alone for the whole
play.''
   Shirley Valentine-Bradshaw is a middle-age English housewife with
a distant husband and two grown, spoiled children. Out of boredom
she talks to the wall in the kitchen where she prepares meals
between sips of wine. Her life changes when a woman friend invites
her to share a contest prize, a trip to the Greek islands. There she
meets a cafe owner, Costas, who changes her life.
   In the play, Collins created Shirley as well as 29 other
characters. The movie, adapted by Russell and directed by Lewis
Gilbert (``Alfie,'' ``Educating Rita''), supplies other actors,
including Tom Conti as a kind of laidback Zorba.
   ``Tom and I did a play together, `Romantic Comedy,''' Collins
remarked. ``And we're neighbors; our daughters go to the same
school. Tom and I work very easily together. First of all, we trust
each other a lot. And we laugh a lot.''
   In the film, Shirley and Costas take a boat cruise and skinny-dip
in a secluded cove. Collins declined an offer by director Gilbert to
use a body double.
   ``It's not a big deal in Europe, nudity,'' she explained. ``Most
people are nude or semi-nude on the beaches. People don't wear tops
there anymore. My only qualms were that I wished I was younger and
thinner (giggle). But I ain't.''
   Nonetheless she is attractive at 49, with mischievous eyes and
apple cheeks. She was born near Liverpool of a family of Irish poets
and teachers. She initially decided to be a teacher, then shifted to
acting.
   ``I started out at the Theater Royal Windsor, which is where the
royal family have their country seat,'' she said. ``I've done 15-16
plays in the West End and lots of television series, many of them
with my husband, John Alderton. American viewers know him from
`Upstairs, Downstairs'; he was the chauffeur. And I was the
downstairs maid.
   ``I didn't start early as an actress; I was 22 when I began. Most
of the peaks in my a career have been rather late. `Upstairs,
Downstairs' came when I was 30. Until that year I hadn't earned much
money. That year I earned 1,200 pounds. So I was in the money _ at
30.''
   Collins admitted that she wasn't the first choice for the film
version of ``Shirley Valentine.''
   ``Several American actresses were considered by Paramount because
I have no track record; nobody knew me from Adam _ or Eve,'' she
said. ``About five Paramount people flew to London to see me in the
play, and they began to think they might have me in the film. And
aren't I lucky?''
   Lucky enough to be predicted for an Academy Award nomination, as
some reviewers of ``Shirley Valentine'' have suggested.
   ``I've heard that, and it's very breathtaking,'' she said,
``especially for someone who has just embarked on a film career.''
   Already she has received offers for American roles, but she
doesn't think she's right for them. ```Shirley Valentine' is a tough
act to follow,'' she commented, adding with a giggle, ``Maybe I
should retire.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions Sept 22-24</NOTE>
