<DOCNO> AP890911-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 0201EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Health:NutritionSurvey     09-11 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Health: Nutrition Survey,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Health: Nutrition Survey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Most Americans want nutritionally sound meals for themselves and
their families but don't have a good enough understanding of
nutrition to do so, according to a survey conducted by the Post
Center for Nutrition and Health.
   The survey asked 1,000 adults what questions they want answered
about nutrition. More than half the responses showed a
misunderstanding or lack of information, and 14 percent reflected a
high level of confusion.
   Virgil Brown, president of the Medlantic Research Foundation and
Post Center advisor, was surprised by the basic level of questions
about cholesterol and thinks that existing information may have
become too technical.
   ``The percentage of fat and saturated fats, as well as the actual
recommendations on cholesterol consumption, are useful to
nutritionists and health professionals but are of little direct help
to most people in the grocery store,'' he says.
   ``While the survey domonstrates an interest in nutrition among
the public, it highlights even more the need to provide clear,
concise information that will enable people to choose a diet that
will contribute to their good health,'' adds Helen Guthrie,
chairperson of the nutrition department at Pennsylvania State
University and another advisor to the Post Center, a division of
Post Cereals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890911-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 0203EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Health:DietCops     09-11 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Health: Diet Cops,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Health: Diet Cops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Athletic trainer Bob Kersee has called in the
Diet Cops to keep nutritional tabs on his star performers _
Olympians Valerie Brisco, Jackie Joyner Kersee and Roy Martin.
   Diet Cops is the nickname for Specialized Diet Consultants _ in
the persons of Susan Cohen and Carol Saunders _ advising athletes on
optimum diets for performance. And they make weekly field calls to
athletes in training.
   ``Many athletes believe that their burning of calories in
workouts is all that is necessary to control body fat,'' says Cohen.
``The empty calories that some athletes fill their bodies with
cannot repair the muscle injury, bone and joint bruises that most
athletes suffer.''
   She says that the recommended diets are ``nutrient dense,'' with
lots of vitamins and minerals per calorie. The plans call for a 60
percent carbohydrate ratio with little fat and limited protein.
   ``Women athletes tend to eat fewer calories and are more likely
to develop nutritional deficiencies,'' she says.
   Brisco, Martin and the Kersees say the steroid scandal of the
Olympics was the catalyst for them to adopt a rational nutrition
program.
   ``Our medical counsel has demonstrated that steroids build
inherent weakness. What appears as strong muscle is fat and water,''
says Jackie Joyner Kersee. ``Our own timetable with frequent travel
and long workouts makes our eating cycles erratic. We suffer from
too many meals grabbed on the run.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890911-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 0203EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Health:WeightandHabits     09-11 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Health: Weight and Habits,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Health Care: Weight and Habits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ITHACA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Behavior modification _ changing the way you
feel about food and eating _ is a key part of controlling your
weight, says a Cornell nutritionist.
   ``For many people, it means adopting techniques that will help
them eat less without feeling deprived,'' says Christina Stark,
nutritionist with the Cornell Cooperative Extension.
   She says behavior modification, healthful dieting and a regular
exercise program are the three elements of a successful
weight-control plan.
   Keep track of your eating patterns, says Stark, and try to
substitute good eating habits for the bad ones.
   ``Choose one specific behavior that is a problem for you and work
to change that one,'' Stark says. ``Don't try to change too many
things at once or you may just frustrate yourself.''
   If watching television means settling down with a big bowl of
buttered popcorn, for instance, try to eliminate that between-meal
snack, or at least learn to like popcorn without butter and salt.
   If skipping breakfast means leaves you tempted by a mid-morning
doughnut from the office canteen, try bringing a piece of fruit or
whole-wheat bread from home instead.
   If snacking is a problem, try to modify that behavior by deciding
to eat only when seated at a table.
   ``Any changes you make must fit your lifestyle,'' says Stark,
``or they won't help with weight control in the long run.
   ``Don't decide to get more exercise by rowing if you hate to row.
Instead, choose one or more physical activities you like and can
stick with.
   ``And don't pick a diet based on exotic foods that you don't
normally eat.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890911-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 0204EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Health:ExerciseStudio     09-11 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Health:Exercise Studio,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Health: Exercise Studio</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Your resolve to exercise on your own may evaporate after the
first week of your self-designed program. Or perhaps you enjoy the
camaraderie of other exercisers and the convenience of an indoor
environment you can't get rained or snowed out of.
   An exercise studio is probably the answer. But how do you sort
out the legitimate ones from the fly-by-nights?
   Good exercise instructors will be certified and have that
certification posted in the studio, says Molly Fox, an instructor
who runs her own studio in New York City. Look for certificates from
the International Dance and Exercise Association, the Aerobics
Fitness Association of America, or the American College of Sports
Medicine.
   Next, evaluate how well the studio and the instructor fit your
needs. ``There are so many qualifications one should have besides a
certificate,'' she says. Some things to look for:
   _ An instructor who will help you set a realistic fitness goal
and help you achieve it. Even in a class setting, the teacher should
be able to give you some personal coaching.
   _ One who is knowledgeable about the field, keeping abreast of
new information through trade magazines, professional conventions
and attendance at advanced classes with other teachers.
   _ One who pays primary attention to the student, evaluating
performance and giving advice. A good instructor is a good listener
and responds to questions. He or she also will call students by
name, Ms. Fox observes.
   _ An instructor who is well organized, with attention to certain
parts of the overall program on given days.
   _ Versatility and flexibility. Ms. Fox points out that a good
teacher will teach a low impact class differently than a high impact
one, or a body sculpting class differently than a body blaster class.
   _ A teacher who looks and acts the part. He or she should be
healthy and in good shape physically and mentally. ``Teachers should
enjoy what they do and be motivated, not burned out.''
   _ The studio that's clean and has equipment in good condition.
Look for flooring that's safe for exercise and dance _ usually wood,
never concrete.
   _ A program with variety. You should be able to vary your
exercise routine.
   _ A studio that's accessible with classes and workouts scheduled
for your convenience.
   Ms. Fox studied with Jane Fonda in San Francisco before opening
her studio in New York. She's an active member of IDEA and AFAA.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890911-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 0205EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Health:PianoPains     09-11 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Health: Piano Pains,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Health: Piano Pains</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY702</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Remember how your piano teacher told
you to hold an orange in each palm to get you to arch your fingers
correctly over the keys?
   The teacher probably was right. Purdue University researchers
looking for sources of hand pain have discovered that slightly
curving the fingers alleviates joint stress, while playing with
straight or nearly straight fingers parallel to the keyboard is the
most harmful way to play the piano.
   Ben M. Hilberry, professor of mechanical engineering at Purdue,
and graduate student David C. Harding say their research into hand
mechanics may eventually help people in hand-intensive occupations.
Pianists were chosen for their study because their finger movement
is primarily two-dimensional.
   Harding says that knowledge of mechanical dynamics can help
pianists with an alternate treatment for ``overuse syndrome'' hand
pain. Traditionally, the treatment has been to cut down on playing
hours.
   ``They can't practice, or the pain hurts them during a
performance, and for professionals that means their job is on the
line,'' he says.
   The researchers used a special piano calibrated to record the
force of a finger's impact on a key. Video cameras simultaneously
recorded the angle of the finger from the side and above. These data
were analyzed by computer to calculate the forces at each of the
finger joints and tendons.
   Early research with five pianists with different playing
techniques showed vast differences in the amount of stress on the
finger joints. These results led to development of a computer
program to determine finger positions to minimize force on the
joints and tendons.
   ``We started out with the idea of trying to create a tool to
examine this issue,'' Harding says. ``We didn't anticipate being
able to also find the best playing positions to minimize forces on
fingers, but we were able to also accomplish that.'' He notes that
piano teachers, who have traditionally maintained that a curved hand
position is the best playing technique, now have scientific evidence
to back them up.
   The research was aimed primarily at developing a computer program
to analyze differences in technique among pianists and other
musicians. It was suggested by Dr. Kenneth D. Brandt, head of the
Rheumatology Division of Indiana University's School of Medicine and
director of its Performing Arts Medicine program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890911-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 0205EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Health:Feet     09-11 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Health: Feet,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Health: Feet ^By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stylish spike-heeled shoes with pointed toes can seriously damage
your feet.
   So says Dr. John Hunter, associate professor of orthopedic
surgery at the University of Oklahoma Health Sciences Center in
Oklahoma City.
   ``Feet already are some of the most used and abused parts of our
body, taking daily wear and tear and other special stresses such as
regular running,'' says Hunter, noting that wearing the wrong shoes
can cause bunions, heel spurs, corns and other serious foot ailments.
   ``I think women abuse their feet more than any other group,
because they tend to wear high-heeled, pointed-toed shoes, the shape
of which is dictated by a fashion designer rather than by their
anatomy.
   ``Lots of women who have feet that just don't fit into this type
of shoe will jam them in anyway, and as they get into middle age
they begin to have problems. It's an especially significant factor
in the development of problems such as bunions, corns and
callouses.''
   Women who want to be stylish but avoid problems should look for
thicker, cushioned soles, a larger toe box, a soft upper, a flexible
forefoot that allows the foot to bend, and, if necessary, room for
arch supports or orthotic inserts, Hunter advises.
   Extra cushioning is particularly important because fat tissues in
the sole waste away as a person ages, he says.
   ``That's one reason people in their 40s and 50s start to develop
callouses when they haven't changed their shoe style or their
lifestyle.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890911-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 0206EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Health:Eyesavers     09-11 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Health: Eyesavers,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Health: Eyesavers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Perils of modern life _ staring at your computer screen or
spending long hours on the road _ are sources of damaging stress to
the eyes, according to the American Optometric Association.
   There are simple steps you can take to offset this stress, the
organization says.
   If you spend many of your working hours in front of a video
display terminal, make it a habit to take a 10-minute break every
hour and relax your eyes by looking at something in the distance.
Room lighting should be soft with lamps to provide extra light for
paperwork. Shades, blinds or drapes should be angled to reduce
window glare.
   AOA cites studies that show eyestrain is the most frequent
complaint among office workers and says that poorly designed
workspaces and poor lighting are most often to blame. Eyestrain can
lead to headaches, body aches and irritability.
   Taking breaks while on the road also is advised. Drivers on long
highway trips should stop after the first 200 miles and every 100
miles thereafter.
   Driving at 55 mph requires concentrated focus on a narrow field,
and this can lead to fatigue and ``highway hypnosis.'' To offset
this, periodically focus on objects ahead and blink frequently.
   And, of course, wear sunglasses on bright days.
   The association advises a yearly checkup to detect vision
changes, which can occur subtly without your being aware of them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890911-0229 </DOCNO>
