<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Health:Visionloss     09-11 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Health: Vision loss,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Health: Vision Loss Warning Signs </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Blindness can catch people unaware, says the American Foundation
for the Blind. Some warning signs can tip you off that something is
wrong:
   _ Bumping into objects.
   _ Groping for objects or touching them in an uncertain way.
   _ Squinting or tilting the head to see.
   _ Holding books or other reading material close to the face.
   _ Dropping food or utensils at mealtimes.
   _ Difficulty recognizing faces.
   _ Looking ungroomed or sloppy.
   _ Acting confused or disoriented.
   ``Sight may be lost so slowly that it is not until a significant
amount of vision has been lost that the person realizes something is
wrong,'' says AFB Executive Director William F. Gallagher.
   ``Most vision loss will result from diabetes, cataracts, macular
degeneration and other eye diseases that affect primarily older
people and develop gradually with few early symptoms,'' he says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
