<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Health:Women     09-11 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Health: Women,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Health: Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a women's medical rights group says that women
still aren't taking enough responsibility for the quality of their
health care.
   ``Twenty years into the new age of the women's movement, women
still have fallen short of their responsibility of managing their
bodies,'' says Merle Hoffman, president and founder of Choices
Women's Medical Center in New York. ``Today's women respond after
the fact, turning towards medical malpractice.''
   Citing a recent New York State legislative report which charged
that unnecessary hysterectomies are on the rise, Hoffman says that
``women need to be transformed from passive, powerless victims into
informed medical consumers, demanding minimum standards of behavior,
information and treatment from their doctors.''
   To increase what she terms ``patient power,'' she says women must
assert their right to question their doctors and not be intimidated
by the medical establishment. They need to find out their options
for treatment and be prepared to comparison shop for both doctors
and drugs. Then, with informed consent, they should take equal
responsibility with their doctors about treatment decisions.
   ``It is not enough to know your rights. You must also accept your
responsibilities.''
</TEXT>
