<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Health Care: Kiosk</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY703</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   What's the most popular health care subject?
   According to a field test of a new video health care information
service, it's personal weight.
   The Health Care Information Center, developed by CareQuest Inc.,
of Roanoke, Va., and designed for use primarily in pharmacies,
offers information on 350 health topics, from acne to warts, back
pain to vitiligo.
   During a 90-day testing phase in the Southeast, in which more
than 19,000 pharmacy customers used the machine, questions about
weight and weight control far outranked all others, according to
CareQuest.
   Making the most use of the system in the test were
25-to-40-year-olds, who represented 39.7 percent of the total. Men
represented 49.2 percent of the users, the company said.
   The health care information in the computer data base is provided
by the Columbia University School of Public Health, in New York.
   Three video screens are encased in a 7-foot kiosk, which includes
a touch-sensitive screen for customer questions and two screens for
advertising and promotions. There is a printout option.
</TEXT>
