<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Health Care: Dentistry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans will spend an estimated $5 billion this year on
cosmetic dentistry and may spend as much as $9 billion by 1992,
according to Customedix Corp., developers of dental products.
   Three years ago, the figure was about $2.5 billion.
   The company says the increase is because people today are more
``cosmetic conscious,'' there is more disposable income, and new
dental products provide a more natural look.
   A new porcelain has been developed, for example, that has three
times the compressive strength of standard porcelains, says Dr.
Gordon Cohen, chairman of Customedix. He says porcelain has a
natural translucency, transmitting and reflecting light in a way
that matches real teeth.
   Cohen believes the use of high strength porcelains will increase
over the next decade, while alloys and conventional porcelains will
decline.
</TEXT>
