<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Health:Insurance     09-11 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Health: Insurance,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Health: Insurance Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The cost per employee of employer-sponsored health care plans
jumped by 18.6 percent in l988, after two years of increases
averaging less than eight percent, according to a survey made among
1,600 employers.
   That translates to a record $2,354 average for every employee.
The average cost in 1987 was $1,985, according to A. Foster Higgins
and Co., Inc., a benefit consulting firm.
   ``Not only is double-digit inflation back in health plans, there
doesn't appear to be much relief in sight,'' says John Erb, managing
consultant in charge of the survey.
   A major factor in the escalation is growing use of mental health
and substance abuse benefits. These alone cost an average of $207 in
l988, compared to $163 in l987.
   Another important factor is wider use of advanced medical
technology. ```Miraculous cures' are becoming more common, but
miracles cost money,'' says Erb.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
