<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 0224EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Health:Briefs     09-11 0799</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Health: Briefs,0817</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Health Care: Briefs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Women in poor physical shape are three times more likely to die
of heart disease at an early age than are those who keep themselves
in good condition, according to a long-term study.
   Dr. Lars G. Ekelund, the principal author of the study, said it
provides the first strong evidence that exercise protects women from
heart disease, just as it does men.
   Poor physical fitness ``is almost as important as smoking as a
risk factor for cardiovascular disease'' in women, said Ekelund, a
researcher at the University of North Carolina.
   The study was based on a 10{-year follow-up of 2,802 women who
ranged in age from 30 to 69. --_
   Fodor's, publishers of travel guides, has come out with a book
describing 240 health-oriented spas and resorts.
   ``Health and Fitness Vacations,'' by travel writer Bernard Burt,
covers everything from weight loss spas to mineral water retreats
and sports conditioning resorts in the United States, Canada, Mexico
and the Caribbean.
   Fodor's will update the book frequently, says Michael Spring,
editorial director. --_
   The American Red Cross has launched a national campaign to help
prevent child deaths from choking, suffocation and drowning.
   The Infant and Child CPR Campaign will encourage parents,
grandparents, baby sitters and others to learn how to deal with
breathing emergencies in infants and children.
   ``There's a lot a parent can do before the ambulance arrives,''
said Robert Burnside, director of health services for the American
Red Cross.
   One of those things, however, is not the Heimlich maneuver.
   That method of using abdominal thrusts to dislodge obstructions
in the breathing passages is effective on choking adults, but it
does more harm than good when used on a baby, Burnside said.
   A choking baby needs to be held in a certain way and be given a
series of blows to the back and thrusts to the chest to restore
breathing, he said. --_
   Bicycle helmets are so effective at preventing head injuries that
a major campaign should be launched to encourage riders to wear
them, a report published in the New England Journal of Medicine
concludes.
   The report, based on a study of injuries treated at five Seattle
area hospitals over a one-year period, shows that riders with
helmets had an 85 percent reduction in their risk of head injury and
an 88 percent reduction in their risk of brain damage. The study was
directed by Dr. Robert S. Thompson of the Group Health Cooperative
in Seattle.
   ``Safety helmets are effective, but they are not being used
enough,'' the researchers wrote. ``The time has come for a major
campaign to increase their use.'' --_
   Knowing how to use a computer as a clinical tool to analyze
patient data and search the medical literature is going to be as
important in the next decade as knowing how to use a stethoscope,
says Family Practice News.
   Citing a seminar run by the American Association of American
Medical Colleges, the publication predicts the use of computers
involving ``medical informatics'' will give the physician more time
for the patient.
   The report, noting that computers are not just teaching-machines,
predicts that they will be indispensible in clinical care and basic
research. For that reason, a medical informatics curriculum should
be on the agenda of medical schools.
   The medical journal adds that a number of medical schools,
including UCLA, have begun to offer courses on medical informatics.
--_
   High blood pressure affects one of every four Americans of all
ages and lifestyles and many of those afflicted don't even know it,
according to a report issued at Redwood, Wash.
   High blood pressure is the leading cause of heart attack, stroke
and kidney disease, say officials of Health Monitor Centers, which
offer free blood pressure reading and health screenings in retail
stores across the nation.
   The report says 60 percent of all Americans will develop some
type of elevated blood pressure during their lifetimes, with one of
every four suffering from hypertension. --_
   Eye examinations not only can disclose visual problems they also
can detect high blood pressure, diabetes and high cholesterol, says
a University of Alabama optometry professor.
   ``In many cases, optometry is the entry point for health care,''
explained Dr. Larry Alexander at an education course at the American
Optometric Association's Congress in New York City.
   ``The majority of optometric patients haven't had a physical exam
for years, so it's the optometrist who's picking up on these
cardiovascular conditions.''
   For example, an optometrist can spot high blood pressure or
diabetes by observing hemorrhaging or blocked blood vessels in the
eye.
   Or a person with high cholesterol may have fatty particles in the
eye's blood vessels, blocked vessels, a gray ring around the eye's
cornea or fatty deposits on the eyelids. --_
</TEXT>
