<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The economic slowdown caught up with American
consumers in July as they paid off $280 million more in credit than
they borrowed, the government reported.
   The Federal Reserve Board said Friday that consumer credit in
July declined at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 0.5 percent,
down from June's 4.7 percent gain. The June advance was revised
downward from 5.1 percent.
   The last reduction in consumer debt was in January 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines' Machinists union said its
officials have been contacted by two buyout specialists seeking to
purchase UAL Corp., the parent of United and a prime takeover target.
   United's pilots and management already have offered $6.75 billion
for the nation's second-largest airline.
   Billionaire Texas investor Robert Bass and takeover firm Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. are seeking meetings to discuss whether the
Machinists would be interested in supporting their bids, a
Machinists spokesman in Washington said. KKR denied meeting with the
union and said it wasn't interested in UAL.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Avon Products Inc. has disclosed it may sell its
Giorgio Beverly Hills and Parfums Stern fragrance businesses,
suppliers of some of the country's hottest selling scents.
   No final decision on whether to divest the subsidiaries has been
reached, said James E. Preston, the big cosmetic company's chairman
and chief executive officer. Avon has hired the investment banking
firm Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. to help it explore the possibility of a
sale and evaluate alternatives.
   Proceeds from a possible sale would go toward reducing Avon's
debt, which at mid-year totaled about $1 billion, Preston said in a
statement Friday.
</TEXT>
