<DOCNO> AP890911-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 0828EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Uniroyal-Michelin     09-11 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Uniroyal-Michelin,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reaction to Rumors of Tire Acquisition Varies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French tire maker Michelin is rumored to be
interested in acquiring Uniroyal Goodrich Tire Co., but analysts
differ on whether the purchase would fit in with Michelin's normal
purchasing patterns.
   Michelin is locked in a three-way contest with Goodyear and
Bridgestone of Japan to be the world's largest tire company.
   Analyst Harry Millis of McDonald &amp; Co. in Cleveland said
acquiring Akron-based Uniroyal Goodrich ``just would not fit
Michelin's normal pattern at all.''
   He noted that a 1970s purchase of a tire plant owned by Gates
Rubber Co. of Denver ``didn't work to (Michelin's) satisfaction.
   ``Historically, Michelin has had very little interst in buying
other people's facilities,'' he said.
   But at least one other industry observer said an acquisition
would be benefit Michelin's in carrying out its strategy in the
United States, giving it a domestic market share almost equal to
that of industry leader Goodyear Tire &amp; Rubber Co.
   ``Francophiles like to be kind of top of the hill, and they see
Goodyear and they know they can't get to be No. 1 by themselves,''
said Arvid Jouppi, analyst with Keane Securities Co. in Grosse
Pointe, Mich.
   Michelin spokesman Jim Morton said Friday he had heard
acquisition rumors for the last day or two, but he said it was
company policy not to comment on rumors or speculation.
   Uniroyal Goodrich became the second-largest tire manufacturer in
North America and fifth-largest in the world when B.F. Goodrich Co.
and Uniroyal Inc. of Middlebury, Conn., merged their tire operations
on Aug. 1, 1986.
   Michelin, which has U.S. headquarters in Greenville, S.C.,
operates eight tire plants in the United States and Canada, while
Uniroyal Goodrich own seven plants in the two countries.
   Analysts estimated a buyout could cost between $700 million and
$1 billion.
   Uniroyal Goodrich had total sales last year of $2.2 billion and
reported profit of $19.2 million, including a one-time gain of $9.3
million from the termination of a pension plan, during the second
quarter ended June 30.
   The company, however, lost $7 million during the first quarter of
this year, after incurring additional interest expense from last
year's restructuring, which wiped out operating profits, the company
said.
   Jouppi said it would be logical for Michelin to acquire Uniroyal
Goodrich because Michelin would win the Ohio firm's market share,
greatly boost its manufacturing capacity and prevent Uniroyal
Goodrich from being bought by another competitor.
   Uniroyal Goodrich declined comment on the prospects of
acquisition by Michelin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
