<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1046EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BigThree-Methanol     09-11 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Big Three-Methanol,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Automotive News: Big Three Agree With Oil Companies to Kill Methanol
Effort</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top executives of the nation's Big Three
automakers have agreed with some oil companies to quash moves which
would require that cars burn methanol instead of gasoline, an
automotive journal reported today.
   Automotive News quoted unidentified sources as saying General
Motors Corp. Chairman Roger Smith and Vice Chairmen Harold Poling of
Ford Motor Co. and Gerald Greenwald of Chrysler Corp. have signed
documents for their companies to work with oil refiners to develop a
reformulated gasoline which would steer them clear of methanol
conversion costs.
   The weekly journal said in the copyright story that killing any
methanol initiatives would save the automakers millions of dollars
in research and development costs, and eliminate competition for oil
companies.
   GM spokesman Bill Noack was in a meeting and not immediately
available for comment this morning.
   Spokesmen Tom Foote of Ford and Tom Houston of Chrysler said
their companies had no immediate reaction to the Automotive News
report.
   It would take the oil industry years to develop and produce
reformulated gasoline which would meet federal clean-air standards,
Automotive News said. Some efforts already are under way.
   Each of the Big Three has an active methanol research program.
Outside engineers also have been studying ways, including new fuels,
to reduce automotive pollution and its effects on the environment.
   President Bush this summer announced a plan that, beginning in
1995, would phase in cars that burn ``clean'' fuels such as methanol
in Connecticut and the cities of Los Angeles, Houston, New York,
Milwaukee, Baltimore, Philadelphia, San Diego and Chicago.
   The Society of Automotive Engineers and GM last spring sponsored
a methanol-fueled car rally in which the automaker supplied a fleet
of Chevrolet Corsicas to 15 colleges and universities. The schools
converted the cars and drove them from Detroit to Washington via
Canada and New England.
   Automotive News said not all of the nation's oil producers are
involved in the reported effort now, but that by a ``summit
meeting'' of top automotive and oil industry executives, tentatively
set for January, most of the major oil refiners will have signed
commitments.
   ``Getting the major auto companies and the gasoline makers
together on the emissions problem is a bit like getting two
elephants to dance,'' Automotive News quoted a Ford fuel engineer as
saying. ``It takes time. Inevitably, toes are going to get stepped
on.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
