<DOCNO> AP890911-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1056EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Dunkin'Donuts     09-11 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dunkin' Donuts,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dunkin' Donuts Rejects DD Acquisition Corp. Offer of $45 Per Share</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANDOLPH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dunkin' Donuts said today that it has
rejected a $45--a-share bid from a Canadian partnership seeking to
take over the company by means of a $308 million merger.
   ``The company believes that the $45 per share in cash offered by
DD Acquisition does not reflect the maximum value achievable for our
stockholders,'' Robert M. Rosenberg, chairman and chief executive
officer said.
   ``We have therefore directed our advisers to explore all
alternatives, including remaining independent or the possible sale
of Dunkin' Donuts, on terms that will realize value for all of our
stockholders in excess of that currently offered by DD
Acquisition,'' he said in a news release.
   DD Acquisition Corp. is a partnership between Cara Operations
Ltd., a restaurant franchise company, and Kingsbridge Capital Group,
the merchant banking arm of Toronto investor George Mann's Unicorp
Canada Corp.
   The Canadians had offered $45 a share for Dunkin' Donuts stock,
contingent on obtaining a majority of the shares and removal of the
company's ``poison pill'' anti-takeover defense. The poison pill
increases the number of shares in the event of a hostile takeover,
which would add a significant amount to a buyer's costs.
</TEXT>
