<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed in Cautious Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were narrowly
mixed in early trading today on the Chicago Board, reflecting
caution ahead of Tuesday's Agriculture Department crop report.
   The report, which is scheduled for release after the markets
close on Tuesday, is widely expected to project smaller corn and
soybean harvests than the USDA predicted in August.
   Forecasts for drier weather in the Midwest late this week and
into the next are weighing slightly on corn and soybean futures.
   And fears of a serious frost this week in the Corn Belt are
rapidly fading, despite prospects for freezing temperatures tonight
in the northern Plains.
   ``Certain sections of Nebraska may come down a little bit but no
large producing areas are supposed to have cold, cold
temperatures,'' said Joel Karlin, a research analyst with Research
Department Inc. in Chicago.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent lower to \ cent higher with
