<TEXT>
   A water pipe break delayed energy futures trading
for more than an hour today on the New York Mercantile Exchange, the
world's largest futures market for crude oil and refined petroleum
products.
   The water pipe break caused an electrical problem that affected
the computers at the exchange, which is in the World Trade Center,
spokesman Robert Baxter said.
   Trading ordinarily begins at 9:45 a.m. EDT and was delayed until
11 a.m. EDT, Baxter said.
