<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Down In Cautious Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
lower Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts for drier
weather in the Midwest and fading fears of an overnight freeze in
important corn and soybean areas.
   Trading activity was light as players evened up their positions
and took to the sidelines ahead of Tuesday's Agriculture Department
crop report.
   The report, scheduled for release after Tuesday's close, is
expected to contain lower corn and soybean crop estimates than the
USDA projected in August.
   Forecasts for drier Midwestern weather later this week and into
next week eased concerns about the possibility of a rain-slowed
harvest.
   And although frost was expected Monday night in Nebraska, few
forecasters expected freezing temperatures to reach into the more
important corn-and-soybean states of Iowa and Illinois.
   At the close, wheat futures were 2{ cents lower to \ cent higher
with the contract for delivery in September at $3.93 a bushel; corn
was 1\ cents lower to { cent higher with September at $2.38\ a
bushel; oats were 1 cent lower to 1{ cents higher with September at
$1.38{ a bushel; soybeans were { cent to 4 cents lower with
September at $6.07 a bushel.
