<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The energy futures market ended mixed in choppy
trading Monday following a sharp runup in prices last week.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the October contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, was
up 1 cent to settle at $19.76 a 42-gallon barrel. The contract had
risen 34 cents on Friday.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange,
wholesale unleaded gasoline for October delivery lost 0.02 cent to
settle at 57.07 cents, after gaining 1.46 cents Friday.
   October heating oil, which rose 1.24 cents at the end of last
week, finished at 56.01 cents, down 0.73 cent.
   ``I think today was just basically a correction day (because) ...
the market had been up sharply on Friday,'' said Andrew Lebow, a
senior trader at E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures Inc.
   He said many traders took profits after prices surged Friday due
to internal market influences and reports suggesting demand for oil
was strong.
   Lebow said concerns of overproduction among members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries put a damper on
Monday's trading.
   ``One has to anticipate higher Iraqi production over the next
couple of months as they utilize their new pipeline,'' he said.
</TEXT>
