<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1922EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AgingAirliners-Incidents     09-11 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aging Airliners-Incidents,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Metal Fatigue Incidents Involve Older Planes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Aging Airliners, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some recent incidents involving metal
fatigue or other problems associated with older airliners that have
had large numbers of landings.
   None of the incidents has involved McDonnell Douglas aircraft,
which are the subject of the latest Federal Aviation Administration
precautionary orders for modifications to increase the safety of
older airliners.
   _Dec. 26, 1988: An Eastern Airlines Boeing 727 built in the late
1960s was forced to land in Charleston, W.Va., after a 14-inch hole
opened in its fuselage at 31,000 feet. There were no injuries among
the 110 people aboard.
   The incident led to fleetwide inspections and discovery of a
3-inch crack in another old Eastern 727.
   _Sept. 21, 1988: An American Airlines 727 made a belly landing at
Dallas-Fort Worth airport after metal fatigue in its landing gear
prevented the pilot from opening the wheel-well door. The 88
passengers and crew evacuated, with three people injured.
   Boeing had recommended inspections eight days earlier after
finding metal fatigue in the same area in other 727s.
   _May 9, 1988: A 20-year-old American Airlines 727 was forced to
make an unscheduled landing at Detroit after a 15-inch crack in a
wheel well caused a drop in cabin pressure. None of the 112 people
aboard was injured.
   _April 28, 1988: A flight attendant was killed and 61 people
injured when a portion fo the fuselage on a heavily flown Aloha
Airlines 737 built in the late 1960s peeled off at 24,000 feet
during a flight from Hilo to Honolulu.
   Tiny cracks were found later in nearly half the aging Boeing 737
jetliners ordered inspected after the incident. The FAA ordered
reriveting of hundreds of older 737s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
