<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1706EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-SovietComputers     09-11 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Computers,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Company to Supply Personal Computers to Soviet Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small American company has been picked to
supply schools in the Soviet Union with personal computers and help
set up Soviet factories to produce PCs, Soviet officials announced
Monday.
   Phoenix Group International of Irvine, Calif., was picked from
among 17 companies worldwide, including ones from West Germany,
France, Austria, Singapore, Malaysia, Canada and the Eastern bloc,
the Soviets said.
   All the computers involved are cleared for export by the U.S.
Department of Commerce.
   Soviet education officials said they hoped a joint venture with
Phoenix would supply 3 million personal computers to schools and
universities and 3 million more to other buyers in the Soviet Union
by 1994.
   Although it is impossible to estimate whether the Soviet sales
projections will be met, Phoenix Chairman Charles W. Missler said,
``It's a very substantial opportunity for us.''
   Phoenix, which broke even on sales of about $10 million in the
past 12 months, is majority-owned by Missler and its vice chairman,
Peter von Braun. Its lightly traded stock rose 25 cents a share to a
bid $4 after jumping $1 a share Friday on early word of the deal.
The late asking price was $5.50 a share.
   Phoenix was picked because it did not insist on being paid
entirely in dollars and was willing to help the Soviets learn the
computer-manufacturing business, said V.V. Krynkin, an official of
the State Committee for Public Education.
   A Phoenix affiliate, Resdel Industries, provided some of the
communications links for the Soyuz-Apollo joint space mission.
   ``A lot of other companies primarily looked at it from the point
of view of business. We're not talking here strictly from the point
of view of buying and selling products,'' Krynkin said through an
interpreter at a New York news conference.
   The new joint venture, Samcom, will start out by shipping kits
from the United States. The plan envisions the Soviets gradually
taking over manufacturing so that in five years, 85 percent of the
work will be done in the Soviet Union.
   The initial system for schools will consist of a network of 10
student workstations, clustered around an instructor's computer and
a ``file server'' computer that will store programs and data.
   The system is new technology that is being announced this week at
a computer networking trade show in Dallas, Missler said.
   Missler said he and von Braun saw the joint venture as a chance
to establish links that could lead to other business deals and
improve relations between the United States and Soviet Union.
   ``Perestroika in the Soviet Union requires that the quality of
Soviet specialists' training must be sharply increased, as well as
the level of education in general,'' Leonid Tereschenko, the deputy
chairman of the State Committee for Public Education, said in a
written statement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
