<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1939EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Trump-WrongRules     09-11 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trump-Wrong Rules,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Suing Trump Castle Because Rules Guide Allegedly Misled Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trump Castle Hotel &amp; Casino did not
intentionally mislead gamblers with incorrect instructions in a
roulette guide that has been distributed since 1986, state gaming
officials said Monday.
   However, Robert Signore, of Ambler, Pa., says he lost $800
because of the faulty guide and has filed a lawsuit in small claims
court to recover the money, according to Monday's editions of The
Philadelphia Inquirer.
   Michael Weber, a spokesman for the casino run by developer Donald
Trump, said Monday the casino would have no comment on the lawsuit.
   State documents show that both the state Division of Gaming
Enforcement and the Casino Control Commission knew as early as
September 1986 that the Trump Castle gaming guide was inaccurate,
the newspaper said.
   The incorrect guides were distributed in 1986, 1987 and part of
1988, said Fred Gushin, deputy attorney general for the Division of
Gaming Enforcement.
   Gushin said Monday that he gave Trump Castle permission to
continue distributing the booklet until the stock was exhausted.
   Signore said he followed that guide after discovering it
contained mistakes. After 22 spins of the roulette wheel, Signore
had lost $600, but should have won $200 according to the guide.
   The DGE questioned why Signore continued to play after he
realized he was losing money, Gushin said.
   ``Why didn't he question it after the first bet?'' Gushin said.
``That seemed a bit curious.''
   Gushin said the error was not intentional and ``didn't appear all
that material.''
   Among the errors was an illustration showing that red paid off on
black and that even numbers paid off on odd numbers.
   Gushin said the casino followed the rules of roulette and that
the gaming guide did not unfairly lure patrons.
</TEXT>
