<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1745EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-BellSouth-LIN Bjt   09-11 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BellSouth-LIN, Bjt,0696</SECOND>
<HEAD>BellSouth, LIN to Merge Cellular Telephone Operations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BellSouth Corp. and LIN Broadcasting Corp. said
Monday they were merging their cellular telephone operations to
become a ``powerhouse'' company with a half-million customers and
dominance in some of the industry's top markets.
   ``They certainly will be a very big cellular company,'' said
Kevin Kelley, a spokesman for the Washington-based Cellular
Telecommunications Industry Association. ``It looks like they could
be the largest.''
   The non-cash deal announced by the two companies comes just a few
months after New York-based LIN rejected an unsolicited $5.85
billion buyout offer from McCaw Cellular Communications Inc., the
current No. 1 in potential customers. LIN rejected that offer,
demanding at least $6.22 billion.
   The merger, subject to the approval of LIN stockholders and
regulatory agencies, would give Atlanta-based BellSouth 50 percent
of the stock of the combined company. Before the completion of the
merger, New York-based LIN will spin off its television broadcasting
subsidiaries to stockholders and will pay each shareholder a $20 per
share special dividend.
   LIN currently operates in fewer markets than does BellSouth, but
LIN does business in five of the top 10 cellular phone markets. The
industry operates under a ``duopolistic'' system that allows only
two companies in each market, one of which is the local phone
company.
   The merger will give Atlanta-based BellSouth entry to the
lucrative New York, Philadelphia and Dallas markets and will
increase its presence in Los Angeles and Houston, where it already
had a joint operating arrangement with LIN.
   Those five cities all are among the nation's top 10 markets for
cellular telephone service.
   Overall, the new company, yet to be named, will start with about
500,000 customers in 43 markets.
   BellSouth, a ``Baby Bell'' company, had 1988 revenues of $13.7
billion and net income of $1.7 billion. LIN had $225 million in
revenues and earnings of $82 million, though company officials say
the rapid growth of LIN makes the company worth more than its
earnings figures might indicate.
   ``This new company clearly will be the powerhouse of the cellular
industry,'' said BellSouth Enterprises President William O. McCoy.
   Kenneth Leon, a cellular industry analyst at Bear, Stearns &amp; Co.
in New York, said the BellSouth package is worth about $105 a share
to LIN shareholders.
   The McCaw offer was worth $120 a share, but Leon suggested the
BellSouth deal may be more desirable to LIN shareholders because it
keeps them involved in cellular instead of just giving them cash.
   McCaw owns 10 percent of LIN, and its offer for the rest of LIN
is still is on the table, McCaw spokesman Steve Bruce said. He said
he could not comment on the BellSouth-LIN deal because it has not
yet been filed with federal regulators, and McCaw has not seen the
official merger proposal.
   Bruce Barnes of Wasserstein, Perella &amp; Co., LIN's financial
advisers, said the deal with BellSouth was attractive in ways that
the McCaw offer was not.
   ``What the other offer involved was someone buying the company
out for an amount of cash that the board felt was inadequate,'' he
said. ``In this, we have increased the value of our own stock and
will be able to participate in the upside of the cellular business.''
   Barnes said BellSouth provides LIN with new markets, technical
expertise and marketing know-how. And LIN offers BellSouth ``a
management team very good at making the cellular business
profitable.''
   LIN Chairman Donald A. Pels will become chairman, president and
chief executive officer of the combined company, which has not been
named. Earle Mauldin, group president for mobile systems at
BellSouth Enterprises, will be executive vice president and chief
operating officer.
   The combined company will serve markets totaling 62 million in
population. However, since they will not have full ownership in
cellular companies in each of the markets, its prorated potential
customer base would be 46 million. That leaves it behind McCaw's 52
million prorated potential customers. BellSouth currently ranks
third and LIN seventh in the industry measure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
