<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-11 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed mostly lower amid profit-taking
on domestic markets Monday after rising in overseas trading.
   Gold prices edged lower.
   Analysts said the dollar's upward momentum was slowed by
increases in market interest rates in other countries, including
West Germany, and U.S. traders, fearing the dollar would decline in
response to those developments, rushed to take profits.
   ``Interest rate differentials begin to work against the dollar at
this level,'' said Ronald Holzer, chief dealer, Harris Trust &amp; Co.
in Chicago.
   However, Holzer said the dollar still had a firm undertone.
   In earlier overseas trading, the dollar rose, but dealers said
three upcoming economic reports from Washington have made traders
reluctant to push the U.S. currency much higher.
   The Commerce Department's August retail sales figures will be
announced Thursday, and on Friday, reports are due on the July trade
deficit figures and August producer prices.
   ``Anyone buying dollars at this stage, ahead of the numbers later
this week is taking a big risk,'' said a U.S. investment bank dealer
in London.
   The financial markets are concerned that the Federal Reserve
might change its monetary policy in response to the reports, which
will give an indication of the economy's health. If the economy is
strong, the Fed would be expected to keep credit tight _ a move
dollar investors would prefer.
   The dollar fell against the British pound in New York. It cost
$1.5460 to buy one British pound, compared with $1.5380 on Friday.
In London earlier, a pound cost $1.5450, cheaper than $1.5505 late
Friday.
   Other late rates for the dollar in New York, compared with
Friday's prices, included: 1.9865 West German marks, down from
1.9950; 1.7135 Swiss francs, down from 1.7245; 6.6910 French francs,
down from 6.7195; 1,425.875 Italian lire, up from 1,421.00; and
1.18715 Canadian dollars, down from 1.18745.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.9875 West German marks, up from 1.9795; 1.7150
Swiss francs, up from 1.7080; 6.6970 French francs, up from 6.6710;
2.2425 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2320; 1,424.75 Italian lire, up
1,421.70; and 1.1873 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1877.
   In Tokyo, where the dollar began its trading day, the dollar rose
1.15 yen to a closing 147.77 yen from Friday's 146.62 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at a lower rate of 147.65 yen, and in New
York, it fell to 146.70 yen from late Friday's 147.20 yen.
   Gold prices slipped in all major markets.
   Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late bid of $358.10 a
troy ounce for gold, down from $359.40 on Friday, and on the
Commodity Exchange in New York, gold slipped to $359.20 an ounce
from $359.40 on Friday.
   Gold fell earlier in London to a late bid price of $358.75 a troy
ounce, compared with late Friday's $360.00.
   In Hong Kong, gold fell 21 cents to close at a bid $358.90.
   The Zurich markets were closed for a holiday.
   Silver bullion prices also fell.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, silver closed at $5.051 a
troy ounce, slightly lower than late Friday's $5.053. On the London
market, silver traded at a late bid price of $5.08 a troy ounce,
down from Friday's $5.12.
</TEXT>
