<DOCNO> AP890911-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1805EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OptionsFraudCharges     09-11 0762</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Options Fraud Charges,0786</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commodity Option Firms Accused of Fraud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators sued two commodity options
firms Monday, charging they misled customers on investment risks
that ran up millions of dollars in losses over five years while the
firms took hefty sales commissions.
   Siegel Trading Company Inc., based in Chicago, and International
Trading Group Ltd., with headquarters in San Mateo, Calif., were
sued separately by the Commodity Futures Trading Commission at
federal court for the central district of California.
   ``This is probably the largest anti-fraud sales solicitation case
the CFTC has ever brought,'' said Dennis Klejna, director of the
commission's enforcement division.
   A spokesman for Chicago-based Siegel was not in his office when
called for comment and did not immediately return a reporter's phone
call.
   In San Mateo, Calif., ITG issued a statement that said it was
reviewing the charges but intended to defend against them
vigorously, adding ``ITG sales practices comply with applicable law
and regulation, do not mislead potential or actual customers and are
proper in all respects.''
   ITG also said it ``is not connected in any way`` with Siegel.
   Options are contracts that give their owners the right to conduct
a specified transaction, such as buying or selling a certain number
of shares of a given common stock, at a set price within a stated
period of time _ usually just a few months.
   Options can be highly risky and since they are usually short-term
investment vehicles, they involve a lot of buying and selling, for
which commissions must be paid each time.
   In the International Trading Group (ITG) case, the CFTC stated
that between Jan. 1, 1984 and May 31 this year, more than 85 percent
of the firm's customers lost a total of $428 million _ $283 million
of it in commissions collected by ITG.
   ``ITG collects a 40 percent commission premium on the options
themselves,''said Klejna, who said other firms charge
``substantially less.''
   Explaining the long lag time between when the alleged illegal
activity began and the filing of civil charges, Klejna denied it had
anything to do with recent congressional criticism of the CFTC,
which is up for reauthorization later this month.
   ``It has everything to do with the fact that we've looking at
these things for a long time,'' said Klejna adding that it ``takes a
long time'' to investigate and file charges in such cases.
   ITG also maintained offices in San Francisco, Foster City,
Newport Beach and San Diego, Calif., Honolulu and in Coconut Grove,
Fla.
   In the other case, officials said Siegel also charged 45 percent
commission plus $155 for each trade. From Jan. 1, 1984 until the
present, according to the complaint, about 85 percent of the firm's
customers lost money, totaling $33.6 million. For the same period,
the firm took in $40 million in commissions.
   The CFTC charged that ITG fraudulently misrepresented and omitted
important facts when it sold dealer and exchange-traded options to
customers through mass mailings of promotional materials, nationwide
advertising and high pressure phone sales, among other sales tactics.
   The complaint alleged that ITG misled customers about the risks
involved and the returns to be expected in the commodity options
market; the experience and expertise of its sales force and the
skills of its research department.
   Officials also charged that the firm claimed it had ``an
outstanding track record,'' which the CFTC maintains is not borne
out by the performance of ITG customers' accounts.
   ITG also failed to diligently supervise its employees while
encouraging ``boiler-room'' type tactics of unsolicited,
high-pressure telephone sales pitches, the CFTC charged.
   In the other case, the CFTC charged that Siegel, which employs 80
people at offices in Los Angeles and Irvine, Calif., directed each
sales person to make up to 100 telephone sales solicitations a day.
   More than 7,000 customer accounts were opened with Siegel and
customers were falsely told they would earn ``fabulous profits''
trading commodity options with the firm without being told the
actual risk, according to the complaint.
   The complaint also stated that Siegel also solicited customers
through a 15-minute commodities television program broadcast
transmitted on cable television every business day. The name of the
program was not given in the complaint and Klejna declined to
discuss it.
   Both lawsuits seek preliminary injunctions barring the firms from
continuing their alleged illegal practices. Klejna said the CFTC
also would seek to have the firms return all profits made through
illegal practices.
   Klejna would not comment on whether evidence from the civil cases
had been turned over to federal prosecutors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890911-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 1812EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-11 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0736</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Climb In Whipsaw Session</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices rose sharply Monday on New York's Commodity
Exchange in a volatile session that saw the price for December
delivery whipsawed over a range of more than 6 cents a pound.
   On other markets, precious metals futures fell, energy futures
were mixed, grains and soybeans were mixed, and livestock and meat
futures were mixed.
   Copper futures settled 3 cents to 3.1 cents higher with the
contract for September delivery at $1.303 a pound. The more actively
traded December contract settled at $1.256 after trading between
$1.19 and $1.257 a pound.
   Prices nosedived at the opening in reaction to the London Metal
Exchange's report that copper stocks in the exchange-approved
warehouse had risen last week by 4,800 metric tons, an unexpectedly
large increase.
   The big buildup in LME stocks appeared to contradict the
tight-supply fears that have provided the main support for copper's
price during the past 1{ months.
   But the market bottomed out quickly, rallied steadily and ended
with a strong burst of buying by some of the same speculative funds
that had sold the market earlier in the day.
   ``The decline was probably excessive,'' said Bette Raptopoulos,
metals analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   Analysts could not agree on a reason for the turnaround. William
O'Neill, director of research with Elders Futures Inc., cited strong
buying by the Japanese, who have been hit hard by the two-month
shutdown of the Bouganville copper mine in Papua New Guinea.
   Continued violence in that area on Monday reinforced predictions
that production at Bouganville will not resume this year.
   Meanwhile, a 9-week-old old strike at a Highland Valley Copper
Co. mine in British Colombia continued Monday, and a strike at the
Chilean Copper Co.'s El Salvador mine entered a second week after
workers there voted against a settlement offer.
   O'Neill said copper's fundamentals were still supportive despite
the market's retreat from about $1.37 a pound, a decline of about 5
percent, in the past two weeks.
   ``We are dealing with a market that has a bullish supply-demand
equation,'' he said. ``I think the market's healthier after this
type of correction.''
   Precious-metals futures slipped lower on the Comex. Gold settled
20 cents to 50 cents lower with October at $360.90 a troy ounce;
silver was 0.2 cent to 0.8 cent lower with September at $5.051 a
troy ounce.
   Energy futures ended mixed in choppy trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange following a sharp rally last week.
   Andrew Lebow, a senior trader with E.D.&amp; F. Man International
Futures, said concerns of overproduction among members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries put a damper on
Monday's trading.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 1 cent higher to 7
cents lower with October at $19.76 a barrel; heating oil was .48
cent to .73 cent lower with October at 56.01 cents a gallon; and
unleaded gasoline was .02 cent to .70 cent lower with October at
57.07 cents a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures prices finished mostly lower on the
Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts for drier weather in the
Midwest and fading fears of an overnight freeze in important corn
and soybean areas.
   Trading activity was light as players evened up their positions
and took to the sidelines ahead of Tuesday's Agriculture Department
crop report, which is expected to project smaller corn and soybean
crops than the USDA's August report.
   Wheat settled 2{ cents lower to { cent higher with September at
$3.93 a bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to { cent higher with
September at $2.38{ a bushel; oats were 1 cent lower to \ cents
higher with September at $1.38\ a bushel; soybeans were { cent to 3{
cents lower with September at $6.07 a bushel.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live cattle futures settled
.20 cent lower to .33 cent higher with October at 71.67 cents a
pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .12 cent higher with
September at 82.27 cents a pound; live hogs were .57 cent lower to
.35 cent higher with October at 38.75 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .05 cent lower to .27 cent higher with February at
46.17 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
