<FIRST>r f BC-Shuwa-London     09-11 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Shuwa-London,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Subsidiary, Big in U.S. Real Estate, Moves Into London</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A subsidiary of Japan's Shuwa Corp. that owns
a string of landmark U.S. office buildings including Los Angeles'
Arco Towers said Monday it was getting into European real estate
with a 250-year lease on Ashdown House in London.
   Shuwa Investments Corp., a Los Angeles-based real estate
investment and development firm, said it would form a joint venture
with Tishman West Cos., a Los Angeles commercial real estate
company, to complete the deal.
   The partnership, Tishman Shuwa Victoria Partners, will pay the
Church Commissioners for England and Shell Pensions Trust Ltd. 100
million British pounds, about $154 million, for the
195,000-square-foot project in Victoria, a prime London office and
retail district near Buckingham Palace and Westminster Cathedral.
   ``Shuwa Investments is ready to fulfill the third link of the
company's corporate strategy,'' said Takaji Kobayashi, president of
the Los Angeles-based subsidiary.
   ``More than 10 years ago, Shuwa successfully expanded operations
from Asia to the United States,'' Kobayashi said. ``This joint
venture positions the company for further acquisitions of commercial
properties in England and other European countries.''
   Kobayashi's father, Shigeru Kobayashi, has become one of the
world's richest men through his giant real estate company,
Tokyo-based Shuwa Corp.
   He bought the Arco Plaza complex for $620 million in 1985 in Los
Angeles. About that time he also paid $165 million for the former
ABC building in Manhattan.
   Shuwa now owns 35 major U.S. office buildings, including the U.S.
News &amp; World Report Building in Washington, Quaker Tower in Boston
and the Paine Webber Building in Boston.
   Ashdown House is 11 stories high with stepped pyramid elevations
and bronze-tinted reflective windows. Completed in 1975, it is 100
percent occupied by government offices and retail shops, according
to a joint press release from Shuwa and Tishman West.
   Tishman West already has a property management operation in
London, but this will be the first building it owns.
   ``This joint venture partnership will position Tishman West to
actively acquire other London properties,'' said Perry S. Herst Jr.,
Tishman chairman and chief executive. ``We also plan to continue
seeking high-quality joint ventures on the Continent.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
