<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 2009EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-FNN     09-11 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-FNN,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profit Falls to $3 Million in Fiscal Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financial News Network Inc. reported Monday that
earnings dropped to about $3 million in its latest fiscal year from
$4.7 million in the comparable year-earlier period, mainly due to
higher programming costs.
   The cable television network said earnings per share were 17
cents in the fiscal year ended June 30, compared with 30 cents in
the ten-month period ended June 30, 1988.
   FNN said it was required under financial reporting requirements
to compare its latest fiscal year with the earlier ten-month period
since that was the first full period of its new fiscal year.
   The company had changed its fiscal year to run through Aug. 31
from the earlier date of June 30.
   FNN attributed the decline in earnings mainly to increased costs
stemming from new prime-time business programming.
   Revenue rose to $44 million in the latest fiscal year from $32
million in the ten-month period. The year-earlier figure reflects
the discontinuation of TelShop, a TV home shopping service.
   ``FNN succeeded in securing its niche as the brand name, cable
television source of business and financial news,'' FNN Executive
Vice President C. Steven Bolen said in a statement. ``FNN faced
certain competitive market forces this past year, and succeeded in
maintaining, and, in fact, improving its position.''
   FNN currently provides business, financial and sports information
to around 32 million homes in the United States that subscribe to it.
</TEXT>
