<FILEID>AP-NR-09-11-89 2011EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-VideoPoker     09-11 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Video Poker,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Leading Gaming Device Makers Reach Tentative Accord in Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the nation's leading gaming device
makers avoided a federal court battle after reaching a tentative
accord Monday in a copyright dispute over a video poker machine.
   International Gaming Technology agreed not to pursue a copyright
and trade infringement lawsuit against Japanese-owned Universal Co.
Ltd., if its Nevada-based distributing company promises not to sell
video poker machines that IGT claimed were copies of its ``Player's
Edge'' machine.
   Under the stipulation, IGT has until next Monday to amend its
lawsuit to continue the dispute if, after examining Universal's
redesigned video poker machine, it decides Universal's new machine
does duplicate IGT's ``Player's Edge'' game.
   Donald Lattin, attorney for Universal Co., said he doesn't
believe IGT will pursue the lawsuit because ``Universal's video
poker machine is substantially different than IGT's.''
   ``All of the video poker machines look basically alike on the
outside,'' Lattin said. ``It's like buying a refrigerator. There're
lots of different brands, but they look the same.''
   Lattin said the inner components of Universal's video poker
machine are very different from IGT's and Universal never let IGT
officials examine the inside of the machine during the dispute.
   Larry Semenza, the Reno attorney for Nevada-based IGT refused to
comment on the lawsuit, saying the parties had agreed not to talk to
reporters about the dispute in what is a highly lucrative and
growing market.
   ``There was a stipulation entered into,'' said Semenza, making
his only comment about the document filed Monday in U.S. District
Court.
   The hearing before Judge Bruce Thompson was scheduled to
determine whether to grant IGT's motion for a preliminary injunction
to prevent Universal from distributing the disputed video poker
machine.
   Earlier this summer, Thompson handed IGT an early victory in the
dispute, issuing a temporary restraining order to prevent Universal
from distributing its disputed video poker machine.
   IGT attorneys said the company's ``Player's Edge'' machine was
displayed during a February 1988 trade show and must have been
copied by Universal workers who viewed the device.
   IGT, now the No. 1 gaming device manufacturer in the nation, and
Universal are battling along with Bally's Manufacturing for a bigger
piece of the gambling market.
   Lattin said the gaming device market has become very competitive
because of rapidly changing computer and electronic technologies
that make gaming devices almost obsolete within a couple of years
after introduction.
   Under the stipulation between the companies, if IGT doesn't
object to the design of Universal's latest video poker machine, the
Japanese company can approach gaming authorities for approval to
distribute the device.
   IGT and Universal have been involved in other disputes, including
one last year in which IGT complained to Nevada gaming regulators
about a ``near miss'' slot maching Universal was distributing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
